00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:43.600
[Amit Varma]: Lovely to be here, Amit.

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:47.440
[Amit Varma]: So you know, you know, before we start talking about your book or about your music or about

00:03:47.440 --> 00:03:52.640
[Amit Varma]: your politics, let's kind of go back to how you started as a musician, like you were a

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:54.040
[Amit Varma]: bit of a child prodigy, weren't you?

00:03:54.040 --> 00:03:56.040
[Amit Varma]: I like the word prodigy.

00:03:56.040 --> 00:04:04.000
[Guest]: So, you know, my home was a home of Carnatic music, definitely, of Bharatanatyam, all these

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:05.400
[Guest]: arts.

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:06.760
[Guest]: But we are a business family.

00:04:06.760 --> 00:04:08.920
[Guest]: My dad was a business person.

00:04:08.920 --> 00:04:14.000
[Guest]: So we're not a family of musicians like we usually hear about in India.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.360
[Guest]: But at the age of four or five, apparently I showed some talent, I used to hum the tunes

00:04:18.360 --> 00:04:19.880
[Guest]: my mother used to sing.

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:25.160
[Guest]: My mother herself was a trained vocalist, not on the professional stage, but she was

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:26.520
[Guest]: formally trained.

00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:30.080
[Guest]: She did a graduation in music, actually, a post graduation in English.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:36.280
[Guest]: So so what happened was, I mean, I started singing when I was about five or six, formally.

00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:38.760
[Guest]: I never wanted to be a musician.

00:04:38.760 --> 00:04:43.680
[Guest]: You know, I grew up playing cricket on the streets, hated the music class thrice a week.

00:04:43.680 --> 00:04:49.600
[Guest]: Me, I'm a left hand batsman, I'm very proud of the fact that I'm a left hand batsman.

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:52.800
[Guest]: So presumed that I'm naturally elegant, basically.

00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:54.800
[Guest]: So so I loved it.

00:04:54.800 --> 00:04:55.800
[Guest]: I used to love to sing.

00:04:55.800 --> 00:04:57.280
[Guest]: There's one thing I never felt any inhibition.

00:04:57.280 --> 00:05:01.040
[Guest]: I know that you go to anybody's home and they say sing a song, I would just belt it out.

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:04.960
[Guest]: So that was one thing I was I was quite fearless about singing.

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:06.240
[Guest]: But I never thought I'd be a musician.

00:05:06.240 --> 00:05:11.720
[Guest]: You know, I got to school, 10th grader, I was economics, I want to be an economist.

00:05:11.720 --> 00:05:13.240
[Guest]: And that was my big dream.

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:16.240
[Amit Varma]: My God, you could have been on the show talking about something else entirely.

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:19.240
[Guest]: How horrible the show would have been.

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:24.360
[Guest]: So I must tell you what Amartya Sen told me when I told him, he said, thank God.

00:05:24.360 --> 00:05:27.000
[Guest]: He feared the competition would go down.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.880
[Guest]: I couldn't have tolerated another economist in the world, probably.

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:31.760
[Guest]: But you know, I want to be an economist.

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:37.600
[Guest]: And I had this whole plan in my head, you know, Delhi School, LSE, as if they're going

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:39.240
[Guest]: to call me and invite me.

00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:40.840
[Guest]: But anyway.

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:45.440
[Guest]: But I started performing when I was about 12, my first concert was when I was 12.

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:48.560
[Guest]: And you know, people thought I was talented.

00:05:48.560 --> 00:05:53.040
[Guest]: And yes, he has a bright big voice, young guy sings without any fear.

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:54.040
[Guest]: All that was there.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:56.160
[Guest]: And I was within the world of Carnatic music.

00:05:56.160 --> 00:06:00.680
[Guest]: And I was within the power structures, my, you know, my uncle was the president of the

00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:04.120
[Guest]: Music Academy in Chennai, which is like one of the premier institutions.

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:07.040
[Guest]: And you descended from T.D. Krishnamachari, you actually started the academy.

00:06:07.040 --> 00:06:10.380
[Guest]: Yes, T.D. Krishnamachari is one of the founders, and he is my grand uncle.

00:06:10.380 --> 00:06:15.000
[Guest]: So yeah, so I come from within the power structures of high art, whatever that is.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.760
[Guest]: And therefore, even so, then I started taking it more seriously.

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:24.160
[Guest]: And I think it was about 92, 91, when I had a series of concerts, and I remember a lot

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:27.080
[Guest]: of senior musicians and colleagues, young people coming and telling me, you should take

00:06:27.080 --> 00:06:29.040
[Guest]: this seriously, what are you doing?

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:31.720
[Guest]: That's when it struck me that, okay, maybe this is something I should be doing.

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:32.720
[Amit Varma]: And you're like 15, 16.

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:35.400
[Guest]: Yeah, I'm just getting into college.

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:41.000
[Guest]: And when I went into college, my undergrads in economics, of course, and by the second

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.200
[Guest]: year, I was singing concerts a bit here and there.

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:47.400
[Guest]: And people said, okay, there's this kid who can, you know, sing, I had to make a choice

00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:50.080
[Guest]: whether it's music or whether it is economics.

00:06:50.080 --> 00:06:54.480
[Guest]: And, you know, I come from all the privileges in the world, I looked, I went to my dad and

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:58.000
[Guest]: said, I want, he said, do what you want, and I'll support you.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.960
[Guest]: That's when I took the plunge to become a singer.

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:05.760
[Guest]: And then things just kind of rolled, opportunities came by.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:10.680
[Guest]: There was this association formed in 1985 called Youth Association for Classical Music.

00:07:10.680 --> 00:07:16.200
[Guest]: It's very interesting that young people who are interested in Carnatic music formed this

00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:20.600
[Guest]: organization because in the 80s, there was this whole thing that Carnatic music is dying.

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:21.760
[Guest]: It's all old people stuff.

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:24.760
[Guest]: There are no young people singing, no young people listening.

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:25.760
[Guest]: What do we do?

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:28.040
[Guest]: The truth of the way young people who are willing to sing, they never got opportunities.

00:07:28.040 --> 00:07:32.120
[Guest]: You know, in India, the grayer you get, the more intelligent you're presumed or more talented

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:33.120
[Guest]: you're presumed.

00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:36.320
[Guest]: And so these guys did something quite remarkable for its time.

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:39.480
[Guest]: They said, you know what, we will organize concerts only for young people below the age

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:40.480
[Guest]: of 30.

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:41.480
[Guest]: Wow.

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:43.920
[Guest]: And those were days when there were no sponsorships.

00:07:43.920 --> 00:07:48.200
[Guest]: So for the first time, they went to corporates and got like 500 rupees, 1000.

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:50.280
[Guest]: So I became a member there later.

00:07:50.280 --> 00:07:51.720
[Guest]: And then all that.

00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:55.200
[Guest]: So we had a community where you could talk about a raga and a thala, which is not a cool

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:57.120
[Guest]: thing to do in school, right?

00:07:57.120 --> 00:08:03.280
[Guest]: But I think all that was part of growing up for me and my interest in jamming with people,

00:08:03.280 --> 00:08:04.280
[Guest]: you know.

00:08:04.280 --> 00:08:05.720
[Amit Varma]: So there's a lot of fun, I must say.

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:08.440
[Amit Varma]: And there seem to be have been two other journeys you've been on.

00:08:08.440 --> 00:08:12.440
[Amit Varma]: One, of course, as a scholar, where you've all studied the history of the music and kind

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:15.840
[Amit Varma]: of looked at all of that, a scholar-cum-historian, so to say.

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:17.800
[Amit Varma]: And two, of course, there's politics.

00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:19.800
[Amit Varma]: How did these two sort of evolve?

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:24.400
[Amit Varma]: Like, initially, like, you know, you said you were going to be an economist and then,

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:27.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, you decided that, fine, these concerts are being received well.

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:31.240
[Amit Varma]: So was it partly that the concerts are being received well, or did you just love the music

00:08:31.240 --> 00:08:34.160
[Amit Varma]: enough to say, this is what I want to do and nothing else?

00:08:34.160 --> 00:08:35.160
[Amit Varma]: Come on, it's both.

00:08:35.160 --> 00:08:36.160
[Amit Varma]: It's a bit of both.

00:08:36.160 --> 00:08:38.360
[Amit Varma]: Of course, you love the stage.

00:08:38.360 --> 00:08:39.560
[Amit Varma]: You love the applause.

00:08:39.560 --> 00:08:43.920
[Amit Varma]: And when is the tendency towards, A, the scholarship, figuring out what the history of this is and

00:08:43.920 --> 00:08:47.040
[Amit Varma]: figuring out what is behind all of this come from?

00:08:47.040 --> 00:08:49.440
[Amit Varma]: And B, is that what then led to the politics?

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:55.840
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, most of this is like, post facto kind of understanding how the movement took

00:08:55.840 --> 00:08:56.840
[Guest]: place.

00:08:56.840 --> 00:09:00.200
[Guest]: Because honestly, I think many of these moments just take place, and you're in the flow of

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:01.200
[Guest]: it.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:02.760
[Guest]: And it's, I don't believe it's ever a moment.

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:06.200
[Guest]: I think the moment we talk about is a moment when you realize it.

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:08.360
[Guest]: It's already happening in its background.

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:12.480
[Guest]: So I think it's, it starts with my home and my school.

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:17.640
[Guest]: In terms of how I grew up in, at home and school, there was nothing that was taboo.

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:20.280
[Guest]: You could talk about anything, you could ask any question.

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:25.080
[Guest]: And so there was this definitely Catholicity at home and open speaking.

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:32.320
[Guest]: My school was a school that came from J. Krishnamurti's philosophy, where it was about asking questions.

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:34.240
[Guest]: So you know, even the notion of how does one ask a question?

00:09:34.240 --> 00:09:35.240
[Guest]: What is the question?

00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:38.000
[Guest]: You know, those are things discussed in school, you know.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:44.800
[Guest]: So I think that plays, these two places play a very important role in what happened to

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:50.640
[Guest]: me later, because they kept me open, they kept me in check.

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:56.400
[Guest]: And see, once I started performing, and opportunities came by, I mean, it's a drug.

00:09:56.400 --> 00:09:58.000
[Guest]: It's like being high always.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:02.040
[Guest]: I mean, when somebody comes, you know, whether you're young or, you know, someone says that

00:10:02.040 --> 00:10:05.360
[Guest]: you're like incredible, I mean, you have incredible talent.

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:08.840
[Guest]: And they keep telling you that you just love it, you love the audience.

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:11.680
[Guest]: In fact, if the applause is not enough, it bothers you.

00:10:11.680 --> 00:10:14.560
[Guest]: And then as a musician, you will do something to get that thunderous applause.

00:10:14.560 --> 00:10:18.640
[Guest]: And I always tell my students, you know, when do you really practice, for example, you know,

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:21.640
[Guest]: we say sadhana and all that, riyaz, whatever.

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:25.080
[Guest]: The truth is most of the times when we are practicing at home, we hear the applause.

00:10:25.080 --> 00:10:26.080
[Guest]: Really?

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:27.320
[Guest]: Yeah, of course.

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:32.920
[Guest]: So it's fascinating how it works, like you're singing at home, and you finished a phrase,

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:37.480
[Guest]: and you can actually hear it in your head, because you're dreaming of it the next day

00:10:37.480 --> 00:10:39.440
[Guest]: on stage.

00:10:39.440 --> 00:10:42.840
[Guest]: So can you cut yourself off that and actually really practice?

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:46.200
[Guest]: These are all very interesting challenges that I think artists go through.

00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:52.560
[Guest]: And so I went through this, I was extremely ambitious guy who just want to be at the top.

00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:55.840
[Guest]: My wife will vouch for my ambitiousness and my cutthroatness.

00:10:55.840 --> 00:11:02.560
[Guest]: So I want to say this, because it's not like, you know, I've always been like this and asking

00:11:02.560 --> 00:11:03.560
[Guest]: these questions.

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:08.460
[Guest]: No, I've had this whole right where I just didn't care a shit, that's the truth.

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:15.200
[Guest]: But I think what happened after a while is I kind of figured out how to be successful

00:11:15.200 --> 00:11:16.200
[Guest]: as an artist.

00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:20.080
[Guest]: And that's can be a good feeling and a bad feeling.

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:24.000
[Guest]: The good feeling is because you can then belt out successful concerts, you know what you

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:29.440
[Guest]: need to add to your repertoire, add to your skill set to keep moving ahead.

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:33.480
[Guest]: But then I think something happened missing, is this all this is about?

00:11:33.480 --> 00:11:36.120
[Guest]: You know, is this all music is about?

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:39.960
[Guest]: I mean, is it just the fact that I can please X number of people, I know how to please them

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:42.280
[Guest]: again and again and again, I'm going to do this all my life.

00:11:42.280 --> 00:11:44.040
[Guest]: So I loved it.

00:11:44.040 --> 00:11:47.200
[Guest]: But that question did come up in my head.

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:49.900
[Guest]: And I think that's when I started diving into history.

00:11:49.900 --> 00:11:53.760
[Guest]: So you know, even questions like, you know, what was music like 100 years ago?

00:11:53.760 --> 00:11:55.400
[Guest]: What was it like 150 years ago?

00:11:55.400 --> 00:11:57.000
[Guest]: Was it different?

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.680
[Guest]: And once I started doing that, and I did some research and we did some archival work, I

00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:02.680
[Guest]: was in for a shock.

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:03.680
[Guest]: And around what time?

00:12:03.680 --> 00:12:08.160
[Guest]: It was about 2002, 2003.

00:12:08.160 --> 00:12:09.160
[Guest]: Around that period of time.

00:12:09.160 --> 00:12:12.440
[Amit Varma]: So you're about 26, 27 at this time.

00:12:12.440 --> 00:12:16.280
[Guest]: And then we started doing this research and this archival work and this reading up, I

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:17.880
[Guest]: started reading treatises.

00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:22.280
[Guest]: I started bothering scholars with questions on Sanskrit on what does this word mean in

00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:26.360
[Guest]: this in Natya Shastra, it's in Brihadeshi, what does this mean in Matanga, I said this,

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:28.440
[Guest]: you know, all these crazy things.

00:12:28.440 --> 00:12:34.200
[Guest]: And I spent a lot of time trying to understand it with my limited abilities.

00:12:34.200 --> 00:12:35.200
[Guest]: I did.

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:37.760
[Guest]: I think that's when a lot of things hit me, you know, about history, about everything

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:42.640
[Guest]: being old, that we are somewhere continuing something that was preciously given to us

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:44.160
[Guest]: 2000 years ago.

00:12:44.160 --> 00:12:48.280
[Guest]: All these things became question marks for me, first musically, had nothing to do with

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:51.560
[Guest]: society or politics, just aesthetically.

00:12:51.560 --> 00:12:55.360
[Guest]: So what is this I'm carrying forward, you know, Amit, you know, I believe I'm a carrier

00:12:55.360 --> 00:12:56.360
[Guest]: of Indian culture.

00:12:56.360 --> 00:13:01.000
[Guest]: You know, especially if you're in the classical world, you believe somehow you represent this

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:02.960
[Guest]: incredible idea of India.

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:06.680
[Guest]: And this has been sold by us to the world over for the last 70 odd years.

00:13:06.680 --> 00:13:08.960
[Guest]: So what am I really selling?

00:13:08.960 --> 00:13:13.680
[Guest]: You are selling something, let's be very brutally honest, this is not some pristine thing that

00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:15.560
[Guest]: you're putting, you're selling it.

00:13:15.560 --> 00:13:17.720
[Guest]: So what am I selling?

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:19.840
[Guest]: Do I mean, and I believe it.

00:13:19.840 --> 00:13:21.160
[Guest]: So what am I holding on to?

00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:25.640
[Guest]: What are these notions of this antiquity, the sense of purity, sense of something that's

00:13:25.640 --> 00:13:31.520
[Guest]: unchanged, that, you know, people just handed over like this precious ceramic piece of art

00:13:31.520 --> 00:13:34.040
[Guest]: that you can't even crack or modify.

00:13:34.040 --> 00:13:38.200
[Guest]: So all these questions started appearing and then some of the things that I thought that

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:43.320
[Guest]: music was like, I thought today if somebody sang like that, it would sound horrible.

00:13:43.320 --> 00:13:46.440
[Guest]: So I'm like, so what is beautiful?

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:53.040
[Guest]: You know, we look at certain colors, certain designs, and we say, that's Indian beauty.

00:13:53.040 --> 00:13:54.280
[Guest]: But what is that?

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:55.560
[Guest]: What construction is that?

00:13:55.560 --> 00:14:00.360
[Guest]: So I think all this started, the moment this started, within a few years, and I can tell

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:03.560
[Guest]: you that I never wrote a book for a long time.

00:14:03.560 --> 00:14:07.840
[Guest]: You know, I was just doing this because I have an OCD, I get obsessive on something,

00:14:07.840 --> 00:14:08.840
[Guest]: I'll just keep doing it.

00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:09.840
[Guest]: So I just kept doing it.

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:14.840
[Guest]: And I was not doing a PhD or anything, I was just doing it because I was just fascinated

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:19.200
[Guest]: by what was happening to me and to my understanding and learning.

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:22.680
[Amit Varma]: And did it sort of help that this is also the time when the internet is taking off,

00:14:22.680 --> 00:14:25.160
[Amit Varma]: so you have a lot of sources online or you didn't have so many then?

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:28.480
[Guest]: I, well, early 2000, not so much.

00:14:28.480 --> 00:14:30.360
[Guest]: But I think through the years, it did help.

00:14:30.360 --> 00:14:33.360
[Guest]: But a lot of my sources then were actually the texts and actually scholars, I used to

00:14:33.360 --> 00:14:36.240
[Guest]: go call them at 10 o'clock in the night, spend one hour talking to them.

00:14:36.240 --> 00:14:40.440
[Guest]: They were very kind people, putting up with this young guy who was asking this question

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:41.440
[Guest]: who knew nothing.

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:47.760
[Guest]: You know, but the first impact of all this happened in the way I was singing.

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:53.000
[Guest]: And I, very naturally, I started fiddling around with the idea of the performance.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:58.720
[Guest]: Every art practice has a performative, a form.

00:14:58.720 --> 00:15:04.860
[Guest]: And we should realize that the form is a reflection of the art, right?

00:15:04.860 --> 00:15:10.280
[Guest]: But after a point of time, that performative becomes the solidified notion of the art,

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:11.280
[Guest]: right?

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:16.040
[Guest]: So slowly, I started playing with the performative, you know, because I felt, you know, if it's

00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:20.800
[Guest]: all just about the way I design something and offer it package and give it to you, then

00:15:20.800 --> 00:15:21.800
[Guest]: it's just so simple.

00:15:21.800 --> 00:15:22.920
[Guest]: It can't be.

00:15:22.920 --> 00:15:25.880
[Guest]: So that was a moment when I started, my music started changing.

00:15:25.880 --> 00:15:27.400
[Guest]: I didn't notice it.

00:15:27.400 --> 00:15:29.600
[Guest]: I didn't notice it was changing.

00:15:29.600 --> 00:15:30.720
[Guest]: The audience didn't notice it.

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:32.240
[Guest]: They didn't see anything radical.

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:35.520
[Guest]: I had not like made a big shift for a long time.

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:40.080
[Guest]: But after a point, I knew I was listening differently, you know, I was, I was looking

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:41.860
[Guest]: at a concert differently.

00:15:41.860 --> 00:15:44.040
[Guest]: So that's where it began.

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:49.280
[Guest]: But the moment all this happens, I think you're also asking questions of society, of people

00:15:49.280 --> 00:15:52.540
[Guest]: who's singing this, you know, who was singing it.

00:15:52.540 --> 00:15:55.120
[Guest]: When they sang it, how did it sound?

00:15:55.120 --> 00:16:00.940
[Guest]: So when you ask these questions, then you're automatically asking political questions.

00:16:00.940 --> 00:16:03.440
[Guest]: And first of all, you're asking these questions of yourself.

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:09.000
[Guest]: So I must tell you that it is not like these ideas of caste or anything were in my any

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.480
[Guest]: part of the horizon for a long time.

00:16:11.480 --> 00:16:14.040
[Guest]: It is a word I never used in my life.

00:16:14.040 --> 00:16:20.840
[Guest]: You know, it is even in the most democratic, open home of mine, caste was never discussed.

00:16:20.840 --> 00:16:22.400
[Guest]: That's the fact.

00:16:22.400 --> 00:16:30.360
[Guest]: It came only because of this kind of confusions and all these struggles that were happening.

00:16:30.360 --> 00:16:36.600
[Guest]: And that's when identity became gender, all these questions started appearing in my view.

00:16:36.600 --> 00:16:41.360
[Amit Varma]: And people often have the view that in contrast with other kinds of music, and I'm sort of

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:43.120
[Amit Varma]: I don't know Carnatic music very well.

00:16:43.120 --> 00:16:47.440
[Amit Varma]: So the listeners and you will have to forgive me if I say something hopelessly naive.

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:51.960
[Amit Varma]: But it's often looked at as something that is very rigid, and that has become ossified

00:16:51.960 --> 00:16:53.240
[Amit Varma]: through the years.

00:16:53.240 --> 00:16:57.800
[Amit Varma]: Is that rigidity also a consequence of what's happening in in the background socially?

00:16:57.800 --> 00:17:02.440
[Guest]: Okay, first of all, like burst the bubble of Hindustani musicians, they are also ossified

00:17:02.440 --> 00:17:03.440
[Guest]: and rigid.

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:07.320
[Guest]: It's just a notion of rigidity and ossification is different.

00:17:07.320 --> 00:17:11.160
[Guest]: Okay, so I have to put it out there.

00:17:11.160 --> 00:17:13.720
[Guest]: So the point is, I think it's true.

00:17:13.720 --> 00:17:14.720
[Guest]: Yes.

00:17:14.720 --> 00:17:18.960
[Guest]: So without going into the idea of rigidity and what it means, I think there is definitely

00:17:18.960 --> 00:17:25.440
[Guest]: this, it becomes crusty, no doubt, whether it is Hindustani music, or that's also because

00:17:25.440 --> 00:17:29.560
[Guest]: of what we think it represents, I think that's a very important aspect we should think about.

00:17:29.560 --> 00:17:31.120
[Guest]: Why is it ossified?

00:17:31.120 --> 00:17:32.120
[Guest]: Why is it crusty?

00:17:32.120 --> 00:17:35.840
[Guest]: Because we believe that in that form, it symbolizes something.

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:39.200
[Guest]: And we're more interested in the symbol than the art.

00:17:39.200 --> 00:17:41.000
[Guest]: That's the point of the performative.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:45.280
[Guest]: So the performative becomes the symbol of identifying something about India, something

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:50.000
[Guest]: about our sound, Nada, you know, all these notions, and you know, whether you believe

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.200
[Guest]: in it or not, is a different issue altogether.

00:17:52.200 --> 00:17:54.680
[Guest]: So we want that symbol to remain.

00:17:54.680 --> 00:18:00.180
[Guest]: And we believe that any movement there kind of demolishes the symbol, and we've created

00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:01.400
[Guest]: this symbol.

00:18:01.400 --> 00:18:07.800
[Guest]: And there's no doubt that all that has played a role in keeping something unquestioned.

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:10.920
[Guest]: And I want to say something, people may say that no, no, no, but certain things have changed

00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:15.140
[Guest]: in the last 60 years, neither Kerala, neither Carnatic music is the same, true.

00:18:15.140 --> 00:18:18.520
[Guest]: So the question is, what do you allow to be questioned?

00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:19.920
[Guest]: What don't you allow to be questioned?

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:22.300
[Guest]: That's society does brilliantly, right?

00:18:22.300 --> 00:18:27.560
[Guest]: We know what can change, I can probably change a raga, I can introduce a new raga, I can

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:31.480
[Guest]: do something, all these are surface level operations, right?

00:18:31.480 --> 00:18:34.680
[Guest]: Because after a point, a musician should be able to do this.

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:38.680
[Guest]: But then what about the fundamentals of what the music itself represents?

00:18:38.680 --> 00:18:41.240
[Guest]: What are the non-negotiables in your, in your idea of the music?

00:18:41.240 --> 00:18:46.040
[Guest]: You ask those questions, those are political questions, and those questions will never

00:18:46.040 --> 00:18:51.360
[Guest]: be asked, especially of the so-called classical, I call them the so-called classicals, because

00:18:51.360 --> 00:18:59.960
[Guest]: you believe that you are the moral, ethical, aesthetic identity of what is Indian culture.

00:18:59.960 --> 00:19:02.200
[Guest]: Everything else plays around.

00:19:02.200 --> 00:19:07.480
[Amit Varma]: So you know, so when you start figuring this stuff out, like one, I think it's almost then,

00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:10.760
[Amit Varma]: if I read it correctly, an act of rebellion and changing the music itself, because that

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:15.560
[Amit Varma]: itself is a political statement, by changing the way you perform, you're questioning the

00:19:15.560 --> 00:19:16.840
[Amit Varma]: sort of existing structures.

00:19:16.840 --> 00:19:24.120
[Amit Varma]: But what it also strikes me is that what must be very difficult about figuring out the politics

00:19:24.120 --> 00:19:27.920
[Amit Varma]: behind all of it, how these entrenched caste structures have played a part, the damage

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:33.520
[Amit Varma]: that they've done to society in general, the privileging of the classical over the non-classical,

00:19:33.520 --> 00:19:37.880
[Amit Varma]: all of this, you're also questioning yourself and your own place, because you are a product

00:19:37.880 --> 00:19:38.880
[Amit Varma]: of all this privilege.

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:41.320
[Amit Varma]: You are at the centre of it, you are this.

00:19:41.320 --> 00:19:45.760
[Amit Varma]: How hard was that process, like, it must be so tempting to say, you know, everything has

00:19:45.760 --> 00:19:46.760
[Amit Varma]: its own place.

00:19:46.760 --> 00:19:48.720
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just, you know, art is by itself.

00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:50.080
[Amit Varma]: And all of this doesn't matter.

00:19:50.080 --> 00:19:56.320
[Guest]: And, you know, well, it was very difficult, especially in the beginning, because there

00:19:56.320 --> 00:19:59.440
[Guest]: was a time period when I was worried I will lose the music.

00:19:59.440 --> 00:20:06.760
[Guest]: Because my question was, if everything is so political, if everything is so entrenched

00:20:06.760 --> 00:20:14.000
[Guest]: in ugliness of sorts, then is there anything to this at all?

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:22.200
[Guest]: You know, should I be saying aha, or is saying aha itself an act of violence, for example,

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:27.000
[Guest]: in the sense that am I saying aha, because I am doing that out of habituation of reiteration

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:30.280
[Guest]: of identities, or is the aha beyond that?

00:20:30.280 --> 00:20:33.640
[Guest]: You know, you can't really say, honestly, you can't really say.

00:20:33.640 --> 00:20:39.440
[Guest]: So there was a point I was saying, suppose after this whole exercise, I don't feel the

00:20:39.440 --> 00:20:40.440
[Guest]: music anymore.

00:20:40.440 --> 00:20:41.440
[Guest]: What do I do?

00:20:41.440 --> 00:20:43.720
[Guest]: And that was very real.

00:20:43.720 --> 00:20:49.120
[Guest]: That feeling, that fear was real, because I knew if I push honestly, I could get to

00:20:49.120 --> 00:20:53.200
[Guest]: a point where everything in this music sounds ugly to me.

00:20:53.200 --> 00:20:56.560
[Guest]: Because I believe I've said everything is social, everything is political, everything

00:20:56.560 --> 00:20:57.600
[Guest]: is discriminative.

00:20:57.600 --> 00:21:02.400
[Guest]: So the whole thing is then collapses, right, in my own emotional and psychological world.

00:21:02.400 --> 00:21:03.760
[Guest]: That fear I did have.

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:06.280
[Guest]: Were there moments when it happened?

00:21:06.280 --> 00:21:12.800
[Guest]: No, I think what's what saved me if you want to use that expression, I won't use that expression,

00:21:12.800 --> 00:21:21.200
[Guest]: is that there were moments in the music still, where I believed that that sound somehow at

00:21:21.200 --> 00:21:29.360
[Guest]: least temporarily made me see the ugliness with greater clarity.

00:21:29.360 --> 00:21:33.760
[Guest]: So I said, okay, maybe it could be Amit that I'm creating this whole thing.

00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:38.200
[Guest]: Okay, what I'm telling you right now, it could be, I'm not a psychologist, I'm not a person

00:21:38.200 --> 00:21:39.680
[Guest]: who can judge that.

00:21:39.680 --> 00:21:44.080
[Guest]: But there were moments when I said, the clarity with which I could see the ugliness because

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:48.400
[Guest]: I was singing, or I was listening to the music, I was not having a discourse, I'm just singing,

00:21:48.400 --> 00:21:55.600
[Guest]: I'm singing a raga, and then pop for about five minutes, there is greater clarity.

00:21:55.600 --> 00:21:59.520
[Guest]: I said, okay, if the sound can give me that, maybe there is some truth to it.

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:04.120
[Guest]: Maybe there is something that is truth to art, that it can really move across it.

00:22:04.120 --> 00:22:05.120
[Guest]: But we can't hold on to it.

00:22:05.120 --> 00:22:07.960
[Guest]: There is something that drags us back into who we are.

00:22:07.960 --> 00:22:14.920
[Guest]: So that's what gave me hope that, okay, I can still sing, I can still feel, and I can

00:22:14.920 --> 00:22:17.660
[Guest]: still say I'm ugly.

00:22:17.660 --> 00:22:22.120
[Guest]: So what I thought was a contradiction, then moved away from becoming a contradiction became

00:22:22.120 --> 00:22:27.640
[Guest]: more real, that these things always exist together, the profound and the profane are

00:22:27.640 --> 00:22:28.640
[Guest]: not opposites.

00:22:28.640 --> 00:22:31.920
[Guest]: They are constantly with each other.

00:22:31.920 --> 00:22:37.120
[Guest]: And they're truly real, when in a way, you feel both.

00:22:37.120 --> 00:22:38.120
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:22:38.120 --> 00:22:43.840
[Amit Varma]: So, I mean, this question about art is also something that I think is alive in other contexts,

00:22:43.840 --> 00:22:49.820
[Amit Varma]: like is art something separate from itself from A, the social structures and the politics

00:22:49.820 --> 00:22:54.000
[Amit Varma]: that have led to it and from B, from the artist, because more and more we find that we look

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:57.640
[Amit Varma]: back upon time and we say that, all right, these artists were accused of me too, should

00:22:57.640 --> 00:23:02.160
[Amit Varma]: we read their books, or these artists were, you know, assaulters, or, you know, Neruda

00:23:02.160 --> 00:23:05.600
[Amit Varma]: raped someone when he was whatever, should we read their work?

00:23:05.600 --> 00:23:10.320
[Amit Varma]: And that becomes sort of a big question on the one hand, it seems to me that at this

00:23:10.320 --> 00:23:15.560
[Amit Varma]: moment in time, if you sing a couple of notes, and it moves me in a particular way, my being

00:23:15.560 --> 00:23:19.840
[Amit Varma]: moved by just the sound is something that is surely independent of where it is coming

00:23:19.840 --> 00:23:20.840
[Amit Varma]: from.

00:23:20.840 --> 00:23:24.120
[Amit Varma]: So that art, that music per se stands apart.

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:29.200
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, it's kind of, I mean, do you agree that it stands apart or do you

00:23:29.200 --> 00:23:30.200
[Amit Varma]: think that?

00:23:30.200 --> 00:23:33.760
[Guest]: I'll try and answer in two parts.

00:23:33.760 --> 00:23:39.160
[Guest]: So this notion of art for art's sake, you know, it's a very well used cliche.

00:23:39.160 --> 00:23:45.460
[Guest]: My problem with that, that construction is somehow inside that construction is a disassociation

00:23:45.460 --> 00:23:47.000
[Guest]: with reality.

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:52.440
[Guest]: That somehow with this bubble floating at 7000 meters up there, and we're all looking

00:23:52.440 --> 00:23:54.740
[Guest]: at it in wonderment.

00:23:54.740 --> 00:24:00.520
[Guest]: But I'm saying suppose you redefine art in that statement and say art is reality with

00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:03.280
[Guest]: all its layers.

00:24:03.280 --> 00:24:07.960
[Guest]: And whenever something has multiple layers, it's automatically profound.

00:24:07.960 --> 00:24:09.680
[Guest]: I'm not judging it, okay?

00:24:09.680 --> 00:24:14.000
[Guest]: When it is flat and literal, there is nothing else to it.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:15.000
[Guest]: Okay?

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:18.880
[Guest]: When we make it a bubble, we're making it flat and literal, we're taking away the layers

00:24:18.880 --> 00:24:19.880
[Guest]: of it.

00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:25.280
[Guest]: But when we say art is, we are in the studio having this conversation, art is not just

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:27.120
[Guest]: what I'm saying and what you're saying.

00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:28.380
[Guest]: It's about what you're evoking.

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:30.420
[Guest]: It's about what the recorder is looking at.

00:24:30.420 --> 00:24:32.180
[Guest]: It's about what I see out of the window.

00:24:32.180 --> 00:24:35.640
[Guest]: It's about all the complexities that's going in my head and your head as we're having this

00:24:35.640 --> 00:24:41.040
[Guest]: conversation beyond this room, then it becomes something so vibrant, right?

00:24:41.040 --> 00:24:45.200
[Guest]: So I would like to trust that kind of art, okay?

00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:48.000
[Guest]: It doesn't mean that art has to be, that has to be like overtly political.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:49.200
[Guest]: No, I'm not saying that.

00:24:49.200 --> 00:24:52.920
[Guest]: To your second question, that's, in fact, something I've struggled with.

00:24:52.920 --> 00:24:55.920
[Guest]: The artist and the art, you know, what does one do?

00:24:55.920 --> 00:24:59.320
[Guest]: And I don't have a correct answer to it.

00:24:59.320 --> 00:25:06.720
[Guest]: I tried grappling with it in a piece I wrote about Wagner, Tiagaraja, and about Polanski.

00:25:06.720 --> 00:25:07.880
[Guest]: Very three different reasons.

00:25:07.880 --> 00:25:10.440
[Guest]: And I want to bring Daniel Barenboim here.

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:13.280
[Guest]: He's a very well-known Jewish conductor.

00:25:13.280 --> 00:25:17.320
[Guest]: And he did something which really impacted me, you know.

00:25:17.320 --> 00:25:24.320
[Guest]: So you know what Wagner's music represents, an anti-Semitic kind of history.

00:25:24.320 --> 00:25:27.280
[Guest]: And he's performing in Jerusalem.

00:25:27.280 --> 00:25:34.000
[Guest]: And Barenboim says he's going to perform Wagner with an audience of Jews.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.600
[Guest]: That was such a profound idea to me.

00:25:36.600 --> 00:25:41.120
[Guest]: Now, do we dissociate Wagner from the music?

00:25:41.120 --> 00:25:47.840
[Guest]: Do we say Wagner is independent to what the historical impressions he leaves, and it's

00:25:47.840 --> 00:25:49.280
[Guest]: just music?

00:25:49.280 --> 00:25:51.040
[Guest]: But Barenboim does something interesting.

00:25:51.040 --> 00:25:52.800
[Guest]: He kind of conflates both.

00:25:52.800 --> 00:25:59.560
[Guest]: He brings the individual in, or what the individual represents in, and he says, I still want us

00:25:59.560 --> 00:26:01.080
[Guest]: to hear it.

00:26:01.080 --> 00:26:03.480
[Guest]: Now what does this do to the experience?

00:26:03.480 --> 00:26:06.520
[Guest]: I think that's where we have an interesting muddle.

00:26:06.520 --> 00:26:10.200
[Guest]: So do I not stop watching Roman Polanski?

00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:19.520
[Guest]: No, but I'm saying if we can, in a way, keep that tension real between the horrible things

00:26:19.520 --> 00:26:26.760
[Guest]: of the artist and the most moving things of the art produced or art object, then that

00:26:26.760 --> 00:26:29.200
[Guest]: tension gives us a different experience.

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:31.800
[Amit Varma]: So we can condemn what the artists read, but celebrate the art.

00:26:31.800 --> 00:26:34.680
[Guest]: At the same time, at the same time, I think, but we can't forget it.

00:26:34.680 --> 00:26:38.240
[Guest]: I'm saying at the same time, I have a problem if you say, you know, I don't care what kind

00:26:38.240 --> 00:26:39.240
[Guest]: of person the artist is.

00:26:39.240 --> 00:26:40.400
[Guest]: I'm not willing to do that.

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:44.280
[Guest]: I'm saying you have to allow that tension to be there in your experience.

00:26:44.280 --> 00:26:46.280
[Guest]: It may change the way you experience the art.

00:26:46.280 --> 00:26:50.960
[Guest]: But if you say, I don't care about who the person, the artist is, I mean, that to me

00:26:50.960 --> 00:26:54.400
[Guest]: is again another way of just brushing something under the carpet.

00:26:54.400 --> 00:26:57.880
[Guest]: So it's a complicated situation for which there's no absolute answer.

00:26:57.880 --> 00:27:02.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I find it evocative what you say about art being so complex with so many

00:27:02.520 --> 00:27:04.640
[Amit Varma]: layers and that's what makes it beautiful.

00:27:04.640 --> 00:27:09.080
[Amit Varma]: But in modern times, what often happens is that politics looks for simple narratives

00:27:09.080 --> 00:27:13.040
[Amit Varma]: and therefore embracing this complexity and accepting that dissonance, like you pointed

00:27:13.040 --> 00:27:15.960
[Amit Varma]: out that on the one hand, there is the ugliness to deal with.

00:27:15.960 --> 00:27:19.280
[Amit Varma]: And on the other hand, there is all this beauty can get hard.

00:27:19.280 --> 00:27:22.880
[Amit Varma]: And a related question to that is when you when you were writing Sebastian and Sons,

00:27:22.880 --> 00:27:29.260
[Amit Varma]: for example, or whenever you've kind of looked back on history, how hard is it to not judge

00:27:29.260 --> 00:27:32.720
[Amit Varma]: historical characters by contemporary morality?

00:27:32.720 --> 00:27:37.200
[Amit Varma]: For example, some of the people in Sebastian and Sons like Vaidyanathan Iyer or later,

00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:41.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, Palgatmani Iyer, where you write about Palgatmani Iyer, you can see how a lot

00:27:41.640 --> 00:27:45.760
[Amit Varma]: of that entrenched Brahmanism is there in his behavior and the things he does.

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:51.040
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, he has an extremely tender relationship with Parlandu who is his,

00:27:51.040 --> 00:27:52.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, chief maker.

00:27:52.040 --> 00:27:55.280
[Amit Varma]: And it's almost touching the sort of bond that they have.

00:27:55.280 --> 00:27:59.480
[Amit Varma]: So you know, and versions of this question can go back forever to Jefferson and his slave

00:27:59.480 --> 00:28:01.840
[Unknown]: Sally Hemings and all the way.

00:28:01.840 --> 00:28:08.680
[Amit Varma]: So you know, when you look back at history, do you try to dissociate contemporary morality

00:28:08.680 --> 00:28:09.680
[Amit Varma]: with that?

00:28:09.680 --> 00:28:13.720
[Amit Varma]: Or you say that, no, you know, there's also something useful in looking at the things

00:28:13.720 --> 00:28:14.720
[Guest]: they did with this lens.

00:28:14.720 --> 00:28:19.360
[Guest]: I mean, I think it's important to look at all this as a flow, okay, whatever direction

00:28:19.360 --> 00:28:20.360
[Guest]: it takes.

00:28:20.360 --> 00:28:27.760
[Guest]: I don't think it's correct to impose upon modern morality or modern ethical living,

00:28:27.760 --> 00:28:29.180
[Guest]: because this is also a movement.

00:28:29.180 --> 00:28:31.760
[Guest]: We are not in some absolute position even today, right?

00:28:31.760 --> 00:28:37.720
[Guest]: But at the same time, I think putting a lens on what happened is very, very important,

00:28:37.720 --> 00:28:41.640
[Guest]: because the tendency for us is to say it was all then like this.

00:28:41.640 --> 00:28:49.980
[Guest]: And now we're all somehow perfect in some sense, you know, and I find that deeply disturbing.

00:28:49.980 --> 00:28:55.600
[Guest]: So when you put the lens on something behind, you're also saying, okay, but what does it

00:28:55.600 --> 00:28:57.040
[Guest]: say about us now?

00:28:57.040 --> 00:29:03.200
[Guest]: And what I like to do is also when I put the lens on history, to add some layer of nuance

00:29:03.200 --> 00:29:06.040
[Guest]: into that, because Maneer is not a flat person.

00:29:06.040 --> 00:29:11.360
[Guest]: I mean, he's not like, you know, so as you said, there is this whole tenderness, there

00:29:11.360 --> 00:29:15.000
[Guest]: is love, but there is hierarchy.

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:22.920
[Guest]: There is this inability to accept the reality, inability to go beyond his own limitations.

00:29:22.920 --> 00:29:28.600
[Guest]: So that is interesting for me, because that is as real today as it was then.

00:29:28.600 --> 00:29:29.600
[Amit Varma]: Because I am like that.

00:29:29.600 --> 00:29:30.600
[Amit Varma]: I'm no different.

00:29:30.600 --> 00:29:33.400
[Amit Varma]: I think we all like that in the sense that there are some things we can see and it's

00:29:33.400 --> 00:29:35.760
[Amit Varma]: almost poignant that they're invisible to him.

00:29:35.760 --> 00:29:38.160
[Guest]: And there are so many things that must be invisible to you.

00:29:38.160 --> 00:29:39.160
[Guest]: Exactly the point.

00:29:39.160 --> 00:29:40.960
[Guest]: And which is why that lens is important.

00:29:40.960 --> 00:29:46.480
[Guest]: Can putting the lens on Maneer with the things that he was blind to somehow reflect upon

00:29:46.480 --> 00:29:48.440
[Guest]: what are we blind to?

00:29:48.440 --> 00:29:50.800
[Guest]: That is what I find interesting within that.

00:29:50.800 --> 00:29:53.520
[Guest]: It is not about the character itself.

00:29:53.520 --> 00:29:56.680
[Guest]: It's about the fact, okay, just to see if I'm, you know, if somebody read Sebastian

00:29:56.680 --> 00:30:01.280
[Guest]: Sons and just see what you described as, you know, this tenderness, and they also see this,

00:30:01.280 --> 00:30:04.760
[Guest]: can they think about themselves, you know, in some way, can I think about, I mean, I

00:30:04.760 --> 00:30:05.760
[Amit Varma]: do that.

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:07.760
[Guest]: Can they think about what they have normalized in their own lives?

00:30:07.760 --> 00:30:08.760
[Guest]: Yes.

00:30:08.760 --> 00:30:09.800
[Guest]: That is the hope.

00:30:09.800 --> 00:30:15.360
[Guest]: That is truly the hope that that is why it makes sense looking at the past for me, at

00:30:15.360 --> 00:30:17.000
[Guest]: least as a writer.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:22.320
[Guest]: Because then I think you can use those, because I don't think society in terms of how it operates

00:30:22.320 --> 00:30:24.880
[Guest]: in frameworks has ever changed.

00:30:24.880 --> 00:30:27.040
[Guest]: The frameworks are always the same.

00:30:27.040 --> 00:30:31.720
[Guest]: It's the interior, the semantics and the structures that may vary.

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:33.160
[Guest]: The basic framework is the same.

00:30:33.160 --> 00:30:37.560
[Guest]: So can we just shift the framework and say, so even in the book, when you see it move

00:30:37.560 --> 00:30:41.520
[Guest]: through time, you will see that the framework is constantly there.

00:30:41.520 --> 00:30:44.480
[Guest]: It's just a negotiational table is changing, right?

00:30:44.480 --> 00:30:47.400
[Guest]: So that is, for me, very important.

00:30:47.400 --> 00:30:52.120
[Amit Varma]: And for me, where your book also works is that it's not it is both a political and a

00:30:52.120 --> 00:30:53.120
[Amit Varma]: non political book.

00:30:53.120 --> 00:30:56.560
[Amit Varma]: It's a political book, because of course, it is looking at all of these things that

00:30:56.560 --> 00:31:00.160
[Amit Varma]: are happening, all of these power structures of Brahmanism is playing out how misogyny

00:31:00.160 --> 00:31:02.400
[Amit Varma]: and patriarchy and all of those are playing out.

00:31:02.400 --> 00:31:06.520
[Amit Varma]: But what it also refreshingly does is that all of these people are humans to me, you

00:31:06.520 --> 00:31:10.840
[Amit Varma]: know, I begin to feel that like someone like Mani Aiyar, where I both have enormous empathy

00:31:10.840 --> 00:31:11.840
[Amit Varma]: for him.

00:31:11.840 --> 00:31:15.200
[Amit Varma]: You know, you feel like, okay, he's trapped in that, you know, he might be doing some

00:31:15.200 --> 00:31:20.120
[Amit Varma]: things which we would not approve of today or do ourselves, but he's kind of trapped.

00:31:20.120 --> 00:31:23.720
[Amit Varma]: Before we sort of get to talking about the book, which is a very rich and interesting

00:31:23.720 --> 00:31:25.000
[Amit Varma]: book.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:30.360
[Amit Varma]: For those of us who are not so familiar with it, which really includes me also, to an extent,

00:31:30.360 --> 00:31:35.880
[Amit Varma]: give us a summary of what you discovered about this world of Carnatic music about all the

00:31:35.880 --> 00:31:41.800
[Amit Varma]: sort of the unexpected ugliness that lay behind the book, not through this book, particularly,

00:31:41.800 --> 00:31:42.800
[Guest]: but in general,

00:31:42.800 --> 00:31:50.280
[Guest]: You know, yeah, so, I mean, I grew up in the interiors of Carnatic music, okay.

00:31:50.280 --> 00:31:55.840
[Guest]: And I grew up in the interiors having the privilege of being an elite in the interior.

00:31:55.840 --> 00:32:00.120
[Guest]: So, you know, I had it all, you know, yeah, I mean, it's like, I was not a middle class

00:32:00.120 --> 00:32:05.440
[Guest]: interior representative, I was an elite interior representative, you know, so I even looked

00:32:05.440 --> 00:32:07.800
[Guest]: down upon the middle class structures within it, right?

00:32:07.800 --> 00:32:15.080
[Guest]: You are the Karan Johar of Carnatic music, I'm gonna let that pass, but I will go on.

00:32:15.080 --> 00:32:19.800
[Guest]: But so, I lived it.

00:32:19.800 --> 00:32:24.120
[Guest]: I was definitely part of the power corridors.

00:32:24.120 --> 00:32:26.520
[Guest]: I probably still am, how much do I dissociate from it?

00:32:26.520 --> 00:32:29.100
[Guest]: And that's, that's what I live with all my life.

00:32:29.100 --> 00:32:33.000
[Guest]: And so I did not see any of these things for a very long time.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:38.120
[Guest]: But then when all these, you know, internal churnings happened towards me, I mean, within

00:32:38.120 --> 00:32:42.080
[Guest]: me, I think I was asking these questions of myself.

00:32:42.080 --> 00:32:47.000
[Guest]: You know, I was asking these questions of, you know, okay, what am I really representing?

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:49.000
[Guest]: What am I really singing?

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:55.160
[Guest]: And what is that, that pleasure that I'm getting from it, the moment that the ugliness I discovered

00:32:55.160 --> 00:33:00.000
[Guest]: and is not unique of Carnatic music, Carnatic music is my entry point, because that's, that's

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:02.520
[Guest]: all I knew.

00:33:02.520 --> 00:33:11.200
[Guest]: Just the fact of how patriarchy, how casteism are so normalized, I think that's the biggest

00:33:11.200 --> 00:33:16.680
[Guest]: learning for me, that it's so normalized, there's a homogeneousness to it.

00:33:16.680 --> 00:33:20.760
[Guest]: And homogeneousness is in fact taken as a conditionality.

00:33:20.760 --> 00:33:25.780
[Guest]: You know, the kind of people who should come, where should this art be produced?

00:33:25.780 --> 00:33:29.280
[Guest]: What is the ideal place that you should consume it?

00:33:29.280 --> 00:33:32.080
[Guest]: How should the people there behave?

00:33:32.080 --> 00:33:35.040
[Guest]: How should the women who come to the concert dress?

00:33:35.040 --> 00:33:38.400
[Guest]: And how, what did my music class tell me about my identity?

00:33:38.400 --> 00:33:43.700
[Guest]: I had to, why was that the music class was not just about music, but it's about so many

00:33:43.700 --> 00:33:48.200
[Guest]: things else and what was being conveyed to me, you know, all these like started hitting

00:33:48.200 --> 00:33:49.200
[Guest]: me.

00:33:49.200 --> 00:33:55.920
[Guest]: And I realized that the entire world is a world of a certain homogeneous, upper caste

00:33:55.920 --> 00:33:58.440
[Guest]: patriarchal structure.

00:33:58.440 --> 00:34:00.840
[Amit Varma]: And within this, we are celebrating Indian culture.

00:34:00.840 --> 00:34:05.920
[Guest]: And not just by default, there are rigidly enforced entry barriers, you know, it's very

00:34:05.920 --> 00:34:09.360
[Guest]: important to understand how these entry barriers operate, you know, and they've operated in

00:34:09.360 --> 00:34:13.200
[Guest]: different ways through time, again, when you go back to the past, but the barrier is still

00:34:13.200 --> 00:34:14.200
[Guest]: there.

00:34:14.200 --> 00:34:17.880
[Guest]: It's these invisible screens, you know, it's, it's, everybody knows that.

00:34:17.880 --> 00:34:21.600
[Guest]: I mean, it's, there's this move, I always use this, I have used in reshaping art, there's

00:34:21.600 --> 00:34:23.920
[Guest]: this Tamil movie called Kaka Muttai.

00:34:23.920 --> 00:34:26.040
[Guest]: And I would urge everybody to watch it.

00:34:26.040 --> 00:34:28.800
[Guest]: I think it's on Amazon Prime or something.

00:34:28.800 --> 00:34:33.240
[Guest]: And there is this scene, and the scene is this, the story is very simple.

00:34:33.240 --> 00:34:38.480
[Guest]: It's about these two kids, who a pizzeria is open in their locality, and they are kids

00:34:38.480 --> 00:34:42.000
[Guest]: from a neighboring slum.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:48.000
[Guest]: And they want to get into pizzeria, and the watchman looks at them and throws them out.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.080
[Guest]: So they then decide they need better clothes.

00:34:50.080 --> 00:34:52.520
[Guest]: And if they wear better clothes, they'll be allowed in.

00:34:52.520 --> 00:34:54.640
[Guest]: So they decide to go to a mall.

00:34:54.640 --> 00:35:00.880
[Guest]: So they go to this, two kids go and they turn the, you know, just turn the end of the road

00:35:00.880 --> 00:35:05.880
[Guest]: and they see the mall and one, they're brothers, one of them looks at the other and said, oh,

00:35:05.880 --> 00:35:08.280
[Guest]: I said, they're going to let us in.

00:35:08.280 --> 00:35:11.460
[Guest]: You know, nobody has said they can't enter the mall.

00:35:11.460 --> 00:35:15.720
[Guest]: The kids have seen the mall, and they've decided that they're not going to be allowed in.

00:35:15.720 --> 00:35:19.420
[Guest]: So this is what we should understand with great care.

00:35:19.420 --> 00:35:21.840
[Guest]: So these designs are always there.

00:35:21.840 --> 00:35:27.640
[Guest]: We design society to decide who can come in, who cannot come in, what sound can come in,

00:35:27.640 --> 00:35:33.360
[Guest]: what sound is outer, when do we throw somebody out, when do we allow somebody in?

00:35:33.360 --> 00:35:37.560
[Guest]: So for example, how do I need to change in order to be acceptable?

00:35:37.560 --> 00:35:39.100
[Guest]: We see this world over.

00:35:39.100 --> 00:35:42.600
[Guest]: It's not just in India, it's ethnicity, it's color, it's race.

00:35:42.600 --> 00:35:44.480
[Guest]: We see the need.

00:35:44.480 --> 00:35:46.760
[Guest]: So it's like everybody is playing a part.

00:35:46.760 --> 00:35:51.160
[Guest]: The person who has power, cultural power, is making sure these notions are there, making

00:35:51.160 --> 00:35:55.400
[Guest]: sure they keep changing according to time, but fundamentals are there.

00:35:55.400 --> 00:36:00.320
[Guest]: People who want to look at social and cultural mobility are saying, okay, how can I become

00:36:00.320 --> 00:36:01.880
[Guest]: more like that?

00:36:01.880 --> 00:36:07.320
[Guest]: And that's such an ugly structure in it, that you need to give up something of yourself,

00:36:07.320 --> 00:36:11.100
[Guest]: you want acceptability at this place, first of all, you place it at a higher level.

00:36:11.100 --> 00:36:12.100
[Guest]: So what about people?

00:36:12.100 --> 00:36:13.240
[Guest]: What about different cultures?

00:36:13.240 --> 00:36:14.980
[Guest]: What about different habits?

00:36:14.980 --> 00:36:16.720
[Guest]: So what are we saying?

00:36:16.720 --> 00:36:22.320
[Guest]: You know, it is, it's very, honestly, even as I say, this is so deeply disturbing for

00:36:22.320 --> 00:36:23.320
[Amit Varma]: me.

00:36:23.320 --> 00:36:27.960
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of it is invisible and unstated, as you just said, in the sense that, you know,

00:36:27.960 --> 00:36:31.560
[Amit Varma]: if a lower caste person enters the house of, you know, someone from a higher caste, he

00:36:31.560 --> 00:36:34.440
[Guest]: will instinctively sit on the floor or he'll be embarrassed about entering.

00:36:34.440 --> 00:36:39.360
[Guest]: And this is so instinctive that to, you know, to someone who's grown up like that, it's

00:36:39.360 --> 00:36:40.360
[Guest]: just understood.

00:36:40.360 --> 00:36:41.360
[Guest]: You don't think about it.

00:36:41.360 --> 00:36:46.040
[Guest]: And also, I can, if that person did not sit on the floor and just sat on the sofa, what

00:36:46.040 --> 00:36:51.440
[Guest]: would my instinctive react, even the progressive TM Krishna think, for a split second in my

00:36:51.440 --> 00:36:56.440
[Guest]: mind will go this thought, oh, now what does that mean?

00:36:56.440 --> 00:37:01.360
[Guest]: It means that somehow I expected a certain behavior from this individual.

00:37:01.360 --> 00:37:03.480
[Guest]: And the person has transgressed.

00:37:03.480 --> 00:37:07.440
[Guest]: I may correct myself for to tick off the liberal box.

00:37:07.440 --> 00:37:10.000
[Guest]: But the fact is that feeling is there, right?

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:13.960
[Guest]: So these, I mean, I always find it very interesting that when you talk about caste, people find

00:37:13.960 --> 00:37:14.960
[Guest]: problematic.

00:37:14.960 --> 00:37:21.160
[Guest]: But, you know, if you just in the frame and talk about gender, I know women and trans

00:37:21.160 --> 00:37:26.160
[Guest]: people know this every day, you know, and it's always fascinating for me when upper

00:37:26.160 --> 00:37:30.680
[Guest]: caste women feminists don't get it in caste, but they get it in feminism.

00:37:30.680 --> 00:37:33.780
[Guest]: I'm like, do you realize it's the same framework?

00:37:33.780 --> 00:37:35.600
[Guest]: It's that look that you talk about.

00:37:35.600 --> 00:37:38.960
[Guest]: It's the inequality in looking at two people that you talk about that you feel it.

00:37:38.960 --> 00:37:42.880
[Guest]: I would never feed it because I'm a man and I'm, I have everything going for me, but it's

00:37:42.880 --> 00:37:47.720
[Guest]: the same framework that happens in caste and race and in ethnicity.

00:37:47.720 --> 00:37:50.800
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, there's a nice bit from Sebastian and Sons, which I marked out, which expresses

00:37:50.800 --> 00:37:52.080
[Amit Varma]: exactly this.

00:37:52.080 --> 00:37:56.800
[Amit Varma]: And I'll quote from your book, and this is someone speaking, quote, the relationship

00:37:56.800 --> 00:38:01.600
[Amit Varma]: between the widwan and honorific often used for seasoned artists and the worker is like

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:03.400
[Amit Varma]: that of a husband and wife.

00:38:03.400 --> 00:38:06.880
[Amit Varma]: Only if there are arguments and disagreements between the husband and the wife, will the

00:38:06.880 --> 00:38:08.120
[Amit Varma]: family move ahead.

00:38:08.120 --> 00:38:10.120
[Amit Varma]: If I am upset, I will not say much.

00:38:10.120 --> 00:38:14.720
[Amit Varma]: They will notice that from my facial expression and introspect about how they spoke to me.

00:38:14.720 --> 00:38:19.000
[Amit Varma]: It has been going on like this, and it should hopefully continue, stop quote.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:24.080
[Amit Varma]: And I mean, this spoke to me so much because it's, it's casteism and the patriarchy, and

00:38:24.080 --> 00:38:25.240
[Amit Varma]: they're both together.

00:38:25.240 --> 00:38:29.800
[Amit Varma]: And all of us have experienced, you know, if not one, at least the other in some form

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:30.800
[Amit Varma]: of the other.

00:38:30.800 --> 00:38:34.280
[Amit Varma]: And I was also reminded of this, but there was this very interesting tweet by a writer

00:38:34.280 --> 00:38:37.840
[Amit Varma]: on Twitter called Asim Ali, who's a journalist, I think he writes for various people where

00:38:37.840 --> 00:38:42.280
[Amit Varma]: he pointed out that if you are at a restaurant and you're mistaken for the waiter, you know,

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:46.160
[Amit Varma]: you immediately feel, you know, a sense of hurt, pride and humiliation.

00:38:46.160 --> 00:38:50.800
[Guest]: And the very fact that we do say something about all of this, that's what that's exactly

00:38:50.800 --> 00:38:51.800
[Guest]: what I'm saying.

00:38:51.800 --> 00:38:52.800
[Guest]: And we all feel it.

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:56.840
[Guest]: I mean, I was actually the bookstore, this happened just about last week.

00:38:56.840 --> 00:38:59.640
[Guest]: And somebody came behind me.

00:38:59.640 --> 00:39:03.480
[Guest]: And he tapped me and he said, where is the fiction section?

00:39:03.480 --> 00:39:04.640
[Guest]: For a second.

00:39:04.640 --> 00:39:05.640
[Guest]: I was like offended.

00:39:05.640 --> 00:39:06.640
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:39:06.640 --> 00:39:07.960
[Guest]: How dare you ask me that question?

00:39:07.960 --> 00:39:08.960
[Guest]: Right?

00:39:08.960 --> 00:39:11.360
[Guest]: Because then I turned around, he said, sorry, sir.

00:39:11.360 --> 00:39:16.480
[Guest]: But the fact is that somebody could presume that I'm just a person in the shop floor.

00:39:16.480 --> 00:39:17.760
[Guest]: Yeah, we are offended.

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:18.920
[Amit Varma]: We definitely are offended.

00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:20.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a sharp observation.

00:39:20.560 --> 00:39:21.820
[Amit Varma]: And you were talking about pizza.

00:39:21.820 --> 00:39:25.160
[Amit Varma]: So I have to tell you this before this, when we were at lunch, I told you about how much

00:39:25.160 --> 00:39:27.560
[Amit Varma]: I love TikTok and you should check it out.

00:39:27.560 --> 00:39:32.200
[Amit Varma]: So there is this nice TikTok video doing the rounds where, you know, this girl calls a

00:39:32.200 --> 00:39:37.560
[Amit Varma]: pizza hut, and she says, pizza hut, and voice at the other end says, yes.

00:39:37.560 --> 00:39:39.640
[Amit Varma]: And she says, apke paas pizza hai?

00:39:39.640 --> 00:39:41.580
[Amit Varma]: And the voice at the other end says, yes.

00:39:41.580 --> 00:39:46.240
[Amit Varma]: And then the girl gives this wistful look and says, maze hai yaar, maze hai, apke paas

00:39:46.240 --> 00:39:51.080
[Guest]: pizza hai, you know, which is both very funny, but it's got resonance with that.

00:39:51.080 --> 00:39:54.280
[Guest]: It completely has a resonance with that, yeah, definitely does.

00:39:54.280 --> 00:40:01.960
[Amit Varma]: And there's a sort of a lot of that happening on TikTok, but we'll sort of define it later.

00:40:01.960 --> 00:40:04.680
[Amit Varma]: You know, so just to kind of sum it up, there are two things happening.

00:40:04.680 --> 00:40:08.640
[Amit Varma]: One, as you described, is in the world of Carnatic music, one, as you described, that

00:40:08.640 --> 00:40:12.080
[Amit Varma]: there have traditionally been all of these entry barriers.

00:40:12.080 --> 00:40:17.960
[Amit Varma]: But also what is happening is that there is a denigration of other forms of art, and this

00:40:17.960 --> 00:40:22.440
[Amit Varma]: elevation of the classical into a fine art, like even I have grown up with this impression

00:40:22.440 --> 00:40:26.240
[Amit Varma]: that Hindustani classical and Carnatic are like the high forms of art.

00:40:26.240 --> 00:40:32.080
[Amit Varma]: And of course, in my case, they've intimidated me and said nahi main rock music sununga,

00:40:32.080 --> 00:40:33.880
[Amit Varma]: but that's the whole impression.

00:40:33.880 --> 00:40:39.640
[Amit Varma]: And as you also point out in your book of essays as well, before this, about art, we've

00:40:39.640 --> 00:40:45.720
[Amit Varma]: seen what, for example, in America, supposedly lower forms of art like jazz, gospel, hip

00:40:45.720 --> 00:40:49.880
[Amit Varma]: hop coming up, and you know, now jazz is pretty much considered, you know, you're supposed

00:40:49.880 --> 00:40:53.600
[Amit Varma]: to be classy, you're supposed to be a classy person, if you listen to jazz, and you're

00:40:53.600 --> 00:40:58.760
[Amit Varma]: very sophisticated, if you argue about who's better Miles Ravis or Coltrane, and all of

00:40:58.760 --> 00:40:59.760
[Amit Varma]: that happens.

00:40:59.760 --> 00:41:03.720
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, that is still a deep problem here, an entrenched problem.

00:41:03.720 --> 00:41:07.400
[Amit Varma]: So what's been your sort of experience of trying to do something about that?

00:41:07.400 --> 00:41:12.160
[Guest]: So initially, I was only thinking of Carnatic music, okay.

00:41:12.160 --> 00:41:17.120
[Guest]: So now retrospectively, I can see why that was problematic in the sense it was about

00:41:17.120 --> 00:41:23.760
[Guest]: this music, about the fact that I felt that this it lacked any kind of societal, political,

00:41:23.760 --> 00:41:30.640
[Guest]: ethicalness, and also the music needed to kind of breathe, so to speak.

00:41:30.640 --> 00:41:31.640
[Guest]: But it was still about the music.

00:41:31.640 --> 00:41:35.880
[Guest]: I mean, I had not really given a year to different cultures, this is the truth.

00:41:35.880 --> 00:41:37.360
[Guest]: And I think that happened slowly.

00:41:37.360 --> 00:41:39.520
[Guest]: And slowly, I started looking at different cultures.

00:41:39.520 --> 00:41:42.560
[Guest]: And that's when I started questioning that word classical.

00:41:42.560 --> 00:41:46.280
[Guest]: You know, some people may say classical is not an Indian word, it's but I think Shastri

00:41:46.280 --> 00:41:48.280
[Guest]: is as deeply problematic as classical.

00:41:48.280 --> 00:41:53.240
[Guest]: Absolutely, what is Shastri, who writes the Shastra, we can ask 100 questions about it.

00:41:53.240 --> 00:41:58.000
[Guest]: But I also believe that classical music in some way was superior.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:02.360
[Guest]: And to be able to appreciate, we've all been told this, that to appreciate classical music,

00:42:02.360 --> 00:42:06.280
[Guest]: you need to kind of a certain level of sophistication, you must have a year you must have kind of

00:42:06.280 --> 00:42:07.280
[Guest]: trained.

00:42:07.280 --> 00:42:11.040
[Guest]: So, you know, and I believed it, I honestly believed it.

00:42:11.040 --> 00:42:15.720
[Guest]: So what we have is this is representative of what Indian culture has been to the world.

00:42:15.720 --> 00:42:20.880
[Guest]: We always have the main shows being the classical world, and the side shows being some drum

00:42:20.880 --> 00:42:25.640
[Guest]: dance from Manipur or Nagaland Meghalaya, then some other thing, you know, that those

00:42:25.640 --> 00:42:30.800
[Guest]: are the diversity, they are the little crumbs we throw for diversity.

00:42:30.800 --> 00:42:35.240
[Guest]: But the main real representative has been these forms.

00:42:35.240 --> 00:42:40.000
[Guest]: We have represented India culturally like this in India and across the world.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:43.240
[Guest]: We treat those artists differently, we treat the classical artists differently, all this

00:42:43.240 --> 00:42:44.240
[Guest]: has been happening.

00:42:44.240 --> 00:42:49.960
[Guest]: But I think what happened was, when I started engaging with other art forms, you know, other

00:42:49.960 --> 00:42:55.680
[Guest]: forms, which were not within the classical tag, is when things started becoming clear.

00:42:55.680 --> 00:43:02.960
[Guest]: But the first person who put the seed in my head is a musicologist named Harold Powers.

00:43:02.960 --> 00:43:09.880
[Guest]: Powers studied Carnatic music, and actually did his PhD on Hindustani music.

00:43:09.880 --> 00:43:15.240
[Guest]: And he was towards the end of his life, and he visited my home, and I was much younger

00:43:15.240 --> 00:43:19.320
[Guest]: and very casually asked Harold, so Harold, what's the difference between classical and

00:43:19.320 --> 00:43:20.840
[Guest]: folk?

00:43:20.840 --> 00:43:23.840
[Guest]: And he didn't bat an eyelid, he said, very simple.

00:43:23.840 --> 00:43:29.480
[Guest]: As an art form goes up the ladder of society, it moves from becoming folk to classical.

00:43:29.480 --> 00:43:32.760
[Guest]: And when he first told me that, I thought that was rubbish.

00:43:32.760 --> 00:43:37.600
[Guest]: Okay, but I'm happy that that quote never went out of my head.

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:38.600
[Guest]: It stayed with me.

00:43:38.600 --> 00:43:40.680
[Guest]: And it kept bothering me.

00:43:40.680 --> 00:43:42.040
[Guest]: You know, how can you say this?

00:43:42.040 --> 00:43:46.560
[Guest]: Are you saying there's nothing intrinsic about the art that makes it more special?

00:43:46.560 --> 00:43:49.520
[Guest]: I mean, I sing it, it has to be more special.

00:43:49.520 --> 00:43:55.380
[Guest]: But when I started then investigating it, you see that he's absolutely right.

00:43:55.380 --> 00:43:57.120
[Guest]: He just nailed it.

00:43:57.120 --> 00:44:01.640
[Guest]: It's a question of who is participating in the creation of that art?

00:44:01.640 --> 00:44:02.640
[Guest]: Who's creating it?

00:44:02.640 --> 00:44:03.680
[Guest]: Who's listening to it?

00:44:03.680 --> 00:44:07.040
[Guest]: And that defines whether you call it classical or you take the world classical across the

00:44:07.040 --> 00:44:13.240
[Guest]: globe, everywhere in the world, it is the cultural elite who are defining the classical.

00:44:13.240 --> 00:44:15.000
[Guest]: So there has to be something about it.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:16.440
[Guest]: So this was the first thing.

00:44:16.440 --> 00:44:20.560
[Guest]: The other thing is when I started engaging with art forms which were not considered classical,

00:44:20.560 --> 00:44:25.800
[Guest]: and I will never forget one experience, I went to a little village near Chennai.

00:44:25.800 --> 00:44:28.960
[Guest]: And this is art form called Katte Koothu.

00:44:28.960 --> 00:44:36.720
[Guest]: And incredible artist Mr. Rajagopal, and he runs a school for this art form, and I performed.

00:44:36.720 --> 00:44:40.680
[Guest]: At that point, I was engaging with art forms, but I think the snoot in me had not gone yet.

00:44:40.680 --> 00:44:41.680
[Guest]: You know, you still feel something.

00:44:41.680 --> 00:44:42.800
[Guest]: I mean, this has to be special.

00:44:42.800 --> 00:44:43.800
[Guest]: Come on.

00:44:43.800 --> 00:44:45.960
[Guest]: And I remember I performed that day.

00:44:45.960 --> 00:44:49.120
[Guest]: So I was performing in an area which was alien.

00:44:49.120 --> 00:44:51.720
[Guest]: I was culturally alien to the people there.

00:44:51.720 --> 00:44:52.720
[Guest]: Okay.

00:44:52.720 --> 00:44:54.960
[Guest]: It was extremely intimidating.

00:44:54.960 --> 00:44:57.520
[Guest]: Classical musicians never usually do that.

00:44:57.520 --> 00:45:00.480
[Guest]: There were about 1000 villagers from across the villages.

00:45:00.480 --> 00:45:02.960
[Guest]: And then was a Koothu performance.

00:45:02.960 --> 00:45:06.280
[Guest]: Now the Koothu unfolded.

00:45:06.280 --> 00:45:08.800
[Guest]: I had no clue what was going on.

00:45:08.800 --> 00:45:13.960
[Guest]: Every person sitting there knew every nuance, every little joke.

00:45:13.960 --> 00:45:18.520
[Guest]: And I'm thinking to myself, who is the sophisticated here?

00:45:18.520 --> 00:45:24.080
[Guest]: Me or the 1000 villagers who I will consider uneducated, crude, you know, these words called

00:45:24.080 --> 00:45:30.240
[Guest]: ethnic, all these words that we use, you know, raw, real, in aesthetic senses, when we use

00:45:30.240 --> 00:45:32.600
[Guest]: that word, it's not a compliment.

00:45:32.600 --> 00:45:33.600
[Guest]: Let's be very clear.

00:45:33.600 --> 00:45:35.840
[Guest]: It's not a compliment.

00:45:35.840 --> 00:45:40.760
[Guest]: And that's when it hit me that this whole notion of sophistication, complexity, subtlety

00:45:40.760 --> 00:45:43.840
[Guest]: is very specific to every art form.

00:45:43.840 --> 00:45:49.000
[Guest]: If I'm able to dive into another culture, then I will feel it in that way.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:54.560
[Guest]: And that's when this whole thing, like crumbled, that these words are only social constructions,

00:45:54.560 --> 00:45:59.320
[Guest]: they're political constructions, which is why even if, you know, jazz is considered

00:45:59.320 --> 00:46:03.280
[Guest]: this profound thing, it's never called classical.

00:46:03.280 --> 00:46:04.280
[Guest]: Why?

00:46:04.280 --> 00:46:06.680
[Guest]: Because it ticks every box that you want to take.

00:46:06.680 --> 00:46:07.760
[Guest]: It's complicated.

00:46:07.760 --> 00:46:08.760
[Guest]: It's difficult to understand.

00:46:08.760 --> 00:46:11.720
[Guest]: Even if you read 100 books, you can do an online course on jazz, you still won't understand.

00:46:11.720 --> 00:46:13.640
[Guest]: I won't still understand it.

00:46:13.640 --> 00:46:16.200
[Guest]: But it still is not called classical.

00:46:16.200 --> 00:46:17.880
[Guest]: Classical is still white man's music.

00:46:17.880 --> 00:46:19.640
[Guest]: There is something to it.

00:46:19.640 --> 00:46:23.960
[Guest]: So that's when I realized that this is not an aesthetic point.

00:46:23.960 --> 00:46:25.840
[Guest]: This is not a musical point.

00:46:25.840 --> 00:46:31.400
[Guest]: This is purely about people and about society and about politics of it.

00:46:31.400 --> 00:46:35.400
[Guest]: When you change the politics, something else may become, in fact, you've got a very nice

00:46:35.400 --> 00:46:39.120
[Amit Varma]: line in your book, which I'll just read out, which, you know, is in the context of North

00:46:39.120 --> 00:46:41.960
[Amit Varma]: Chennai, where all the Dalit slave and all of that.

00:46:41.960 --> 00:46:46.600
[Amit Varma]: And your sentence goes, quote, culture is not a word commonly associated with North

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:51.520
[Amit Varma]: Chennai, simply because this culture is not that of the upper caste, stop quote, which

00:46:51.520 --> 00:46:54.920
[Amit Varma]: kind of says everything is then.

00:46:54.920 --> 00:46:58.640
[Amit Varma]: And is it a fair analogy to say that what you're talking about, you know, you're trained

00:46:58.640 --> 00:47:03.360
[Amit Varma]: in Carnatic music, so you see all the sophistication and all that, but is it a fair analogy to

00:47:03.360 --> 00:47:07.840
[Amit Varma]: say that it's like you're being really good at a language and a language which you know

00:47:07.840 --> 00:47:12.720
[Amit Varma]: nothing of sounds like noise to you till you actually take the effort to immerse yourself?

00:47:12.720 --> 00:47:17.440
[Amit Varma]: And at some point in the book, you've spoken about noise becoming music, you know, and

00:47:17.440 --> 00:47:19.360
[Guest]: the analogy is very true.

00:47:19.360 --> 00:47:20.360
[Guest]: That's what it is.

00:47:20.360 --> 00:47:21.360
[Guest]: Right.

00:47:21.360 --> 00:47:25.400
[Guest]: And what we should also realize how difficult it is for us to actually move to another culture

00:47:25.400 --> 00:47:30.600
[Guest]: or shall we dive into another culture, it's we're always carrying something with us, okay.

00:47:30.600 --> 00:47:34.200
[Guest]: And because we always carry something, it's so much harder to do.

00:47:34.200 --> 00:47:37.680
[Guest]: And so really, to be immerse yourself in multiple cultures is not an easy thing.

00:47:37.680 --> 00:47:39.560
[Guest]: And probably we're all never going to be able to do it.

00:47:39.560 --> 00:47:43.440
[Guest]: But even if you do it once with something, then we realize about this whole idea of how

00:47:43.440 --> 00:47:44.840
[Guest]: can noise become music.

00:47:44.840 --> 00:47:49.520
[Guest]: So, you know, I'll give you a very, very Indian example.

00:47:49.520 --> 00:47:53.480
[Guest]: Many Hindustani musicians think that Carnatic musicians sing Besur.

00:47:53.480 --> 00:47:59.640
[Guest]: We are not singing Besur because the movement that they hear is Besur is actually a technical

00:47:59.640 --> 00:48:02.680
[Guest]: required movement in Carnatic music.

00:48:02.680 --> 00:48:06.240
[Guest]: Now, is it off tune or not?

00:48:06.240 --> 00:48:08.960
[Guest]: Is there an absolute answer to the question?

00:48:08.960 --> 00:48:10.440
[Guest]: When is somebody singing in pitch?

00:48:10.440 --> 00:48:13.840
[Guest]: Even a simple idea like that is so complicated.

00:48:13.840 --> 00:48:20.480
[Guest]: To your ear it may seem off pitch, to my ear, musically, that's in pitch.

00:48:20.480 --> 00:48:24.160
[Guest]: So I mean, this is a classic and then listen to Makhan music.

00:48:24.160 --> 00:48:26.960
[Guest]: I mean, their movements sound Besur to me.

00:48:26.960 --> 00:48:30.040
[Guest]: All of us sound Besur to the Western classical musician.

00:48:30.040 --> 00:48:31.600
[Guest]: So who is singing off tune?

00:48:31.600 --> 00:48:32.600
[Guest]: We don't know.

00:48:32.600 --> 00:48:34.000
[Guest]: That's what I'm saying.

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:35.760
[Guest]: It's so specific.

00:48:35.760 --> 00:48:40.480
[Guest]: So and this is very important, not just musically to understand, to culturally understand, you

00:48:40.480 --> 00:48:41.480
[Guest]: know.

00:48:41.480 --> 00:48:46.360
[Guest]: So it happened to me when I heard so many kinds of music first, I thought it was just

00:48:46.360 --> 00:48:47.360
[Guest]: noisy.

00:48:47.360 --> 00:48:48.360
[Guest]: This is loud.

00:48:48.360 --> 00:48:51.560
[Guest]: But now I feel the music inside sometimes.

00:48:51.560 --> 00:48:55.640
[Amit Varma]: So is it a journey then you then make from this intellectual understanding that no, this

00:48:55.640 --> 00:49:00.080
[Amit Varma]: kind of music is also legit in its own way to an emotional understanding where you can

00:49:00.080 --> 00:49:03.000
[Amit Varma]: just sit back and enjoy that music and it doesn't sound Besur anymore?

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:05.600
[Guest]: I think that's the most important part.

00:49:05.600 --> 00:49:09.800
[Guest]: The intellectual understanding doesn't even scratch the surface.

00:49:09.800 --> 00:49:14.240
[Guest]: The fact is that none of us are going to change because we comprehend something or we believe

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:15.800
[Guest]: that intellectually that's right.

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:16.800
[Guest]: We have to feel the music.

00:49:16.800 --> 00:49:17.800
[Guest]: You have to feel it.

00:49:17.800 --> 00:49:20.200
[Guest]: I mean, you have to feel the people.

00:49:20.200 --> 00:49:21.200
[Guest]: That's the message.

00:49:21.200 --> 00:49:22.200
[Guest]: You feel the people.

00:49:22.200 --> 00:49:23.200
[Guest]: You feel the dancer.

00:49:23.200 --> 00:49:24.200
[Guest]: You feel the culture.

00:49:24.200 --> 00:49:25.200
[Guest]: You have to feel the streets.

00:49:25.200 --> 00:49:26.200
[Guest]: You have to feel that you should taste the food.

00:49:26.200 --> 00:49:27.200
[Guest]: You have to.

00:49:27.200 --> 00:49:28.200
[Guest]: I mean, it's all that.

00:49:28.200 --> 00:49:29.200
[Guest]: Right.

00:49:29.200 --> 00:49:34.200
[Guest]: And then somewhere, at least momentarily, you feel you're part of it.

00:49:34.200 --> 00:49:37.680
[Guest]: And then that drumbeat is right at the bottom of your stomach.

00:49:37.680 --> 00:49:38.680
[Amit Varma]: And that's happened to you.

00:49:38.680 --> 00:49:39.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:49:39.680 --> 00:49:40.680
[Guest]: Your smile.

00:49:40.680 --> 00:49:41.680
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:49:41.680 --> 00:49:43.520
[Amit Varma]: I mean, and that moment is incredibly emotional.

00:49:43.520 --> 00:49:45.480
[Amit Varma]: And does it then change the way you look at your own music?

00:49:45.480 --> 00:49:47.320
[Amit Varma]: Are you taking some of that into your music?

00:49:47.320 --> 00:49:48.320
[Guest]: So yeah, it does.

00:49:48.320 --> 00:49:50.880
[Guest]: I mean, it does change the way you hear.

00:49:50.880 --> 00:49:54.640
[Guest]: I mean, you often say that the music is not in the singing or playing.

00:49:54.640 --> 00:49:55.920
[Guest]: It's in the listening.

00:49:55.920 --> 00:49:58.800
[Guest]: The painting is not in the brush.

00:49:58.800 --> 00:49:59.800
[Amit Varma]: It's in the scene.

00:49:59.800 --> 00:50:03.700
[Amit Varma]: There's a similar thing I like to say that, you know, great art is not about talent.

00:50:03.700 --> 00:50:04.700
[Amit Varma]: It's about judgment.

00:50:04.700 --> 00:50:05.700
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:50:05.700 --> 00:50:06.700
[Guest]: Separate thing.

00:50:06.700 --> 00:50:07.700
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:50:07.700 --> 00:50:11.400
[Guest]: But I'm saying that, you know, when you start feeling it, then you hear differently.

00:50:11.400 --> 00:50:14.280
[Guest]: You know, the lines kind of disappear, you know.

00:50:14.280 --> 00:50:15.280
[Guest]: This is right.

00:50:15.280 --> 00:50:16.480
[Guest]: This is not right.

00:50:16.480 --> 00:50:19.920
[Guest]: So kind of understand context for this technique, you know, and what are the things you can

00:50:19.920 --> 00:50:20.920
[Guest]: judge?

00:50:20.920 --> 00:50:23.080
[Guest]: I mean, I mean, how do you separate things?

00:50:23.080 --> 00:50:25.000
[Guest]: These things become far more fluid.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:31.160
[Guest]: And I can tell you the way I hear Carnatic music, which is musically my home, is entirely

00:50:31.160 --> 00:50:32.160
[Guest]: different.

00:50:32.160 --> 00:50:33.320
[Guest]: It's entirely different.

00:50:33.320 --> 00:50:34.600
[Guest]: I hear it differently.

00:50:34.600 --> 00:50:36.520
[Guest]: I know I hear it differently.

00:50:36.520 --> 00:50:38.600
[Guest]: I don't look for when I sing.

00:50:38.600 --> 00:50:44.800
[Guest]: I don't look for the things that I was looking for in my own music anymore.

00:50:44.800 --> 00:50:46.240
[Guest]: I know I'm not looking for it.

00:50:46.240 --> 00:50:49.840
[Guest]: I don't care a damn about so many things that I cared so much about in the music that I

00:50:49.840 --> 00:50:50.840
[Amit Varma]: sang.

00:50:50.840 --> 00:50:56.600
[Amit Varma]: So as a performer, where is then the intersection between your new way of hearing this music

00:50:56.600 --> 00:51:01.720
[Amit Varma]: and you know, how your understanding of your own music has evolved and how the audience

00:51:01.720 --> 00:51:05.240
[Amit Varma]: is because it's still the same audience and you still want to push the buttons and get

00:51:05.240 --> 00:51:06.240
[Guest]: the applause.

00:51:06.240 --> 00:51:07.240
[Guest]: So.

00:51:07.240 --> 00:51:14.600
[Guest]: So the thing is that I do like to hope that I push less buttons now, but nevertheless,

00:51:14.600 --> 00:51:16.520
[Guest]: actually that has been an interesting journey itself.

00:51:16.520 --> 00:51:17.520
[Guest]: There are two parts.

00:51:17.520 --> 00:51:21.120
[Guest]: The one is that when things started changing the way I performed, the people who thought

00:51:21.120 --> 00:51:26.720
[Guest]: that I was committing blasphemy, that I was killing the art form, that I was disrespecting

00:51:26.720 --> 00:51:27.720
[Guest]: tradition.

00:51:27.720 --> 00:51:33.320
[Guest]: A lot of people just disliked what I was doing.

00:51:33.320 --> 00:51:40.720
[Guest]: And though I was singing all within the structures within the environment and this and what I

00:51:40.720 --> 00:51:42.640
[Guest]: want to say is also tough for me.

00:51:42.640 --> 00:51:47.160
[Guest]: So again, you know, you may believe in something, but when you actually do it, it may not still

00:51:47.160 --> 00:51:48.320
[Guest]: be you.

00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:50.600
[Guest]: It takes some time because before it becomes you.

00:51:50.600 --> 00:51:53.760
[Guest]: So as the audience was struggling, I was also struggling, right?

00:51:53.760 --> 00:51:57.260
[Guest]: Because you're kind of demolding yourself in some way.

00:51:57.260 --> 00:51:59.920
[Guest]: And that process can be very difficult because you're grappling.

00:51:59.920 --> 00:52:01.200
[Guest]: You have nothing to follow.

00:52:01.200 --> 00:52:02.380
[Guest]: You don't know what you're doing.

00:52:02.380 --> 00:52:06.120
[Guest]: You just know you just have to get out of this and your problems are visible only to

00:52:06.120 --> 00:52:07.120
[Guest]: you.

00:52:07.120 --> 00:52:08.120
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:52:08.120 --> 00:52:12.640
[Guest]: And because of the discomfort, the audience goes through incredible discomfort, enormous

00:52:12.640 --> 00:52:14.480
[Guest]: difficulty to understand what is this guy doing?

00:52:14.480 --> 00:52:18.960
[Guest]: I'm going through discomfort saying, you know, does this answer what I'm asking for or am

00:52:18.960 --> 00:52:19.960
[Guest]: I asking for?

00:52:19.960 --> 00:52:20.960
[Guest]: What am I asking for?

00:52:20.960 --> 00:52:21.960
[Guest]: I don't even know that.

00:52:21.960 --> 00:52:25.920
[Guest]: So there is this great amount of churn that's happening to everybody who's participating

00:52:25.920 --> 00:52:26.920
[Guest]: in this.

00:52:26.920 --> 00:52:27.920
[Guest]: Right.

00:52:27.920 --> 00:52:28.920
[Guest]: That's one part.

00:52:28.920 --> 00:52:34.460
[Guest]: And then there is, there is the whole other idea of how does this respond to the politics

00:52:34.460 --> 00:52:37.120
[Guest]: that you're talking about, to the social.

00:52:37.120 --> 00:52:39.240
[Guest]: So you know, things like, where do I sit?

00:52:39.240 --> 00:52:40.760
[Guest]: Things change the way I sat on stage.

00:52:40.760 --> 00:52:43.680
[Guest]: I completely changed the way we sat on stage.

00:52:43.680 --> 00:52:49.040
[Guest]: And then the interesting thing happened is I started also questioning space, place.

00:52:49.040 --> 00:52:54.840
[Guest]: So I, you know, sang in open spaces where the audience was not the traditional audience.

00:52:54.840 --> 00:53:00.200
[Guest]: I've sung at a beach when there were six kids listening to me with their hands in their

00:53:00.200 --> 00:53:02.360
[Guest]: ears saying, this is awful.

00:53:02.360 --> 00:53:04.160
[Guest]: To them, mine was noise.

00:53:04.160 --> 00:53:06.140
[Guest]: How does an artist react to that?

00:53:06.140 --> 00:53:11.400
[Guest]: You know, singing in a bus, singing to people that have no clue, you know, they're different

00:53:11.400 --> 00:53:12.400
[Guest]: culture entirely.

00:53:12.400 --> 00:53:16.560
[Guest]: In my city, just one kilometer away from the suburb where everybody will applaud everything

00:53:16.560 --> 00:53:17.640
[Guest]: I'm singing.

00:53:17.640 --> 00:53:21.040
[Guest]: One kilometer later, these people think this is noisy stuff, man, ask them to stop.

00:53:21.040 --> 00:53:22.680
[Guest]: So what does that do to me?

00:53:22.680 --> 00:53:24.440
[Guest]: You know, that also changed me.

00:53:24.440 --> 00:53:27.040
[Guest]: That also changed the way I was, I was thinking I was singing.

00:53:27.040 --> 00:53:30.000
[Guest]: So it's multiple things involved here.

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:35.480
[Guest]: One is that internal musical rediscovery, hopefully.

00:53:35.480 --> 00:53:38.280
[Guest]: Then there is the idea of place and the idea of people.

00:53:38.280 --> 00:53:40.280
[Guest]: All these three are at play.

00:53:40.280 --> 00:53:45.080
[Guest]: And which is why I think all these three need to be at play for art to remain true.

00:53:45.080 --> 00:53:48.640
[Guest]: You know, you can say that I'm making art, which is not elitist, but if you're just going

00:53:48.640 --> 00:53:52.000
[Guest]: to make it and make it, make sure that it's only in a gallery where a few people can enter.

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:53.360
[Guest]: It's still that.

00:53:53.360 --> 00:53:56.440
[Guest]: So can you deconstruct a gallery?

00:53:56.440 --> 00:53:58.800
[Guest]: Not only deconstruct your art, but deconstruct the gallery.

00:53:58.800 --> 00:54:03.200
[Guest]: These, you know, also the kind of people, the moment you do this, it's all fluid, which

00:54:03.200 --> 00:54:06.920
[Guest]: means it's mayhem, which means you really don't know what's going to come out of all

00:54:06.920 --> 00:54:07.920
[Guest]: this.

00:54:07.920 --> 00:54:13.160
[Guest]: You know, when I sang on a, on a moving public transport bus, it was the most incredible

00:54:13.160 --> 00:54:15.040
[Guest]: experience by the end of it.

00:54:15.040 --> 00:54:16.040
[Guest]: It's a moving bus.

00:54:16.040 --> 00:54:17.040
[Amit Varma]: How did that happen?

00:54:17.040 --> 00:54:20.560
[Guest]: So this is part of many projects that we are involved in, right?

00:54:20.560 --> 00:54:25.600
[Guest]: So as we moved from, as I move from not just talking about Carnatic music, the fact that

00:54:25.600 --> 00:54:30.240
[Guest]: we are looking at different cultures and each are occupying different spaces and also at

00:54:30.240 --> 00:54:36.440
[Guest]: a different hierarchical position, how do we create little contestation?

00:54:36.440 --> 00:54:38.960
[Guest]: You need to create contestation between different cultures.

00:54:38.960 --> 00:54:43.440
[Guest]: You need to allow them to kind of come in, you know, kind of bang each other and some

00:54:43.440 --> 00:54:45.640
[Guest]: amount of equality, at least for some time.

00:54:45.640 --> 00:54:50.040
[Guest]: So one of the things we said is, why don't we just take the Carnatics and the classicals

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:53.120
[Guest]: onto a bus, this public transport bus.

00:54:53.120 --> 00:55:00.000
[Guest]: So we call it, now it's called MTC, I think it used to be called PTC when we were young.

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:01.960
[Guest]: And we, I was not going to sing.

00:55:01.960 --> 00:55:03.440
[Guest]: So we did this relay of music.

00:55:03.440 --> 00:55:09.880
[Guest]: So we had not just Carnatic music, but we had some Tamil rock, we had Carnatic, we had

00:55:09.880 --> 00:55:12.800
[Guest]: some Naam Sankirtan, all happening like a relay.

00:55:12.800 --> 00:55:16.800
[Guest]: So these musicians, all young musicians had to board the bus at different bus stops.

00:55:16.800 --> 00:55:19.960
[Guest]: And they hand over the baton to the other person, it was fun.

00:55:19.960 --> 00:55:22.600
[Guest]: So I said, the first time we did it, I said, I want to check out how it is.

00:55:22.600 --> 00:55:23.600
[Guest]: Was it recorded, video shooting?

00:55:23.600 --> 00:55:25.600
[Guest]: There's a video on YouTube of it, of me singing.

00:55:25.600 --> 00:55:26.840
[Amit Varma]: That'll be linked from the show.

00:55:26.840 --> 00:55:30.760
[Guest]: So what I did was I just got onto the bus in one of the bus stops, I was just going

00:55:30.760 --> 00:55:32.200
[Guest]: to check it out.

00:55:32.200 --> 00:55:33.680
[Guest]: But these young guys said, you have to sing.

00:55:33.680 --> 00:55:36.120
[Guest]: I mean, how can you not sing?

00:55:36.120 --> 00:55:37.120
[Guest]: It was unbelievable.

00:55:37.120 --> 00:55:45.160
[Guest]: I mean, just the experience, you see, it was unbelievable because I was completely exposed.

00:55:45.160 --> 00:55:47.280
[Guest]: I was entirely vulnerable.

00:55:47.280 --> 00:55:52.280
[Guest]: I couldn't push any button, you couldn't push any button, that's the point.

00:55:52.280 --> 00:55:54.720
[Guest]: Once you know your audience, you push a button.

00:55:54.720 --> 00:55:56.640
[Guest]: Once you know your environment, you can push a button.

00:55:56.640 --> 00:55:59.360
[Guest]: You know the place, the people, the content, everything.

00:55:59.360 --> 00:56:02.480
[Guest]: If everything is removed, you can't push any button.

00:56:02.480 --> 00:56:04.840
[Guest]: You don't know whether the person is going to hate what you're doing.

00:56:04.840 --> 00:56:06.120
[Guest]: You don't know if you're going to get acceptability.

00:56:06.120 --> 00:56:07.120
[Guest]: You want to be accepted.

00:56:07.120 --> 00:56:08.120
[Guest]: You're an artist.

00:56:08.120 --> 00:56:09.120
[Guest]: You want acceptance.

00:56:09.120 --> 00:56:10.120
[Guest]: You want the applause.

00:56:10.120 --> 00:56:11.120
[Guest]: But you have no clue how to get it, man.

00:56:11.120 --> 00:56:13.760
[Guest]: And it was, it was exhilarating.

00:56:13.760 --> 00:56:16.880
[Guest]: I have, it was also panic, you're scared.

00:56:16.880 --> 00:56:21.200
[Guest]: You know, by the time I did this, I've been in the field for what, two decades.

00:56:21.200 --> 00:56:24.120
[Guest]: I've never been scared of being on stage, but that day I was terrified.

00:56:24.120 --> 00:56:27.320
[Guest]: I was terrified when I sang on the beach for the first time, because I didn't know who's

00:56:27.320 --> 00:56:28.320
[Guest]: going to, what's going to happen.

00:56:28.320 --> 00:56:29.320
[Guest]: Am I going to be discarded?

00:56:29.320 --> 00:56:30.320
[Guest]: You know, is somebody going to say, stop?

00:56:30.320 --> 00:56:35.520
[Guest]: Is somebody going to scream, for example, say, hey, please stop.

00:56:35.520 --> 00:56:36.520
[Guest]: Get out.

00:56:36.520 --> 00:56:38.320
[Guest]: I mean, so on the bus, this happened.

00:56:38.320 --> 00:56:39.320
[Guest]: I'll never forget.

00:56:39.320 --> 00:56:43.560
[Guest]: It was the last leg when these young guys said, you have to sing.

00:56:43.560 --> 00:56:45.360
[Guest]: So I belted out a song.

00:56:45.360 --> 00:56:51.320
[Guest]: And I remember as we came to the terminus, bus terminus, everybody on the roads were

00:56:51.320 --> 00:56:53.480
[Guest]: wondering where music was coming from, right?

00:56:53.480 --> 00:56:58.040
[Guest]: And there was this man who was drunk and he started dancing.

00:56:58.040 --> 00:57:02.760
[Guest]: He was on the road and he's like walking with the bus dancing.

00:57:02.760 --> 00:57:03.760
[Guest]: Is this in the video?

00:57:03.760 --> 00:57:05.080
[Guest]: I don't think that's in the video.

00:57:05.080 --> 00:57:06.080
[Amit Varma]: Unfortunately.

00:57:06.080 --> 00:57:07.080
[Amit Varma]: We'll have to imagine it.

00:57:07.080 --> 00:57:08.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:57:08.080 --> 00:57:13.080
[Guest]: And I was like, this is the most beautiful connection I've made.

00:57:13.080 --> 00:57:18.360
[Guest]: You know, we belong to very different worlds, very different ideas.

00:57:18.360 --> 00:57:20.320
[Guest]: He just heard the music and danced.

00:57:20.320 --> 00:57:23.520
[Guest]: And because he's drunk now, he'll forget the connection the next morning.

00:57:23.520 --> 00:57:24.520
[Guest]: I wish I was drunk.

00:57:24.520 --> 00:57:26.520
[Amit Varma]: Maybe they would have leveled it off.

00:57:26.520 --> 00:57:32.640
[Amit Varma]: How did your traditional audience, what you've called the 25,000 Brahmins who congregate every

00:57:32.640 --> 00:57:39.240
[Amit Varma]: December in Chennai, how did your traditional audience react to you in light of the politics

00:57:39.240 --> 00:57:41.800
[Amit Varma]: that you were now expressing?

00:57:41.800 --> 00:57:43.720
[Amit Varma]: React to your music in light of the politics?

00:57:43.720 --> 00:57:47.640
[Guest]: You had two or three different reactions.

00:57:47.640 --> 00:57:52.960
[Guest]: Of course, my politics is and was very disconcerting.

00:57:52.960 --> 00:57:54.480
[Guest]: And I can understand why it is.

00:57:54.480 --> 00:57:57.560
[Guest]: I mean, there's no point, I can't pontificate because it's true.

00:57:57.560 --> 00:58:00.320
[Guest]: I mean, I guess 20 years ago, I would have probably also looked at somebody who was doing

00:58:00.320 --> 00:58:01.800
[Guest]: this and what the hell is he doing?

00:58:01.800 --> 00:58:05.120
[Guest]: You know, so I can understand it at some level.

00:58:05.120 --> 00:58:10.040
[Guest]: So there were people who either said, I've had people sending me an email saying I've

00:58:10.040 --> 00:58:12.560
[Guest]: thrown all your CDs.

00:58:12.560 --> 00:58:14.320
[Guest]: I don't have any CD of yours anymore.

00:58:14.320 --> 00:58:19.680
[Guest]: You've disrespected Hindu gods, you've disrespected Indian culture, therefore, I don't listen

00:58:19.680 --> 00:58:20.680
[Amit Varma]: to you anymore.

00:58:20.680 --> 00:58:21.680
[Amit Varma]: I've had that.

00:58:21.680 --> 00:58:23.160
[Guest]: They can't do that anymore because you can't throw MP3s.

00:58:23.160 --> 00:58:24.160
[Guest]: Yeah, I know.

00:58:24.160 --> 00:58:26.360
[Amit Varma]: I'm on YouTube, they're stuck with me.

00:58:26.360 --> 00:58:32.200
[Guest]: So they've had people who have actually even now many people say, how is this guy who produces

00:58:32.200 --> 00:58:35.120
[Guest]: such divine music speak such filth?

00:58:35.120 --> 00:58:37.000
[Guest]: I've had many people say that.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:38.000
[Guest]: In so many words.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:39.000
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly.

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:40.000
[Guest]: Those words actually.

00:58:40.000 --> 00:58:42.480
[Guest]: I'm not even paraphrasing.

00:58:42.480 --> 00:58:48.720
[Guest]: So how can he be so filthy and say all these horrible things, but when he sings, it's divine.

00:58:48.720 --> 00:58:50.000
[Guest]: You have that.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:53.720
[Guest]: And you have also the other end of people who have never heard me, who listen to me

00:58:53.720 --> 00:58:59.280
[Guest]: because of my politics, usually younger, younger people, and many people who don't belong within

00:58:59.280 --> 00:59:04.080
[Guest]: the Carnatic world, who have now said, you know, I want to listen to this music because

00:59:04.080 --> 00:59:09.720
[Guest]: I find it interesting that you can actually challenge it from being inside, which they

00:59:09.720 --> 00:59:11.200
[Guest]: never thought was possible.

00:59:11.200 --> 00:59:14.120
[Guest]: So you have different shades of all this happening.

00:59:14.120 --> 00:59:16.480
[Guest]: So the power structures are uncomfortable with me.

00:59:16.480 --> 00:59:19.960
[Guest]: But the fact of the matter is, I'm doing all this because I'm powerful.

00:59:19.960 --> 00:59:22.960
[Guest]: So let's not run away from the fact that if I did this 20 years ago, I would have been

00:59:22.960 --> 00:59:26.280
[Guest]: thrown and nobody would, we wouldn't be having this conversation.

00:59:26.280 --> 00:59:32.840
[Guest]: So the fact also is the fact that I can, I can handle all this is because I know I have

00:59:32.840 --> 00:59:33.840
[Guest]: the...

00:59:33.840 --> 00:59:35.360
[Guest]: But you have also been deplatformed and stuff.

00:59:35.360 --> 00:59:36.360
[Guest]: Oh, yeah, of course.

00:59:36.360 --> 00:59:38.000
[Guest]: There's been many concerts cancelled.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:39.000
[Guest]: It's happened in India.

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:40.000
[Guest]: It's happened in the US.

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:41.600
[Guest]: It's happened in the US, wow.

00:59:41.600 --> 00:59:42.600
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:59:42.600 --> 00:59:46.320
[Guest]: So this was about a couple of years, 2018, when actually some colleagues of mine were

00:59:46.320 --> 00:59:50.720
[Guest]: targeted for singing Christian themes in Carnatic music.

00:59:50.720 --> 00:59:52.240
[Guest]: And they were really bullied.

00:59:52.240 --> 00:59:57.840
[Guest]: And especially the women, I mean, the trolling was just, you know, I can't even quote the

00:59:57.840 --> 01:00:02.500
[Guest]: kind of things that were said, and I really pissed me off.

01:00:02.500 --> 01:00:04.040
[Guest]: And there was some guy who said he'll break my legs also.

01:00:04.040 --> 01:00:06.200
[Guest]: I mean, that also happened, but that is not so important.

01:00:06.200 --> 01:00:10.720
[Guest]: So I put out saying, a video saying, I'm going to release a song on Allah and Jesus every

01:00:10.720 --> 01:00:12.760
[Guest]: month in Carnatic music.

01:00:12.760 --> 01:00:18.360
[Guest]: And it was done as a protest, saying that nobody has a right to tell me what I can sing

01:00:18.360 --> 01:00:19.360
[Guest]: about.

01:00:19.360 --> 01:00:22.680
[Guest]: And this music doesn't belong to any community, any religion.

01:00:22.680 --> 01:00:26.560
[Guest]: And when I did that, I was just going to the US on a tour.

01:00:26.560 --> 01:00:31.800
[Guest]: And the concert was at Washington DC at the Shiva Vishnu temple where I've sung Amti number

01:00:31.800 --> 01:00:33.480
[Guest]: of times.

01:00:33.480 --> 01:00:35.360
[Guest]: And they cancelled the concert.

01:00:35.360 --> 01:00:41.400
[Guest]: And they said that they have been threatened by right wing groups.

01:00:41.400 --> 01:00:45.040
[Guest]: And there was this huge blog this woman wrote about how they celebrated that the concert

01:00:45.040 --> 01:00:46.040
[Guest]: was cancelled.

01:00:46.040 --> 01:00:49.360
[Guest]: And I was shown my place and that Indian culture was protected.

01:00:49.360 --> 01:00:52.080
[Guest]: And I understand recently that she's going to stand for election to something that the

01:00:52.080 --> 01:00:53.080
[Guest]: same woman.

01:00:53.080 --> 01:00:54.080
[Guest]: That's very interesting.

01:00:54.080 --> 01:00:55.760
[Guest]: So I think it's Trump land.

01:00:55.760 --> 01:00:58.840
[Guest]: But yeah, so that's happened too.

01:00:58.840 --> 01:01:01.520
[Guest]: But I must say the positive of that, that happened.

01:01:01.520 --> 01:01:07.760
[Guest]: But then a group got together on the very same day, same time, a concert in DC did happen

01:01:07.760 --> 01:01:09.240
[Guest]: as a as an answer.

01:01:09.240 --> 01:01:10.640
[Guest]: So that too happened.

01:01:10.640 --> 01:01:11.920
[Guest]: Yes, it was cancelled.

01:01:11.920 --> 01:01:15.160
[Guest]: But there are also people who came together and said this cannot happen.

01:01:15.160 --> 01:01:16.160
[Guest]: And we will do the concert.

01:01:16.160 --> 01:01:18.160
[Amit Varma]: So there are both sides to it.

01:01:18.160 --> 01:01:21.560
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that it's not just casteism.

01:01:21.560 --> 01:01:25.200
[Amit Varma]: There is of course, you know, the sexism is there in the sense women cannot play the mridangam

01:01:25.200 --> 01:01:26.440
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

01:01:26.440 --> 01:01:27.440
[Amit Varma]: But there's also racism.

01:01:27.440 --> 01:01:32.280
[Amit Varma]: For example, you know, Sudha Raghunathan, whose daughter married an African American

01:01:32.280 --> 01:01:37.280
[Amit Varma]: gentleman and her concerts got cancelled because her son-in-law was African American.

01:01:37.280 --> 01:01:38.280
[Guest]: Was it cancelled?

01:01:38.280 --> 01:01:39.280
[Guest]: Yeah, that's what I've heard.

01:01:39.280 --> 01:01:40.280
[Guest]: I knew she was trolled.

01:01:40.280 --> 01:01:41.280
[Guest]: I know she was trolled.

01:01:41.280 --> 01:01:43.760
[Guest]: She was trolled and her shows were cancelled in January apparently.

01:01:43.760 --> 01:01:49.040
[Guest]: Okay, that's but you know, if you think of it, how far is casteism from racism?

01:01:49.040 --> 01:01:54.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's, you know, it's the same insularity, we are the group, everyone else is the other.

01:01:54.560 --> 01:01:55.560
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:01:55.560 --> 01:02:01.240
[Guest]: In fact, we Indians are probably the most racist lot, especially, you know, and what

01:02:01.240 --> 01:02:06.080
[Guest]: do you also forget is there's a homogeneousness more or less in bandwidth of so called Indians

01:02:06.080 --> 01:02:10.840
[Guest]: abroad, who are the majority of Indians who have migrated, they're most of them coming

01:02:10.840 --> 01:02:16.080
[Guest]: from forward caste or shall we say socially mobile, OBCs, if you look at the government

01:02:16.080 --> 01:02:18.240
[Guest]: categorization.

01:02:18.240 --> 01:02:22.840
[Guest]: And therefore, there's a certain homogeneousness of ideas and, and there is a certain commonness

01:02:22.840 --> 01:02:24.800
[Guest]: with the way they want to build a narrative.

01:02:24.800 --> 01:02:27.440
[Guest]: And the narrative casteism is entrenched.

01:02:27.440 --> 01:02:30.280
[Guest]: And in casteism is color.

01:02:30.280 --> 01:02:35.480
[Guest]: And therefore, the notion of the darker skin notion of the African American is also seen

01:02:35.480 --> 01:02:36.760
[Guest]: as a lower caste.

01:02:36.760 --> 01:02:40.280
[Guest]: The African American is seen as a lower caste.

01:02:40.280 --> 01:02:41.280
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:02:41.280 --> 01:02:42.280
[Guest]: Right.

01:02:42.280 --> 01:02:46.160
[Guest]: So this just works perfectly in casteist narrative.

01:02:46.160 --> 01:02:48.760
[Guest]: And that is why you have this ridiculous thing happening.

01:02:48.760 --> 01:02:52.720
[Guest]: And there's a personal thing about somebody getting married, and has got nothing to do

01:02:52.720 --> 01:02:58.440
[Guest]: with anybody, and, but then the person is actually harassed and trolled for a personal

01:02:58.440 --> 01:02:59.440
[Amit Varma]: decision.

01:02:59.440 --> 01:03:00.440
[Guest]: And her son-in-law was called the n-word.

01:03:00.440 --> 01:03:01.440
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely.

01:03:01.440 --> 01:03:10.440
[Guest]: I mean, the surprising thing, Amit, is after all this, even people who are viewing it,

01:03:10.440 --> 01:03:13.160
[Guest]: you know, forget the people who are throwing this nonsense out, maybe, you know, maybe

01:03:13.160 --> 01:03:15.680
[Guest]: we can have a conversation with people, I don't know.

01:03:15.680 --> 01:03:21.040
[Guest]: But even people are viewing it, just don't see the horribleness of it, or say, you know,

01:03:21.040 --> 01:03:24.560
[Guest]: they shouldn't say this, but I just don't get that.

01:03:24.560 --> 01:03:25.680
[Guest]: I mean, I just don't get it.

01:03:25.680 --> 01:03:29.000
[Guest]: I said, you know, there can't be any but over there.

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:33.720
[Guest]: I mean, but a lot of us speak that way.

01:03:33.720 --> 01:03:37.840
[Guest]: You know, they should have not made this public, they should have done the marriage quietly.

01:03:37.840 --> 01:03:38.840
[Guest]: What do you mean?

01:03:38.840 --> 01:03:41.840
[Guest]: You want to just say that these things don't happen?

01:03:41.840 --> 01:03:42.840
[Guest]: What are we saying?

01:03:42.840 --> 01:03:46.680
[Guest]: You know, so you'll be happy if the she had married a Jewish white person?

01:03:46.680 --> 01:03:49.560
[Guest]: I mean, what are we saying?

01:03:49.560 --> 01:03:53.560
[Guest]: I mean, these moments are horrible for the person experiencing it.

01:03:53.560 --> 01:03:55.180
[Amit Varma]: These moments are also revealing.

01:03:55.180 --> 01:03:58.940
[Amit Varma]: And I think the point I'd like to clarify is, and this is a common confusion that when

01:03:58.940 --> 01:04:03.400
[Amit Varma]: you talk about all of you know, these upper caste NRIs taking their caste baggage with

01:04:03.400 --> 01:04:07.920
[Amit Varma]: them, you don't mean to say that they are necessarily casteist or they are thinking

01:04:07.920 --> 01:04:12.800
[Amit Varma]: in terms of caste consciously, it's just that they're carrying those entrenched ways of

01:04:12.800 --> 01:04:15.000
[Amit Varma]: thinking and responding to the world.

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:16.900
[Amit Varma]: And it's completely internalized.

01:04:16.900 --> 01:04:19.720
[Amit Varma]: They may be the best human beings otherwise, and all of that.

01:04:19.720 --> 01:04:20.720
[Guest]: Very true.

01:04:20.720 --> 01:04:21.720
[Guest]: You know, that's not a big problem, right?

01:04:21.720 --> 01:04:25.200
[Guest]: When you speak in these terms, people think that you're painting somebody as evil people.

01:04:25.200 --> 01:04:26.200
[Amit Varma]: They react defensively.

01:04:26.200 --> 01:04:27.740
[Guest]: Yeah, it's not.

01:04:27.740 --> 01:04:31.120
[Guest]: But that's why I keep saying I am still casteist.

01:04:31.120 --> 01:04:32.640
[Guest]: You know, all these invisible ways.

01:04:32.640 --> 01:04:33.640
[Guest]: I do it every day.

01:04:33.640 --> 01:04:34.640
[Guest]: I do it.

01:04:34.640 --> 01:04:40.760
[Guest]: I mean, especially, you know, sexist, casteist, I mean, you know, in your relationship with

01:04:40.760 --> 01:04:45.180
[Guest]: your wife, there are things that you presume that your wife should be doing without even

01:04:45.180 --> 01:04:49.200
[Guest]: thinking about it twice, whereas it comes from patriarchy that you don't recognize.

01:04:49.200 --> 01:04:52.440
[Guest]: And then you, when you talk about it, you realize, yep, where is this coming?

01:04:52.440 --> 01:04:57.280
[Guest]: So these things are so ingrained and normalized that we just don't see it.

01:04:57.280 --> 01:05:01.560
[Guest]: So actually, a lot of times I will say that these are not intentional in that sense.

01:05:01.560 --> 01:05:06.800
[Guest]: You're not purposely saying, I look at Amit, you're like this, and therefore I'm targeting.

01:05:06.800 --> 01:05:07.800
[Guest]: No.

01:05:07.800 --> 01:05:11.280
[Guest]: See, we're all pattern recognizers as a species.

01:05:11.280 --> 01:05:15.720
[Guest]: And these are all patterns we've been taught to recognize, you know, starting from gender.

01:05:15.720 --> 01:05:16.720
[Amit Varma]: These are instinctive aversions.

01:05:16.720 --> 01:05:22.520
[Guest]: So we do all this automatically, we do this automatically, and these engines start working.

01:05:22.520 --> 01:05:25.920
[Guest]: And, but it's important that we are aware that we are functioning in that manner.

01:05:25.920 --> 01:05:27.840
[Guest]: I mean, that's the problem.

01:05:27.840 --> 01:05:32.480
[Guest]: And I think what gets accentuated in a place like with the NRAs is the fact that at least

01:05:32.480 --> 01:05:36.680
[Guest]: in India, you have to walk the street and go to the dhukan.

01:05:36.680 --> 01:05:42.720
[Guest]: You know, you meet, even if you don't want to, people of diversity, you know, but what

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:48.160
[Guest]: happens in the States is you are a homogeneous lot, only meeting those people, carrying these

01:05:48.160 --> 01:05:53.880
[Guest]: things from India and constantly reaffirming that over 20, 30 years, that makes it much

01:05:53.880 --> 01:05:54.880
[Guest]: harder.

01:05:54.880 --> 01:05:57.800
[Guest]: Actually, I'm saying that it's much harder for the NRAs to break free of this because

01:05:57.800 --> 01:06:03.080
[Guest]: they don't, that they lose that connection of the possibility of being hit by something

01:06:03.080 --> 01:06:07.840
[Guest]: that they never expected or experiencing people in a way that they never expected, because

01:06:07.840 --> 01:06:10.760
[Guest]: you are this little bubble in these lit cities.

01:06:10.760 --> 01:06:13.680
[Amit Varma]: And once you get into a comfort zone, you don't question it, which is why your journey

01:06:13.680 --> 01:06:17.760
[Amit Varma]: is so surprising that you've reached the top of the Carnatic music ladder.

01:06:17.760 --> 01:06:22.200
[Amit Varma]: And then you are, you know, you have the level of self reflection, I can imagine someone

01:06:22.200 --> 01:06:26.320
[Amit Varma]: from the outside or someone who's not so successful doing that, you know, just speaking to this

01:06:26.320 --> 01:06:30.080
[Amit Varma]: point, there's a beautiful poem by Akhil Katyal, who's just read a book out, and I'm just going

01:06:30.080 --> 01:06:31.080
[Amit Varma]: to read that out.

01:06:31.080 --> 01:06:32.460
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sure you're familiar with it.

01:06:32.460 --> 01:06:36.160
[Amit Varma]: But for those of my listeners who aren't, and the poem is called Poetic License, is

01:06:36.160 --> 01:06:37.960
[Amit Varma]: by Akhil Katyal.

01:06:37.960 --> 01:06:42.000
[Amit Varma]: One day when he was about 10 or 12, he asked his mother, what is my caste?

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:45.420
[Amit Varma]: Some boys in the school were asking, I didn't know what to say.

01:06:45.420 --> 01:06:50.200
[Amit Varma]: The mother got up in the middle of a supper, beta, if you don't know it by now, it must

01:06:50.200 --> 01:06:51.200
[Amit Varma]: be upper.

01:06:51.200 --> 01:06:58.560
[Guest]: That's, that's a very important poem, because it's true of most of us.

01:06:58.560 --> 01:07:06.080
[Guest]: You know, it's like, somebody told me is that if you are a Dalit, every day, every moment

01:07:06.080 --> 01:07:10.040
[Guest]: of your life, you're reminded that you're a Dalit.

01:07:10.040 --> 01:07:15.440
[Guest]: So when we all say, especially that, what caste, we never spoke about caste at home.

01:07:15.440 --> 01:07:20.400
[Guest]: This is said very often, just means exactly what he said.

01:07:20.400 --> 01:07:24.240
[Amit Varma]: It's that extra layer of awareness, even women carry it, you know, when women walk on the

01:07:24.240 --> 01:07:27.440
[Amit Varma]: street, they have this extra layer of awareness, which is not important to us.

01:07:27.440 --> 01:07:30.240
[Amit Varma]: We can take our being male for granted.

01:07:30.240 --> 01:07:31.240
[Amit Varma]: No woman can do that.

01:07:31.240 --> 01:07:35.600
[Amit Varma]: You enter a lift, you're looking at everyone who's there before you get in.

01:07:35.600 --> 01:07:39.800
[Amit Varma]: And that's consistent, and it's normalized, and men don't see it.

01:07:39.800 --> 01:07:43.600
[Guest]: And men think it's normal to look at a woman in a certain manner.

01:07:43.600 --> 01:07:47.800
[Guest]: And you have to catch yourself sometimes doing things that you would not normally think,

01:07:47.800 --> 01:07:52.360
[Guest]: you know, you know, it's not about whether you're liberal, progressive, etc, etc, etc.

01:07:52.360 --> 01:07:54.120
[Guest]: This is not about being conservative.

01:07:54.120 --> 01:07:57.120
[Guest]: This is just about these entrench habits.

01:07:57.120 --> 01:08:02.840
[Guest]: So I catch myself looking in a certain manner at a woman so many times, then I see it myself.

01:08:02.840 --> 01:08:04.920
[Amit Varma]: This is things that we do.

01:08:04.920 --> 01:08:06.680
[Amit Varma]: You know, wife is listening to this.

01:08:06.680 --> 01:08:07.680
[Amit Varma]: What are you saying?

01:08:07.680 --> 01:08:12.400
[Amit Varma]: Okay, before we go into a break, and after the break, we have to get to your wonderful

01:08:12.400 --> 01:08:13.400
[Amit Varma]: book.

01:08:13.400 --> 01:08:14.520
[Amit Varma]: We're not doing it justice if we don't.

01:08:14.520 --> 01:08:19.280
[Amit Varma]: But sort of a final question, just you know, going back to that old theme we were exploring

01:08:19.280 --> 01:08:24.160
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, the evolution of Carnatic music and the setting it apart from other kinds

01:08:24.160 --> 01:08:29.840
[Amit Varma]: of lower art, which are not classical and all that, did also the academies play a part

01:08:29.840 --> 01:08:30.840
[Amit Varma]: in this?

01:08:30.840 --> 01:08:34.400
[Amit Varma]: For example, in your book, there is this passage about the Music Academy, which you know, your

01:08:34.400 --> 01:08:39.440
[Amit Varma]: grand uncle, T.T. Krishnamacharya played a part in founding, quote, the Music Academy,

01:08:39.440 --> 01:08:44.520
[Amit Varma]: established in 1928, had quickly become the sanctum sanctorum of Carnatic music, sabhas

01:08:44.520 --> 01:08:48.760
[Amit Varma]: such as Parthasarathy Swami Sabha, Perambur Sangeet Sabha, Jagannath Bhakt Sabha were

01:08:48.760 --> 01:08:53.680
[Amit Varma]: changing the nature of Carnatic music consumption, ticket paying public and membership driven

01:08:53.680 --> 01:08:56.120
[Amit Varma]: models became the accepted norm.

01:08:56.120 --> 01:09:01.800
[Amit Varma]: This was enabled by Brahmin families migrating from Tanjavur, Tirunelveli and surrounding

01:09:01.800 --> 01:09:07.200
[Amit Varma]: areas, the Chettiyars from Karaikudi district and other high culture seeking business communities

01:09:07.200 --> 01:09:09.240
[Amit Varma]: such as the Mudaliars, stop quote.

01:09:09.240 --> 01:09:13.920
[Amit Varma]: And what seems to me to be happening here, and where say Carnatic music gets this kind

01:09:13.920 --> 01:09:18.720
[Amit Varma]: of advantage as it were over the other forms which are looked down upon, is that you have

01:09:18.720 --> 01:09:23.160
[Amit Varma]: an academy, you have theory building around it, you have a pedagogy building around it,

01:09:23.160 --> 01:09:27.720
[Amit Varma]: you have a community building around it, while other forms of music may survive sort of as

01:09:27.720 --> 01:09:33.080
[Amit Varma]: oral traditions do, without this accumulated knowledge passing through to future generations.

01:09:33.080 --> 01:09:34.520
[Guest]: Very important point you make.

01:09:34.520 --> 01:09:37.900
[Guest]: So I think we have to go back to the political context of the times.

01:09:37.900 --> 01:09:41.480
[Guest]: So this is a times of Hindu nationalism.

01:09:41.480 --> 01:09:45.840
[Guest]: So there's not just a Carnatic phenomena, you see Bhatkande trying to do the same thing,

01:09:45.840 --> 01:09:50.760
[Guest]: you see Paluskar trying to do the something, this whole notion of presenting Indian culture

01:09:50.760 --> 01:09:55.640
[Guest]: as this very old, very pristine, you know, idea.

01:09:55.640 --> 01:10:01.080
[Guest]: And so you have these people, all upper caste people, in the case of Khyal, they feel that

01:10:01.080 --> 01:10:05.680
[Guest]: the Muslims have basically spoiled this art form, they sing whatever they want.

01:10:05.680 --> 01:10:09.240
[Guest]: And so we need to get the original music.

01:10:09.240 --> 01:10:14.360
[Guest]: So Bhatkande decides to go through the musicological way, Paluskar said bhakti is the way.

01:10:14.360 --> 01:10:17.060
[Guest]: Bhakti is the essence of this music.

01:10:17.060 --> 01:10:19.060
[Guest]: So he uses another channel.

01:10:19.060 --> 01:10:23.000
[Guest]: So you have that happening, and that's when you have all the Gandharva Mahavidyas forming,

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:24.000
[Guest]: you have all these things.

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:26.440
[Guest]: A similar narrative is happening in the South.

01:10:26.440 --> 01:10:29.040
[Guest]: But in the South, what is happening is that Devadasis are the targets.

01:10:29.040 --> 01:10:31.980
[Guest]: Now, they are now by then considered niche.

01:10:31.980 --> 01:10:35.920
[Guest]: So then they can't be part of something we are considered old and pure.

01:10:35.920 --> 01:10:41.880
[Guest]: So then you again building a very, very nationalistic, very upper caste notion, theosophical society

01:10:41.880 --> 01:10:49.400
[Guest]: plays a very important role in these constructions of what Hindu philosophy, Hindu history, the

01:10:49.400 --> 01:10:52.400
[Guest]: Rishis in the Himalayas, all these notions, right?

01:10:52.400 --> 01:10:54.600
[Guest]: So you have these art forms forming in that.

01:10:54.600 --> 01:11:01.760
[Guest]: Thyagaraja is now becoming this saint, he becomes this real, beyond reality human being.

01:11:01.760 --> 01:11:06.320
[Guest]: So all this construction is happening at the same time, everybody recognizes another battle

01:11:06.320 --> 01:11:11.400
[Guest]: you have to fight with the British is not just emotionally getting this music, but also

01:11:11.400 --> 01:11:15.840
[Guest]: say that it's technical, also say that it is intellectual.

01:11:15.840 --> 01:11:19.520
[Guest]: So then you have this Music Academy forming, and it's fascinating if you go through Music

01:11:19.520 --> 01:11:25.360
[Guest]: Academy discussions, and it's all documented, you have lawyers, okay, they're not professional

01:11:25.360 --> 01:11:26.360
[Guest]: musicians.

01:11:26.360 --> 01:11:31.040
[Guest]: So all these lawyers and well educated upper caste Brahmin men, who are having these debates

01:11:31.040 --> 01:11:33.040
[Guest]: on Carnatic music with musicians.

01:11:33.040 --> 01:11:34.040
[Guest]: Wow.

01:11:34.040 --> 01:11:37.560
[Guest]: Okay, so they are saying so that's when the rules are then being formed, like you're then

01:11:37.560 --> 01:11:39.680
[Guest]: giving knowledge validity in document.

01:11:39.680 --> 01:11:42.400
[Guest]: Sounds like the Constituent Assembly debates, are these online?

01:11:42.400 --> 01:11:43.400
[Guest]: Oh, it's online.

01:11:43.400 --> 01:11:45.280
[Guest]: It's all online, you can go it's very interesting.

01:11:45.280 --> 01:11:48.560
[Guest]: So that's part of creating intellectual capital.

01:11:48.560 --> 01:11:50.360
[Guest]: That's actually creating knowledge.

01:11:50.360 --> 01:11:51.360
[Guest]: And it has been modern.

01:11:51.360 --> 01:11:52.360
[Guest]: And you're codifying it.

01:11:52.360 --> 01:11:53.360
[Amit Varma]: Basically, it's a codification.

01:11:53.360 --> 01:11:54.440
[Unknown]: Yeah, and it's a modern notion.

01:11:54.440 --> 01:11:57.520
[Guest]: This has happened, the same thing is happening with Hindustani music.

01:11:57.520 --> 01:12:03.600
[Guest]: And then the interesting part is post independence, we just continued the same narrative.

01:12:03.600 --> 01:12:08.040
[Guest]: Just look at the institutions that were created for culture across the country.

01:12:08.040 --> 01:12:14.240
[Guest]: That was for Bharatanatyam, private Carnatic music or Hindustani music for Kathakali.

01:12:14.240 --> 01:12:18.880
[Guest]: So again, you're only looking at those art forms that are practiced by a certain group

01:12:18.880 --> 01:12:23.720
[Guest]: of people or enjoy by certain group of people that is decided that you believe needs to

01:12:23.720 --> 01:12:27.320
[Guest]: be codified that deserves even codification of intellectual activity.

01:12:27.320 --> 01:12:31.840
[Guest]: So you're actually designing cultural knowledge, you're actually defining what is knowledge

01:12:31.840 --> 01:12:33.280
[Guest]: in culture and art.

01:12:33.280 --> 01:12:38.120
[Guest]: So all this played a very important role in placing these art forms where they are, in

01:12:38.120 --> 01:12:43.480
[Guest]: placing them in the fact that this is what we want to present as ourselves, without doubt.

01:12:43.480 --> 01:12:49.480
[Guest]: And the fact that this did not happen for so many art forms, meant that for 70 years,

01:12:49.480 --> 01:12:55.720
[Guest]: they are still considered just they considered, of course, exotic, very important, or you

01:12:55.720 --> 01:12:58.040
[Guest]: say one thing, they are the source for this.

01:12:58.040 --> 01:13:00.960
[Guest]: You know, I always find it deeply disturbing when classical musicians say, you know what

01:13:00.960 --> 01:13:04.480
[Guest]: folk say, what do you mean by that?

01:13:04.480 --> 01:13:09.160
[Guest]: It's like it was something that was an, you know, unpolished diamond that we took from

01:13:09.160 --> 01:13:11.120
[Guest]: there and made it polished.

01:13:11.120 --> 01:13:14.080
[Guest]: So those were like resource material.

01:13:14.080 --> 01:13:17.120
[Guest]: And they have their beauty, they have their limitedness.

01:13:17.120 --> 01:13:20.560
[Guest]: But then the classical is what is an evolution of them.

01:13:20.560 --> 01:13:25.760
[Guest]: So all this allowed for this kind of cultural discourse to be entrenched in our psyche

01:13:25.760 --> 01:13:28.640
[Guest]: and in our emotional beings, because we feel that way.

01:13:28.640 --> 01:13:32.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and, you know, just thinking in terms of cultural equity, it just seems that the

01:13:32.960 --> 01:13:38.760
[Amit Varma]: inequality in cultural equity was enormously exacerbated by these institutions, which just

01:13:38.760 --> 01:13:42.600
[Amit Varma]: keep, you know, doing what they're doing, which is not to say that these forms of music

01:13:42.600 --> 01:13:48.040
[Amit Varma]: should not have academies or, you know, theoretic development or whatever, but the other forms

01:13:48.040 --> 01:13:49.040
[Guest]: are...

01:13:49.040 --> 01:13:50.040
[Guest]: Definitely.

01:13:50.040 --> 01:13:53.560
[Guest]: And you can point to so many forms across this country, you know, so I won't say I'm

01:13:53.560 --> 01:13:57.640
[Guest]: not talking about what I would like to call, I don't like the word folk, social music,

01:13:57.640 --> 01:14:00.600
[Guest]: for example, harvest songs or a lullaby.

01:14:00.600 --> 01:14:06.480
[Guest]: Those are social music that is passed on from mother to daughter or, you know, all the villagers.

01:14:06.480 --> 01:14:08.920
[Guest]: That's different from organized art.

01:14:08.920 --> 01:14:14.600
[Guest]: And you've organized art across this country, and none of them had the benefit of being

01:14:14.600 --> 01:14:20.000
[Guest]: codified or being given theorization or being written about in, you know, with the nuances

01:14:20.000 --> 01:14:25.240
[Guest]: and the technicalities that they all have, simply because of where they belonged in society.

01:14:25.240 --> 01:14:30.160
[Amit Varma]: So does that now, assuming that this started out as, I don't want to use the word equal,

01:14:30.160 --> 01:14:34.560
[Amit Varma]: because we're not weighing different art forms, but assuming that at one time, they were all

01:14:34.560 --> 01:14:38.560
[Amit Varma]: art forms at a similar level of evolution, have those kind of fallen back?

01:14:38.560 --> 01:14:41.000
[Guest]: I mean, I'm uncomfortable about using this language itself.

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:42.000
[Guest]: I'm not sure.

01:14:42.000 --> 01:14:43.320
[Guest]: Because of this codification process.

01:14:43.320 --> 01:14:44.320
[Guest]: I'm not sure.

01:14:44.320 --> 01:14:45.320
[Guest]: I wouldn't think so.

01:14:45.320 --> 01:14:49.760
[Guest]: I would think that it's not an upper view, does not mean that it has not had its own

01:14:49.760 --> 01:14:50.760
[Guest]: evolution.

01:14:50.760 --> 01:14:51.760
[Guest]: It had its own changes.

01:14:51.760 --> 01:14:54.680
[Guest]: You go to any of these art forms, and the practitioners will tell you how things have

01:14:54.680 --> 01:14:55.680
[Guest]: changed.

01:14:55.680 --> 01:14:56.680
[Amit Varma]: Narratives have changed.

01:14:56.680 --> 01:14:57.680
[Amit Varma]: Storytelling has changed.

01:14:57.680 --> 01:14:59.080
[Guest]: And maybe the absence of codification is a feature, not a bug.

01:14:59.080 --> 01:15:00.080
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:15:00.080 --> 01:15:02.400
[Guest]: And then that kind of takes it to a different kind of a journey.

01:15:02.400 --> 01:15:03.400
[Guest]: It's definitely happened.

01:15:03.400 --> 01:15:09.440
[Guest]: I think the fact that they seem to be invisible is what the problem is, that they don't exist

01:15:09.440 --> 01:15:12.720
[Guest]: in serious discussion, you know, in all these highbrow.

01:15:12.720 --> 01:15:16.720
[Guest]: So I think an important point that you're raising, and it's all important, is knowledge.

01:15:16.720 --> 01:15:18.280
[Guest]: How does knowledge get created?

01:15:18.280 --> 01:15:22.360
[Guest]: When is something knowledge and who is deciding these things, you know?

01:15:22.360 --> 01:15:23.360
[Guest]: And what is documentation?

01:15:23.360 --> 01:15:25.000
[Guest]: You know, it's very odd, no?

01:15:25.000 --> 01:15:29.200
[Guest]: At one point, we keep saying Indian culture is not written culture.

01:15:29.200 --> 01:15:31.880
[Guest]: Indian culture is what we carry forward.

01:15:31.880 --> 01:15:35.680
[Guest]: But then we decide to only codify some of them.

01:15:35.680 --> 01:15:36.720
[Guest]: We say both.

01:15:36.720 --> 01:15:40.040
[Guest]: We say Indian culture is oral history, or we are an oral system.

01:15:40.040 --> 01:15:42.280
[Guest]: We didn't believe in, you know, writing things down.

01:15:42.280 --> 01:15:43.900
[Guest]: We celebrate that.

01:15:43.900 --> 01:15:49.880
[Guest]: But when it comes to judging art or judging cultures, we give more importance to the ones

01:15:49.880 --> 01:15:54.160
[Guest]: that have documents, that have some shastra, and that is not shastra.

01:15:54.160 --> 01:15:59.720
[Guest]: So, you know, we play this little game, we choose when we want to be oral and oral, when

01:15:59.720 --> 01:16:01.480
[Guest]: we want to be organized.

01:16:01.480 --> 01:16:04.320
[Amit Varma]: And this reminds me of a similar privileging you mentioned in your book where you point

01:16:04.320 --> 01:16:08.480
[Amit Varma]: out that documentaries about Chennai will always show Mylapore and, you know, those

01:16:08.480 --> 01:16:09.880
[Guest]: areas from which you belong.

01:16:09.880 --> 01:16:10.880
[Guest]: Of course I do.

01:16:10.880 --> 01:16:12.760
[Amit Varma]: I'm from the innermost circles.

01:16:12.760 --> 01:16:13.760
[Amit Varma]: You are from the innermost circles.

