01:17:32.600 --> 01:17:33.880
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

01:17:33.880 --> 01:17:38.320
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with TM Krishna about Carnatic music and especially about his new book, Sebastian

01:17:38.320 --> 01:17:43.120
[Amit Varma]: and Sons, which carries this delightful quote from C. Rajagopalachari.

01:17:43.120 --> 01:17:47.360
[Amit Varma]: You talk about how, you know, Palgatmani Iyer goes to see Rajagopalachari with a problem

01:17:47.360 --> 01:17:52.540
[Amit Varma]: about the contradiction that the instrument that he uses involves taking the lives of

01:17:52.540 --> 01:17:55.480
[Amit Varma]: three animals because there are three kinds of hide on there.

01:17:55.480 --> 01:18:00.360
[Amit Varma]: And Rajaji tells him, quote, don't look for the source of a river or the antecedents of

01:18:00.360 --> 01:18:02.320
[Amit Varma]: a saint, stop quote.

01:18:02.320 --> 01:18:09.280
[Amit Varma]: And this seems to me to not only speak to the question of the Mridangam itself, but

01:18:09.280 --> 01:18:10.760
[Amit Varma]: to all of Carnatic music.

01:18:10.760 --> 01:18:13.200
[Amit Varma]: And you've actually, you know, you've done that.

01:18:13.200 --> 01:18:15.800
[Amit Varma]: You've questioned the source of the river.

01:18:15.800 --> 01:18:16.800
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:18:16.800 --> 01:18:20.440
[Guest]: I mean, in Tamil, it's like Rishi moolam nadhi moolam kekka kodathu.

01:18:20.440 --> 01:18:23.000
[Guest]: I'm just telling you how it sounds in Tamil.

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:24.200
[Guest]: Rishi moolam nadhi moolam.

01:18:24.200 --> 01:18:25.200
[Guest]: Nadhi is river.

01:18:25.200 --> 01:18:26.440
[Guest]: So Rishi moolam nadhi moolam.

01:18:26.440 --> 01:18:28.440
[Guest]: Never ask for that.

01:18:28.440 --> 01:18:33.080
[Guest]: You know, when I first, it was told to me, this story was told to me, it seemed very

01:18:33.080 --> 01:18:34.080
[Guest]: normal to me.

01:18:34.080 --> 01:18:36.960
[Guest]: It's like certain questions don't ask, you know, why do you want to know?

01:18:36.960 --> 01:18:40.840
[Guest]: But then when I looked at it again and again, this is like, wow, that's so convenient.

01:18:40.840 --> 01:18:42.640
[Guest]: We decide what we don't want to see.

01:18:42.640 --> 01:18:44.520
[Guest]: That's a rationalization of denial.

01:18:44.520 --> 01:18:45.520
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:18:45.520 --> 01:18:50.320
[Guest]: Entirely denial that, you know, cow skin is required for the Mridangam.

01:18:50.320 --> 01:18:53.240
[Guest]: And I find Palagatmaneer most interesting here.

01:18:53.240 --> 01:18:55.880
[Guest]: He said I wouldn't brush it under the carpet, right?

01:18:55.880 --> 01:18:57.960
[Guest]: He could have very easily said, I don't want to talk about this.

01:18:57.960 --> 01:19:00.360
[Guest]: But he's this man who loves the Mridangam.

01:19:00.360 --> 01:19:01.600
[Guest]: He's obsessed with it.

01:19:01.600 --> 01:19:03.960
[Guest]: He's really obsessed with it.

01:19:03.960 --> 01:19:05.520
[Guest]: And he wants to get the best tone.

01:19:05.520 --> 01:19:07.000
[Guest]: He wants the best skin.

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:08.040
[Guest]: He's very clear.

01:19:08.040 --> 01:19:09.240
[Guest]: He wants to improve the tone.

01:19:09.240 --> 01:19:10.840
[Guest]: He's trying his best.

01:19:10.840 --> 01:19:17.080
[Guest]: And then it suddenly hits him like, wow, but isn't this the cow that I worship, but I want

01:19:17.080 --> 01:19:18.080
[Guest]: the skin.

01:19:18.080 --> 01:19:19.680
[Guest]: So he kind of, you can see.

01:19:19.680 --> 01:19:23.000
[Guest]: So he's then asking, he wants, he wants reconciliation.

01:19:23.000 --> 01:19:26.000
[Guest]: He wants somehow to make sure that he feels better about it.

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:28.160
[Guest]: And we all do that, right?

01:19:28.160 --> 01:19:33.040
[Guest]: And he goes and asks Rajaji and Srirajagopalachari comes up with his answer.

01:19:33.040 --> 01:19:36.720
[Guest]: And to me, his answer is more problematic than Maneer's seeking.

01:19:36.720 --> 01:19:38.440
[Guest]: Maneer's seeking is very honest.

01:19:38.440 --> 01:19:43.080
[Guest]: But Srirajagopalachari isn't, he's saying don't ask this because he's almost saying,

01:19:43.080 --> 01:19:46.000
[Guest]: if you go there, you won't be at in peace.

01:19:46.000 --> 01:19:47.940
[Guest]: You won't be able to do what you're great at.

01:19:47.940 --> 01:19:51.800
[Guest]: You won't be able to play the Mridangam and be this incredible musician because you know,

01:19:51.800 --> 01:19:54.360
[Guest]: you'll have to see things that you should not be seeing.

01:19:54.360 --> 01:19:58.480
[Guest]: So that means you forget the maker, you forget the person who's cutting the skin out, you

01:19:58.480 --> 01:20:01.260
[Guest]: forget the person who's cleaning their skin for you.

01:20:01.260 --> 01:20:08.240
[Guest]: So you're actually removing a whole section of people and culture from the conversation,

01:20:08.240 --> 01:20:11.680
[Guest]: but just saying, I don't, I know what lies behind it.

01:20:11.680 --> 01:20:13.080
[Guest]: He's not blind to it.

01:20:13.080 --> 01:20:16.240
[Guest]: He knows what happens, but I don't want to see it.

01:20:16.240 --> 01:20:20.600
[Amit Varma]: So basically Palgat Maneer accepted Rajaji's advice, but you did not.

01:20:20.600 --> 01:20:21.600
[Guest]: Of course.

01:20:21.600 --> 01:20:24.360
[Amit Varma]: I took great offense.

01:20:24.360 --> 01:20:29.440
[Amit Varma]: This reminds me of this old story about Tolstoy that Tolstoy once he became a vegetarian and

01:20:29.440 --> 01:20:34.600
[Amit Varma]: he was very, you know, rigid about his vegetarianism and an aunt came to visit one day and the

01:20:34.600 --> 01:20:39.240
[Amit Varma]: aunt said, I would really like to eat some chicken and Tolstoy was unhappy, but he couldn't

01:20:39.240 --> 01:20:40.240
[Amit Varma]: say no to the aunt.

01:20:40.240 --> 01:20:41.240
[Amit Varma]: So he said, okay.

01:20:41.240 --> 01:20:44.880
[Amit Varma]: And then at dinnertime, the aunt gets to the dining table and she finds a live chicken

01:20:44.880 --> 01:20:46.400
[Amit Varma]: on her chair.

01:20:46.400 --> 01:20:48.920
[Amit Varma]: And Tolstoy said that none of us had the heart to carve it up.

01:20:48.920 --> 01:20:50.300
[Amit Varma]: You do it yourself.

01:20:50.300 --> 01:20:57.040
[Amit Varma]: And this reminds me of this beautiful bit I'm going to quote from your book about Palgat

01:20:57.040 --> 01:21:01.640
[Amit Varma]: Maneer Iyer, who is, and this is in the context of Alkaton, who is Parilandu's cousin.

01:21:01.640 --> 01:21:02.640
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

01:21:02.640 --> 01:21:05.680
[Amit Varma]: And quote, Iyer gave Alkaton a job.

01:21:05.680 --> 01:21:10.240
[Amit Varma]: He said he wanted top draw cow skin, no compromises and the cost did not matter.

01:21:10.240 --> 01:21:12.360
[Amit Varma]: Alkaton said it would cost rupees hundred.

01:21:12.360 --> 01:21:16.920
[Amit Varma]: Iyer gave him that amount immediately in advance and headed out to a restaurant around three

01:21:16.920 --> 01:21:17.920
[Amit Varma]: or 4pm.

01:21:17.920 --> 01:21:22.920
[Amit Varma]: When he returned, he found Alkaton standing outside his house, cow in tow.

01:21:22.920 --> 01:21:24.960
[Amit Varma]: Iyer was startled to say the least.

01:21:24.960 --> 01:21:30.040
[Amit Varma]: Alkaton informed him that this cow had great skin, but the seller wanted rupees 120.

01:21:30.040 --> 01:21:33.240
[Amit Varma]: So he wanted to check with Iyer before completing the transaction.

01:21:33.240 --> 01:21:34.920
[Amit Varma]: Iyer was shocked.

01:21:34.920 --> 01:21:38.840
[Amit Varma]: Almost certainly this would have been the first time he had to make a decision on the

01:21:38.840 --> 01:21:44.280
[Amit Varma]: slaughtering itself and take responsibility for something that was thus far hidden.

01:21:44.280 --> 01:21:47.820
[Amit Varma]: He just shooed Alkaton away and demanded that he take the cow with him.

01:21:47.820 --> 01:21:51.480
[Amit Varma]: This incident from Iyer's life is a universal condition.

01:21:51.480 --> 01:21:56.720
[Amit Varma]: I am certain that no Mridangam artist would like to be placed in a similar situation.

01:21:56.720 --> 01:22:00.300
[Amit Varma]: Skin just drops down from the heavens as far as they are concerned.

01:22:00.300 --> 01:22:01.300
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:22:01.300 --> 01:22:02.300
[Amit Varma]: This is such a beautiful line.

01:22:02.300 --> 01:22:04.040
[Amit Varma]: Skin just drops down from the heavens.

01:22:04.040 --> 01:22:06.240
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, thank you for that moment.

01:22:06.240 --> 01:22:08.200
[Amit Varma]: We'll sort of come back to this later.

01:22:08.200 --> 01:22:12.640
[Amit Varma]: And I want to especially delve into your chapter on how you went to an abattoir and enjoyed

01:22:12.640 --> 01:22:13.640
[Amit Varma]: the experience.

01:22:13.640 --> 01:22:16.160
[Amit Varma]: So I'm totally judging you on that.

01:22:16.160 --> 01:22:21.680
[Amit Varma]: But first, tell me about how the thought of the book came to you.

01:22:21.680 --> 01:22:27.200
[Guest]: You know, my first book was called Southern Music, a Carnatic Story.

01:22:27.200 --> 01:22:33.280
[Guest]: And the book is a more academic book in that sense into technicalities, history, and in

01:22:33.280 --> 01:22:38.160
[Guest]: a way, I think all the journey that I went through within music for myself, somehow got

01:22:38.160 --> 01:22:39.320
[Guest]: encapsulated in the book.

01:22:39.320 --> 01:22:44.220
[Guest]: And I actually think that the book that book helped me in gaining clarity with all the

01:22:44.220 --> 01:22:45.800
[Guest]: different streams of thoughts I had.

01:22:45.800 --> 01:22:50.120
[Guest]: So the book really helped me in, you know, figuring out what was happening through almost

01:22:50.120 --> 01:22:51.960
[Guest]: six, seven years.

01:22:51.960 --> 01:22:55.240
[Guest]: And there is a whole section on the sociology and the politics of the music.

01:22:55.240 --> 01:22:58.160
[Guest]: And there's a whole chapter on caste.

01:22:58.160 --> 01:23:02.720
[Guest]: And that chapter was very heavily debated when the book came out.

01:23:02.720 --> 01:23:06.800
[Guest]: And I remember with my editor, we were looking at the second edition or something.

01:23:06.800 --> 01:23:11.520
[Guest]: And I just flipping through that chapter, suddenly, the instrument maker came to my

01:23:11.520 --> 01:23:15.640
[Amit Varma]: head and I said, and I'll interrupt you because you said editor and I'll point out I'm a big

01:23:15.640 --> 01:23:20.560
[Amit Varma]: fan of your editor Ajita Jaya's fantastic job she did on that book and this one continue.

01:23:20.560 --> 01:23:21.560
[Guest]: Thank you very much.

01:23:21.560 --> 01:23:23.040
[Guest]: She's a fantastic editor.

01:23:23.040 --> 01:23:24.040
[Guest]: That's true.

01:23:24.040 --> 01:23:29.880
[Guest]: So what happened was, I suddenly realized I had said nothing about the instrument maker.

01:23:29.880 --> 01:23:33.400
[Guest]: And I was like, what did I do?

01:23:33.400 --> 01:23:37.080
[Guest]: In my head, music was only about the performance.

01:23:37.080 --> 01:23:43.360
[Guest]: In my head, the instrument was got its life because of the instrumentalist.

01:23:43.360 --> 01:23:47.680
[Guest]: What about the person who actually gives it the sound?

01:23:47.680 --> 01:23:50.080
[Guest]: And that's when I said, what about the Mridangam maker?

01:23:50.080 --> 01:23:56.400
[Guest]: And that's also because the Mridangam is slightly different from other instruments.

01:23:56.400 --> 01:23:58.120
[Guest]: I mean, tabla is also close by.

01:23:58.120 --> 01:24:02.680
[Guest]: The sense if I buy a tanpura, the tanpura stays with me and my connection with the maker

01:24:02.680 --> 01:24:03.680
[Guest]: is lost.

01:24:03.680 --> 01:24:08.800
[Guest]: I can retune it, I can change the strings, unless something gets damaged.

01:24:08.800 --> 01:24:10.720
[Guest]: The tanpura then is just with me.

01:24:10.720 --> 01:24:13.760
[Guest]: So there is no constant relationship.

01:24:13.760 --> 01:24:15.040
[Guest]: It's not the case with the Mridangam.

01:24:15.040 --> 01:24:16.760
[Guest]: The Mridangam needs constant change.

01:24:16.760 --> 01:24:17.760
[Guest]: It needs skin change.

01:24:17.760 --> 01:24:19.880
[Guest]: It needs that black spot to be changed.

01:24:19.880 --> 01:24:23.400
[Guest]: So all the Mridangam makers, I mean, players will come and say, you know, this is old,

01:24:23.400 --> 01:24:24.400
[Guest]: I need to go back.

01:24:24.400 --> 01:24:25.760
[Guest]: And they're constantly at the Mridangam shop.

01:24:25.760 --> 01:24:27.880
[Guest]: You've heard stories about what happens in Mridangam shop.

01:24:27.880 --> 01:24:30.240
[Guest]: So I know all this folklore.

01:24:30.240 --> 01:24:32.280
[Guest]: So I said, what about them?

01:24:32.280 --> 01:24:35.800
[Guest]: And Amit actually wrote a paragraph to plug in.

01:24:35.800 --> 01:24:41.080
[Guest]: And, you know, you're writing this to save yourself, actually, right?

01:24:41.080 --> 01:24:42.840
[Amit Varma]: Because you want to be politically correct.

01:24:42.840 --> 01:24:43.840
[Amit Varma]: Plausible deniability.

01:24:43.840 --> 01:24:45.200
[Guest]: I did not ignore it.

01:24:45.200 --> 01:24:46.480
[Guest]: Yes, exactly.

01:24:46.480 --> 01:24:49.960
[Guest]: And I think I, I stopped.

01:24:49.960 --> 01:24:55.760
[Guest]: And I stopped because I realized that it was fake and I realized I've been completely dishonest.

01:24:55.760 --> 01:24:58.880
[Guest]: I also realized I knew nothing about them.

01:24:58.880 --> 01:24:59.880
[Guest]: I knew nothing.

01:24:59.880 --> 01:25:00.880
[Guest]: I mean, I knew the names.

01:25:00.880 --> 01:25:01.880
[Guest]: I knew Parlan's name.

01:25:01.880 --> 01:25:03.400
[Guest]: That was one name people knew.

01:25:03.400 --> 01:25:07.420
[Guest]: I knew a few of the stories that people have told me, but I didn't know anything.

01:25:07.420 --> 01:25:11.440
[Guest]: So I paused and I said, maybe I should learn about them.

01:25:11.440 --> 01:25:14.520
[Guest]: Maybe there is a story, there are stories to tell.

01:25:14.520 --> 01:25:19.240
[Guest]: That's when I first started going and interviewing Mridangam makers.

01:25:19.240 --> 01:25:23.760
[Guest]: And I did this for about three and a half years.

01:25:23.760 --> 01:25:29.560
[Guest]: I met, I don't know how many of them, I mean, the book comes out of about close to 50 interviews.

01:25:29.560 --> 01:25:35.440
[Guest]: 30 of them are long, one and a half hour interviews, and then short conversations.

01:25:35.440 --> 01:25:40.480
[Guest]: And I just kept interviewing people, makers of different generation, different parts of

01:25:40.480 --> 01:25:41.480
[Guest]: South India.

01:25:41.480 --> 01:25:43.920
[Guest]: I also spoke to Mridangam players.

01:25:43.920 --> 01:25:46.280
[Guest]: And it was that whole journey.

01:25:46.280 --> 01:25:51.480
[Guest]: And then sitting with them, honestly, I remember there were points in the interview stage,

01:25:51.480 --> 01:25:55.000
[Guest]: the fieldwork stage, when I was overwhelmed by all the stuff I was hearing.

01:25:55.000 --> 01:25:56.520
[Guest]: I was like, how am I going to even say this?

01:25:56.520 --> 01:25:57.840
[Guest]: I mean, how am I going to tell this story?

01:25:57.840 --> 01:26:02.800
[Guest]: There are so many streams, there are so many voices, is it even possible to say this?

01:26:02.800 --> 01:26:08.280
[Guest]: And then it took me a long time to just sit with the interviews, watch them again and

01:26:08.280 --> 01:26:11.080
[Guest]: again, look at the transcripts.

01:26:11.080 --> 01:26:12.080
[Guest]: And then from there evolved.

01:26:12.080 --> 01:26:14.160
[Guest]: So you actually recorded those?

01:26:14.160 --> 01:26:19.080
[Guest]: I actually videoed almost every interview, along with audio.

01:26:19.080 --> 01:26:20.080
[Amit Varma]: And I did.

01:26:20.080 --> 01:26:24.520
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, I find you extraordinarily, and I'm jealous of this because I wish I had

01:26:24.520 --> 01:26:26.800
[Amit Varma]: that quality, extremely self-aware.

01:26:26.800 --> 01:26:31.280
[Amit Varma]: So therefore, you know, when it comes to these interviews that you're doing, you are talking

01:26:31.280 --> 01:26:39.720
[Amit Varma]: essentially to lower class Mridangam makers, who have essentially played a secondary role

01:26:39.720 --> 01:26:44.720
[Amit Varma]: to the people who actually play the Mridangam, who are upper caste people.

01:26:44.720 --> 01:26:50.560
[Amit Varma]: And there is, in what you are doing itself, an echo of that instrumentality, where you're

01:26:50.560 --> 01:26:55.200
[Amit Varma]: using these lower caste people for your own purposes of writing this book, and you are

01:26:55.200 --> 01:26:59.920
[Amit Varma]: an upper caste man yourself, which is clearly something you must have pondered.

01:26:59.920 --> 01:27:02.360
[Amit Varma]: How did you sort of negotiate that?

01:27:02.360 --> 01:27:06.520
[Amit Varma]: And this is, you know, even outside of this caste angle, this is a question that nonfiction

01:27:06.520 --> 01:27:11.360
[Amit Varma]: writers get all the time, that at the end of the day, you might feel tremendous empathy

01:27:11.360 --> 01:27:14.680
[Amit Varma]: with the people you're writing about, you might even be friends with them.

01:27:14.680 --> 01:27:16.600
[Amit Varma]: But there is a sense that you're using them.

01:27:16.600 --> 01:27:20.400
[Amit Varma]: And I guess the standard answer is that, look, I am being very upfront and honest about what

01:27:20.400 --> 01:27:21.640
[Amit Varma]: I am doing.

01:27:21.640 --> 01:27:23.120
[Amit Varma]: And they are responding to that.

01:27:23.120 --> 01:27:24.440
[Amit Varma]: And then what happens is happens.

01:27:24.440 --> 01:27:26.440
[Guest]: I don't think it's as simple as that.

01:27:26.440 --> 01:27:29.160
[Guest]: I think it's, it's very problematic.

01:27:29.160 --> 01:27:31.480
[Guest]: I've struggled with it.

01:27:31.480 --> 01:27:36.800
[Guest]: Because I didn't know at what point, I mean, these are these are people.

01:27:36.800 --> 01:27:39.200
[Guest]: And these are their lives.

01:27:39.200 --> 01:27:41.320
[Guest]: These are their realities.

01:27:41.320 --> 01:27:43.520
[Guest]: These are the stories they've experienced have been told.

01:27:43.520 --> 01:27:45.640
[Guest]: It's about family, it's about history.

01:27:45.640 --> 01:27:50.680
[Guest]: I mean, it's, I mean, it's not just information they're giving you, they're sharing themselves

01:27:50.680 --> 01:27:51.680
[Guest]: with you, right?

01:27:51.680 --> 01:27:53.200
[Guest]: So it really matters.

01:27:53.200 --> 01:27:56.520
[Guest]: And the big problem is that you come from such privilege.

01:27:56.520 --> 01:28:02.360
[Guest]: And you know, you can't treat them as some resource material, they're not resource material.

01:28:02.360 --> 01:28:08.280
[Guest]: I mean, it's like if somebody came and asked me about my life, I mean, I'm opening myself

01:28:08.280 --> 01:28:09.280
[Guest]: to you, right?

01:28:09.280 --> 01:28:11.320
[Guest]: And I'm, you know, I'm asking difficult questions.

01:28:11.320 --> 01:28:15.080
[Guest]: So, for example, I mean, I've never done any work like this before.

01:28:15.080 --> 01:28:20.840
[Guest]: My writing has always been in a way in the more ideational observation and ideational

01:28:20.840 --> 01:28:21.840
[Guest]: sense.

01:28:21.840 --> 01:28:25.640
[Guest]: I have not done work where I was speaking to people and what they told me is the story.

01:28:25.640 --> 01:28:28.160
[Amit Varma]: You've done essays before, this was almost journalism.

01:28:28.160 --> 01:28:30.000
[Guest]: Yeah, this is, it is very journalistic.

01:28:30.000 --> 01:28:34.120
[Guest]: And in fact, all the journalists I know understand how difficult your job is.

01:28:34.120 --> 01:28:36.000
[Guest]: So it was very different territory for me.

01:28:36.000 --> 01:28:37.800
[Guest]: I learned through the process.

01:28:37.800 --> 01:28:41.080
[Guest]: I mean, what question crosses the line?

01:28:41.080 --> 01:28:44.120
[Guest]: And I say it in the book at one point, I don't know.

01:28:44.120 --> 01:28:48.320
[Guest]: I really don't know what line, what is that line, you know, when am I really pushing it

01:28:48.320 --> 01:28:52.520
[Guest]: and I'm not being insensitive and not seeing that I'm able to ask that question only because

01:28:52.520 --> 01:28:53.720
[Guest]: I'm privileged.

01:28:53.720 --> 01:28:57.200
[Guest]: I mean, I would not ask this question if not for that, I wouldn't, I wouldn't even think

01:28:57.200 --> 01:28:58.320
[Guest]: about asking that question.

01:28:58.320 --> 01:28:59.840
[Guest]: So I don't know what that line was.

01:28:59.840 --> 01:29:03.360
[Guest]: And I don't know, I may have transgressed, I'm sure.

01:29:03.360 --> 01:29:08.800
[Guest]: And but I was always aware of it, you know, I mean, you know, whenever I interview a maker,

01:29:08.800 --> 01:29:15.320
[Guest]: does the maker feel confident enough about that conversation to express displeasure in

01:29:15.320 --> 01:29:17.640
[Guest]: a question I asked, for example?

01:29:17.640 --> 01:29:18.640
[Guest]: I don't know.

01:29:18.640 --> 01:29:22.640
[Guest]: Because that's very, you will probably tell me, you know, if I asked you a question that

01:29:22.640 --> 01:29:26.400
[Guest]: cross line, you'll just take me off and say, boss, stop.

01:29:26.400 --> 01:29:27.400
[Guest]: Because we're both of equal privilege.

01:29:27.400 --> 01:29:28.400
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:29:28.400 --> 01:29:29.400
[Amit Varma]: So I can do that.

01:29:29.400 --> 01:29:30.680
[Guest]: No, the maker is not going to do that.

01:29:30.680 --> 01:29:33.880
[Guest]: The maker is going to look at me, TM Krishna, who is a great singer, I'm, like I said in

01:29:33.880 --> 01:29:38.400
[Guest]: the book, it's, you know, when I was looking back at the materials, when it hits you, right?

01:29:38.400 --> 01:29:42.920
[Guest]: The amount of respect I got by people who are like three times my age.

01:29:42.920 --> 01:29:47.800
[Guest]: You know, automatically, I mean, just by my presence, I was considered to be somebody

01:29:47.800 --> 01:29:50.480
[Guest]: who has to be respected, and somebody who has value.

01:29:50.480 --> 01:29:54.640
[Amit Varma]: And is there a danger that they want to please you, so they want to tell you what they think

01:29:54.640 --> 01:29:55.640
[Guest]: you want to hear?

01:29:55.640 --> 01:29:56.640
[Guest]: So, yeah.

01:29:56.640 --> 01:29:58.400
[Guest]: So that is where you build trust.

01:29:58.400 --> 01:29:59.920
[Guest]: That is where it's very important.

01:29:59.920 --> 01:30:00.920
[Guest]: You have to spend time.

01:30:00.920 --> 01:30:02.120
[Guest]: You have to spend time.

01:30:02.120 --> 01:30:05.920
[Guest]: There were interviews there where the trust came early, there were interviews where it

01:30:05.920 --> 01:30:09.840
[Guest]: took a long time where you could ask questions that were personal.

01:30:09.840 --> 01:30:14.960
[Guest]: So that completely depended on the relationship and the bond you were trying to make, however

01:30:14.960 --> 01:30:15.960
[Guest]: temporary it is.

01:30:15.960 --> 01:30:21.400
[Guest]: You know, I think the first thing was, does the person trust you, telling you all this,

01:30:21.400 --> 01:30:25.680
[Guest]: you know, sometimes it took a long time, it took a long time to the person feel comfortable

01:30:25.680 --> 01:30:30.840
[Guest]: to, you know, say these things, or, you know, I had to coax and ask these questions and

01:30:30.840 --> 01:30:31.840
[Guest]: move.

01:30:31.840 --> 01:30:35.880
[Guest]: Sometimes, sometimes they did not say to, there were interviews where they did not answer

01:30:35.880 --> 01:30:36.880
[Guest]: difficult questions.

01:30:36.880 --> 01:30:40.040
[Guest]: They were not willing to answer difficult questions, which is also fine.

01:30:40.040 --> 01:30:45.920
[Guest]: That also happens, but it's still, it is, you asked me a question for which, honestly

01:30:45.920 --> 01:30:50.080
[Guest]: speaking, there is, I don't know whether I did the right thing or the wrong thing.

01:30:50.080 --> 01:30:51.080
[Guest]: That's your question.

01:30:51.080 --> 01:30:52.080
[Guest]: I don't know.

01:30:52.080 --> 01:30:53.080
[Guest]: I mean, I really don't know.

01:30:53.080 --> 01:31:00.720
[Guest]: I, all I can say is that I remained absolutely truthful to what was said.

01:31:00.720 --> 01:31:01.720
[Guest]: Okay.

01:31:01.720 --> 01:31:02.960
[Guest]: I also took care.

01:31:02.960 --> 01:31:08.000
[Guest]: And that was the way I could respond to what you said is to, for example, change names

01:31:08.000 --> 01:31:13.400
[Guest]: when I felt the court were very sensitive, though they never asked me to, like you said,

01:31:13.400 --> 01:31:16.240
[Guest]: that even coming into the horizon, they could say that to me.

01:31:16.240 --> 01:31:19.440
[Amit Varma]: They wouldn't even have realized how this sort of journalism works.

01:31:19.440 --> 01:31:24.720
[Guest]: So I took the decision sometimes when I felt the courts were sensitive, that I changed

01:31:24.720 --> 01:31:25.720
[Guest]: the names.

01:31:25.720 --> 01:31:30.680
[Guest]: Those, I think those were ways by which I was also trying to say that this is not just

01:31:30.680 --> 01:31:31.680
[Guest]: information.

01:31:31.680 --> 01:31:35.440
[Guest]: This is not just people who are giving me something so that I could gloat for having

01:31:35.440 --> 01:31:40.560
[Guest]: written this radical book that, you know, that says these things, but these are people.

01:31:40.560 --> 01:31:41.560
[Guest]: These are real people.

01:31:41.560 --> 01:31:43.200
[Guest]: They are leading lives.

01:31:43.200 --> 01:31:44.400
[Guest]: And I need to respect that.

01:31:44.400 --> 01:31:46.440
[Guest]: I need to, I need to remember that.

01:31:46.440 --> 01:31:51.800
[Guest]: So I think that that was my way of, of remembering that, you know, when I wrote the book.

01:31:51.800 --> 01:31:55.920
[Amit Varma]: And before we come to the book itself, a final question about the craft that, you know, your

01:31:55.920 --> 01:31:57.560
[Amit Varma]: earlier books are essays.

01:31:57.560 --> 01:32:00.680
[Amit Varma]: This is journalistic nonfiction in a sense.

01:32:00.680 --> 01:32:01.800
[Amit Varma]: It's very accessible.

01:32:01.800 --> 01:32:04.880
[Amit Varma]: And as is obvious from the parts I read out very well-written, I think my listeners get

01:32:04.880 --> 01:32:07.320
[Amit Varma]: that and they should certainly buy the book.

01:32:07.320 --> 01:32:09.920
[Amit Varma]: So when it came to craft, what kind of thought did you put into it?

01:32:09.920 --> 01:32:10.920
[Amit Varma]: Who were your models?

01:32:10.920 --> 01:32:14.240
[Amit Varma]: Like, were there books that you looked at and said, yeah, it should be like this or

01:32:14.240 --> 01:32:17.440
[Guest]: none, none.

01:32:17.440 --> 01:32:25.280
[Guest]: So I did read a lot, but I, I think there was one thing that I kept in mind is I wanted

01:32:25.280 --> 01:32:28.520
[Guest]: to be as close to the language as possible.

01:32:28.520 --> 01:32:29.520
[Guest]: How do you do that?

01:32:29.520 --> 01:32:34.320
[Guest]: So for example, you know, I'll tell you why this, I felt sometime there could be a disconnection

01:32:34.320 --> 01:32:37.160
[Guest]: between commentary and quoting, right?

01:32:37.160 --> 01:32:39.700
[Guest]: So the quotes, many of them are in Tamil, right?

01:32:39.700 --> 01:32:42.840
[Guest]: So you're then transcribing it and then you're translating.

01:32:42.840 --> 01:32:48.880
[Guest]: How much can the English remain Tamil in its source, you know, I kept that in mind.

01:32:48.880 --> 01:32:53.440
[Guest]: So it remains as close to the quote as possible because it's possible to change the word to

01:32:53.440 --> 01:32:58.760
[Guest]: an extent where it almost transforms in its intonation, in its, in its messaging.

01:32:58.760 --> 01:32:59.760
[Guest]: So that was there.

01:32:59.760 --> 01:33:03.660
[Guest]: Then when I write commentary and commentary, I felt that there should be a connection between

01:33:03.660 --> 01:33:08.240
[Guest]: my style of writing and the voices of the makers, because ultimately this book is about

01:33:08.240 --> 01:33:09.740
[Guest]: the voice of the makers.

01:33:09.740 --> 01:33:14.140
[Guest]: So the way I tell the story must also be part of the voice that is coming.

01:33:14.140 --> 01:33:16.560
[Guest]: So I kept that in mind right through.

01:33:16.560 --> 01:33:21.380
[Guest]: So the style of writing in this is entirely different from anything I've written, okay,

01:33:21.380 --> 01:33:27.440
[Guest]: in terms of language usage, in terms of even vocabulary, it's very different.

01:33:27.440 --> 01:33:33.400
[Guest]: And that was because I said it should sound as close to the voices that the book is of,

01:33:33.400 --> 01:33:38.440
[Guest]: that is of the makers primarily, this is a book being told from the voice of the maker.

01:33:38.440 --> 01:33:42.880
[Guest]: So that's those are the things I kept in mind, because I felt then there'll be fluidity in

01:33:42.880 --> 01:33:44.320
[Guest]: reading.

01:33:44.320 --> 01:33:50.160
[Guest]: If I remained a kind of an academic kind of a tone, then there's a disconnect between

01:33:50.160 --> 01:33:54.040
[Amit Varma]: that and the voice of the maker, which is full of the book.

01:33:54.040 --> 01:33:58.160
[Amit Varma]: So though I won't understand it for the Tamil listeners of the show, is there an illustration

01:33:58.160 --> 01:34:03.960
[Amit Varma]: of that you can give about a translating decision that you took?

01:34:03.960 --> 01:34:08.360
[Guest]: For example, somebody made some people, the one important thing decision is that we also

01:34:08.360 --> 01:34:13.760
[Guest]: wanted to document the various words, technical words in Tamil itself.

01:34:13.760 --> 01:34:17.040
[Guest]: So you have words like kottu tattu, vettu tattu, which are all completely technical

01:34:17.040 --> 01:34:18.040
[Guest]: Tamil words.

01:34:18.040 --> 01:34:19.920
[Guest]: And it was very important that they remain that way.

01:34:19.920 --> 01:34:24.920
[Guest]: I give descriptions once in a while to remind the reader, but we wanted it that way, because

01:34:24.920 --> 01:34:27.680
[Guest]: you wanted to feel what that vocabulary is.

01:34:27.680 --> 01:34:29.520
[Guest]: I'll give you an example of something.

01:34:29.520 --> 01:34:34.600
[Guest]: So many times, you know, you retain sounds and retain these expressions that are said.

01:34:34.600 --> 01:34:38.360
[Guest]: Here is one from Varadhan.

01:34:38.360 --> 01:34:41.240
[Guest]: So I'll start with a paragraph.

01:34:41.240 --> 01:34:46.280
[Guest]: The most beautiful part of our conversation was the elegant simplicity with which he described

01:34:46.280 --> 01:34:48.200
[Guest]: the music of artists.

01:34:48.200 --> 01:34:51.840
[Guest]: M. Chandrasekhar violinist was set for Madurai Subbu.

01:34:51.840 --> 01:34:59.320
[Guest]: Now was set for Madurai Subbu is very much from Tamil, that means they are a team together.

01:34:59.320 --> 01:35:00.320
[Guest]: Okay.

01:35:00.320 --> 01:35:04.040
[Guest]: We retain, I retained it because I wanted that sound.

01:35:04.040 --> 01:35:07.080
[Guest]: So and it's then it's Varadhan's voice, right?

01:35:07.080 --> 01:35:10.840
[Guest]: Otherwise it becomes my voice and Varadhan says basically, M. Chandrasekhar was set for

01:35:10.840 --> 01:35:11.840
[Guest]: Madurai Subbu.

01:35:11.840 --> 01:35:12.840
[Guest]: Rumba super.

01:35:12.840 --> 01:35:18.000
[Guest]: Okay, that's a classic Tamil expression, rumba is of course Tamil.

01:35:18.000 --> 01:35:21.640
[Guest]: At a concert in in Mettur, people just lifted him up.

01:35:21.640 --> 01:35:23.280
[Guest]: He played so well.

01:35:23.280 --> 01:35:27.400
[Guest]: Of Ramabhadran's playing technique, he said he provided the groove so beautifully, it

01:35:27.400 --> 01:35:30.080
[Guest]: would come along like jile jile jile.

01:35:30.080 --> 01:35:35.720
[Guest]: Now, all this was very important for the way I we took the courts and retained its Tamilness

01:35:35.720 --> 01:35:37.120
[Guest]: to that extent.

01:35:37.120 --> 01:35:43.640
[Guest]: And that was part of a decision that I made that it should remain close to the sound possible.

01:35:43.640 --> 01:35:48.480
[Guest]: I remember there's some expression called sweet, I remember my editor Ajitha and I had

01:35:48.480 --> 01:35:53.880
[Guest]: this huge discussion about this expression that Johnson or somebody says, there should

01:35:53.880 --> 01:35:58.640
[Guest]: be this sweetness, the make something to this effect, I don't remember the point, but something

01:35:58.640 --> 01:36:02.760
[Guest]: the fact that sweetness in sound or something like that, you know, which doesn't make any

01:36:02.760 --> 01:36:03.760
[Guest]: sense.

01:36:03.760 --> 01:36:07.560
[Guest]: But it's an expression of an idea, a feeling, right?

01:36:07.560 --> 01:36:12.600
[Guest]: We retained all that as close as possible to the Tamil original as possible.

01:36:12.600 --> 01:36:13.800
[Guest]: So that is a very important part.

01:36:13.800 --> 01:36:17.120
[Guest]: So because when you're reading this book, you're not only reading the stories, but actually

01:36:17.120 --> 01:36:22.280
[Guest]: immersing yourself in language, in the culture, in the way things are said, in the way things

01:36:22.280 --> 01:36:23.280
[Guest]: are exchanged.

01:36:23.280 --> 01:36:25.960
[Guest]: And that was very important for me.

01:36:25.960 --> 01:36:31.880
[Amit Varma]: No, so I recently did an episode on translation, recorded an episode on the art of translation

01:36:31.880 --> 01:36:35.680
[Amit Varma]: with Arunabha Sinha, who's done more than 50 Bengali novels, though it will broadcast

01:36:35.680 --> 01:36:37.040
[Amit Varma]: after this one.

01:36:37.040 --> 01:36:40.440
[Amit Varma]: But one of the interesting things I came across while researching for that was this quote

01:36:40.440 --> 01:36:45.040
[Amit Varma]: by Richard Pevear, about translation being a dialogue between two languages.

01:36:45.040 --> 01:36:49.200
[Amit Varma]: And what you just said about the example that so and so was set for so and so, you know,

01:36:49.200 --> 01:36:51.520
[Amit Varma]: almost seems like you're modifying English as well.

01:36:51.520 --> 01:36:54.040
[Guest]: So who knows, that could take off because it's a...

01:36:54.040 --> 01:36:59.560
[Guest]: It's very important that we think in that in those terms, especially in India, and wherever

01:36:59.560 --> 01:37:03.840
[Guest]: English is spoken, I think there are many kinds of, you know, this language snootiness

01:37:03.840 --> 01:37:05.680
[Guest]: is also something we're all obsessed with.

01:37:05.680 --> 01:37:09.360
[Guest]: I think there are different kinds of English, there are different, you know, even in whether

01:37:09.360 --> 01:37:12.480
[Guest]: it's Kannada or Tamil, there are different kinds of Tamil, different kinds of Hindi,

01:37:12.480 --> 01:37:16.080
[Guest]: there is a different forms of idea of English too.

01:37:16.080 --> 01:37:22.160
[Guest]: And it's very closely connected with Malayalam or with Hindi or with Tamil and these terms

01:37:22.160 --> 01:37:23.160
[Amit Varma]: that come into being.

01:37:23.160 --> 01:37:26.600
[Amit Varma]: And that's a feature, not a bug, if you're, you know, taking some of that local flavor

01:37:26.600 --> 01:37:28.680
[Guest]: and becoming something of your own.

01:37:28.680 --> 01:37:29.920
[Guest]: Absolutely, absolutely.

01:37:29.920 --> 01:37:34.320
[Guest]: That flexibility is what really makes language interesting.

01:37:34.320 --> 01:37:35.320
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:37:35.320 --> 01:37:36.320
[Guest]: Right?

01:37:36.320 --> 01:37:37.320
[Guest]: If not, you would not, language would die.

01:37:37.320 --> 01:37:41.760
[Amit Varma]: I mean, we have language Nazis saying that, you know, pre-poning is not a word and all

01:37:41.760 --> 01:37:42.760
[Guest]: of that.

01:37:42.760 --> 01:37:43.760
[Guest]: I'm saying everybody uses pre-poning.

01:37:43.760 --> 01:37:48.760
[Guest]: My dad used to keep saying that, by the way, I used to say pre-poning, he used to say advanced.

01:37:48.760 --> 01:37:53.600
[Amit Varma]: Pre-poning, one, it has become a word because so many people have used it and two, it's

01:37:53.600 --> 01:37:54.600
[Guest]: a lovely word.

01:37:54.600 --> 01:37:55.600
[Guest]: It works.

01:37:55.600 --> 01:37:56.600
[Guest]: Yeah, it does work.

01:37:56.600 --> 01:37:57.600
[Guest]: It means I like the word.

01:37:57.600 --> 01:37:58.600
[Guest]: I'm sticking with pre-poning.

01:37:58.600 --> 01:38:01.440
[Guest]: So by the way, that's another thing that I love creating words.

01:38:01.440 --> 01:38:07.520
[Guest]: So sometimes I just land up just creating this word and then we'd have this, my editor

01:38:07.520 --> 01:38:09.560
[Guest]: and I would say, what is this word you've used?

01:38:09.560 --> 01:38:11.800
[Guest]: I said, no, I just created it.

01:38:11.800 --> 01:38:14.120
[Amit Varma]: So that's I think part of the.

01:38:14.120 --> 01:38:15.400
[Amit Varma]: And then what does your editor do?

01:38:15.400 --> 01:38:17.240
[Guest]: It depends on the word.

01:38:17.240 --> 01:38:21.320
[Guest]: And then we argue about it and if it's acceptable, we let it go.

01:38:21.320 --> 01:38:22.320
[Guest]: Sometimes I know you just can't use it.

01:38:22.320 --> 01:38:23.320
[Guest]: Give me an example of a neologism.

01:38:23.320 --> 01:38:28.880
[Guest]: So I'll give you one from the older book, Syllabomelodic Identity.

01:38:28.880 --> 01:38:29.880
[Guest]: Syllabomelodic Identity.

01:38:29.880 --> 01:38:34.120
[Guest]: It comes from Southern music that is entirely my creation.

01:38:34.120 --> 01:38:40.840
[Guest]: So when I said that language in music is not about the word, but it's about the syllable

01:38:40.840 --> 01:38:43.300
[Guest]: and the movement of the syllable musically.

01:38:43.300 --> 01:38:48.000
[Guest]: So I called it Syllabomelodic Identity.

01:38:48.000 --> 01:38:49.000
[Amit Varma]: Quite beautiful.

01:38:49.000 --> 01:38:51.680
[Amit Varma]: We'll have to sort of discuss that at a separate time.

01:38:51.680 --> 01:38:53.040
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of get to the book.

01:38:53.040 --> 01:38:57.400
[Amit Varma]: And one of the first things that struck me because it's on page one, that's why it struck

01:38:57.400 --> 01:39:03.720
[Amit Varma]: me, is your whole notion when you're talking about Nanganallur, you write, quote, Nanganallur

01:39:03.720 --> 01:39:09.400
[Amit Varma]: is a congested urban village, more specifically a Brahman enclave within a village, stop quote.

01:39:09.400 --> 01:39:12.800
[Amit Varma]: And then later you say, quote, I've always thought of Nanganallur as a poor man's mile

01:39:12.800 --> 01:39:16.320
[Amit Varma]: apart, a cliched symbol of Brahmanism, stop quote.

01:39:16.320 --> 01:39:22.120
[Amit Varma]: But one theme that sort of comes up at times during your book is how geographical location

01:39:22.120 --> 01:39:24.640
[Amit Varma]: and social location are so interlinked.

01:39:24.640 --> 01:39:25.640
[Guest]: It's very important.

01:39:25.640 --> 01:39:27.080
[Guest]: It's true of every city.

01:39:27.080 --> 01:39:28.360
[Guest]: It's true of every place.

01:39:28.360 --> 01:39:32.000
[Guest]: You know, we think that urbanization somehow dissolves all this.

01:39:32.000 --> 01:39:34.440
[Guest]: We have this notion that in the village, it's more stark.

01:39:34.440 --> 01:39:35.440
[Guest]: It is more stark.

01:39:35.440 --> 01:39:38.360
[Guest]: There's no doubt that the lines are sharper and you can see it.

01:39:38.360 --> 01:39:40.400
[Amit Varma]: I think urbanization helps, but nothing is a panacea.

01:39:40.400 --> 01:39:41.400
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:39:41.400 --> 01:39:44.960
[Guest]: It helps in certain ways because transactions change and requirements change.

01:39:44.960 --> 01:39:49.760
[Guest]: But if you look at any city, look at Mumbai, look at any other city, you will find these

01:39:49.760 --> 01:39:52.300
[Guest]: multiple enclaves that are created, right?

01:39:52.300 --> 01:39:56.200
[Guest]: You know, for example, who's going to live in South Bombay, you know, you know, all these

01:39:56.200 --> 01:39:59.160
[Guest]: things, you know, where the South Indian population is.

01:39:59.160 --> 01:40:03.600
[Guest]: So, you know, and so, you know, some people actually, my friends of mine said, how can

01:40:03.600 --> 01:40:06.800
[Guest]: you start the book by saying you thought of it as a Brahman enclave?

01:40:06.800 --> 01:40:07.800
[Guest]: They got upset.

01:40:07.800 --> 01:40:10.040
[Guest]: I said, but that's exactly how I've seen it.

01:40:10.040 --> 01:40:11.760
[Guest]: You see it that way too.

01:40:11.760 --> 01:40:16.920
[Guest]: Because if you think of Nanganallur, it was a place where people who did not live in Mylapore,

01:40:16.920 --> 01:40:20.720
[Guest]: which is a middle class Brahman enclave, moved to at some point of time.

01:40:20.720 --> 01:40:22.440
[Amit Varma]: So it's like Bandra is to South Bombay.

01:40:22.440 --> 01:40:23.440
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:40:23.440 --> 01:40:24.640
[Guest]: I mean, we all have it.

01:40:24.640 --> 01:40:30.400
[Guest]: So it's very important for us to identify that within our city structures, within our,

01:40:30.400 --> 01:40:34.280
[Guest]: you know, habitations, these, none of these habitations are accidental.

01:40:34.280 --> 01:40:37.200
[Guest]: We're making these decisions because of so many reasons.

01:40:37.200 --> 01:40:39.000
[Guest]: So we're looking for similar people.

01:40:39.000 --> 01:40:42.040
[Guest]: So when I say similar people, what are we saying, we look at all these markers, we're

01:40:42.040 --> 01:40:46.240
[Guest]: looking at caste, we're looking at school, we're looking at many things, who is going

01:40:46.240 --> 01:40:48.160
[Guest]: to be my children's classmate in this school?

01:40:48.160 --> 01:40:49.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:40:49.160 --> 01:40:53.240
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it's not necessary, like we said earlier, that you're thinking of caste per se, but

01:40:53.240 --> 01:40:54.720
[Guest]: it's what your comfort zone is.

01:40:54.720 --> 01:40:56.920
[Guest]: And your comfort zone is designed by all these things.

01:40:56.920 --> 01:41:02.440
[Guest]: I mean, I mean, you know, how many of how many people be comfortable to live in a gay

01:41:02.440 --> 01:41:03.440
[Guest]: neighborhood?

01:41:03.440 --> 01:41:05.840
[Guest]: You know, because they look at it and say, oh, I don't want to be here.

01:41:05.840 --> 01:41:10.360
[Guest]: You may not even think that you processed it that way, but you are making these decisions.

01:41:10.360 --> 01:41:15.400
[Guest]: And therefore cities themselves have these little little pockets that function in those

01:41:15.400 --> 01:41:16.400
[Guest]: in those manners.

01:41:16.400 --> 01:41:18.200
[Guest]: And that's why Nanganallur is a certain pocket.

01:41:18.200 --> 01:41:21.760
[Guest]: Even within Mylapore and Alwarpet, there's a difference because there is certain money

01:41:21.760 --> 01:41:24.440
[Guest]: involved and you see those distinctions coming in.

01:41:24.440 --> 01:41:32.080
[Guest]: So all our habitations, all our city living is filled with these kind of, I had this huge

01:41:32.080 --> 01:41:36.600
[Guest]: argument with a man from Kolkata about this, you know, Kolkata is not like that.

01:41:36.600 --> 01:41:39.680
[Guest]: So I said, I'm going to put a wager on this one.

01:41:39.680 --> 01:41:40.680
[Guest]: I don't know Kolkata.

01:41:40.680 --> 01:41:44.760
[Guest]: He said, okay, he's promised to spend two months about it and get back to me.

01:41:44.760 --> 01:41:47.000
[Guest]: I said, I'm sure you can draw these lines everywhere.

01:41:47.000 --> 01:41:48.000
[Guest]: He did.

01:41:48.000 --> 01:41:49.000
[Guest]: He's not yet got back.

01:41:49.000 --> 01:41:50.000
[Guest]: I'm waiting.

01:41:50.000 --> 01:41:51.000
[Amit Varma]: Okay, he's run away.

01:41:51.000 --> 01:41:53.840
[Amit Varma]: I'm listening to this Kolkata person kindly bite the bullet.

01:41:53.840 --> 01:41:57.360
[Amit Varma]: It will help society if you confess that you that you were wrong.

01:41:57.360 --> 01:42:01.600
[Amit Varma]: No, but I got to tell you, I mean, although caste is not necessarily involved, there is

01:42:01.600 --> 01:42:07.200
[Amit Varma]: more class and coolness, but I live on Johu-Varsova link road, which is basically next to Varsova

01:42:07.200 --> 01:42:08.840
[Amit Varma]: and very far from Johu.

01:42:08.840 --> 01:42:11.360
[Amit Varma]: But all my neighbors say, oh, we live in Upper Johu.

01:42:11.360 --> 01:42:12.360
[Unknown]: Yeah, exactly.

01:42:12.360 --> 01:42:17.720
[Guest]: It's the same kind of absolutely shit that's going down there, though, in this case, it's

01:42:17.720 --> 01:42:18.720
[Guest]: more.

01:42:18.720 --> 01:42:21.680
[Guest]: We live in a place called Nilangare now in Chennai.

01:42:21.680 --> 01:42:24.840
[Guest]: The road we live in is not the cool road, the next road.

01:42:24.840 --> 01:42:27.360
[Guest]: So anybody I say Nilangare, oh, you live in Kashirena Drive.

01:42:27.360 --> 01:42:29.720
[Guest]: I said, no, I don't live on Kashirena Drive.

01:42:29.720 --> 01:42:32.720
[Guest]: I live in this little thing called Singaravelento street.

01:42:32.720 --> 01:42:35.280
[Amit Varma]: Kashirena Drive sounds very nice.

01:42:35.280 --> 01:42:37.040
[Amit Varma]: If you were living there, I would have visited you.

01:42:37.040 --> 01:42:38.040
[Guest]: But now I'm not.

01:42:38.040 --> 01:42:41.600
[Amit Varma]: No, you're not going to come to my place.

01:42:41.600 --> 01:42:43.720
[Amit Varma]: So tell me, who are Sebastian and Svans?

01:42:43.720 --> 01:42:44.720
[Guest]: Give me the background of this.

01:42:44.720 --> 01:42:51.440
[Guest]: So Sebastian's, all these names have their Tamil equivalents, it's Sevityan.

01:42:51.440 --> 01:42:59.960
[Guest]: And Sevityan seems to be from my research, the oldest full Mridangam maker I can trace.

01:42:59.960 --> 01:43:05.040
[Guest]: So Sebastian's cousin Ratnam is somebody who is in the cover of the book.

01:43:05.040 --> 01:43:06.040
[Guest]: He lived in Madurai.

01:43:06.040 --> 01:43:07.860
[Guest]: He'd moved to Madurai when he was much younger.

01:43:07.860 --> 01:43:12.160
[Guest]: But he identified and came to, told Sebastian and his father that, you know, you have so

01:43:12.160 --> 01:43:14.920
[Guest]: many Mridangam players in Tanjavur, why are you making Tawals?

01:43:14.920 --> 01:43:15.920
[Unknown]: This is 1910s, 1920s.

01:43:15.920 --> 01:43:17.400
[Unknown]: This must be around that time.

01:43:17.400 --> 01:43:21.400
[Guest]: See, other thing, you know, timeline's very difficult in oral stories.

01:43:21.400 --> 01:43:23.800
[Guest]: You don't know exactly when you're trying to trace it.

01:43:23.800 --> 01:43:25.880
[Guest]: So I'll place it around that time.

01:43:25.880 --> 01:43:27.400
[Guest]: And he says, what are you guys doing with Tawal?

01:43:27.400 --> 01:43:29.600
[Guest]: You guys have so many Mridangam players in Tanjavur.

01:43:29.600 --> 01:43:32.640
[Guest]: In Tanjavur, you had a lot of Mridangam players because there was Harikatha happening, there

01:43:32.640 --> 01:43:34.960
[Guest]: was Bharatanatyam, then called Sadir.

01:43:34.960 --> 01:43:36.480
[Guest]: Sadir was happening.

01:43:36.480 --> 01:43:39.320
[Guest]: And you also had concerts, Carnatic concerts happening.

01:43:39.320 --> 01:43:41.940
[Guest]: So you had a lot of people playing the Mridangam.

01:43:41.940 --> 01:43:46.080
[Guest]: So the market was there and he's saying, why are you not exploiting the market?

01:43:46.080 --> 01:43:48.480
[Guest]: So Sebastian begins.

01:43:48.480 --> 01:43:53.160
[Guest]: He begins first working with Tanjavur Vaidyanath Iyer.

01:43:53.160 --> 01:43:56.000
[Guest]: And that's when the story, their family story begins.

01:43:56.000 --> 01:44:00.960
[Guest]: And Sebastian's three sons turn out to be the most important three names in Mridangam

01:44:00.960 --> 01:44:01.960
[Guest]: making.

01:44:01.960 --> 01:44:09.080
[Guest]: Shengol, the oldest, probably, probably not the most skilled of the three.

01:44:09.080 --> 01:44:10.800
[Guest]: Second is Parland.

01:44:10.800 --> 01:44:14.360
[Guest]: So Parland's actual name is Fernandes.

01:44:14.360 --> 01:44:16.640
[Guest]: And the third is Shetty, okay, whose name is Anthony.

01:44:16.640 --> 01:44:20.880
[Amit Varma]: And the point to note is that, you know, there's a distinction, as you point out in your book,

01:44:20.880 --> 01:44:26.560
[Amit Varma]: which people make between converted Christians and, you know, Christians from abroad.

01:44:26.560 --> 01:44:30.120
[Amit Varma]: This sort of carries the implication that these are actually lower caste people who

01:44:30.120 --> 01:44:31.200
[Amit Varma]: converted to Christians.

01:44:31.200 --> 01:44:32.200
[Amit Varma]: So they're still lower caste.

01:44:32.200 --> 01:44:34.320
[Guest]: It doesn't matter if they're Christians, right?

01:44:34.320 --> 01:44:35.320
[Guest]: This remains.

01:44:35.320 --> 01:44:36.320
[Guest]: That remains, that remains.

01:44:36.320 --> 01:44:41.880
[Guest]: The notion that, like you said, they've become Christians does not change the, move them

01:44:41.880 --> 01:44:43.120
[Guest]: away from the caste identity.

01:44:43.120 --> 01:44:44.760
[Guest]: You can check out, but you can never leave.

01:44:44.760 --> 01:44:45.760
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:44:45.760 --> 01:44:49.080
[Guest]: And then in a way you're also saying that's why they're still there.

01:44:49.080 --> 01:44:50.760
[Guest]: I mean, upper caste people are not going to convert.

01:44:50.760 --> 01:44:52.120
[Guest]: Why should we convert?

01:44:52.120 --> 01:44:53.120
[Guest]: You know?

01:44:53.120 --> 01:44:57.120
[Guest]: So there's that whole narration that's going subconsciously in this.

01:44:57.120 --> 01:44:58.120
[Guest]: So they've converted.

01:44:58.120 --> 01:45:02.200
[Guest]: I mean, I tried, I mean, again, the whole notion that who's converted, who's not converted,

01:45:02.200 --> 01:45:03.200
[Guest]: you know, we don't know.

01:45:03.200 --> 01:45:05.720
[Guest]: So they've seemed to have embraced Christianity.

01:45:05.720 --> 01:45:10.800
[Guest]: I would say early 20th century, I mean, late 19th century, maybe early 20th centuries when

01:45:10.800 --> 01:45:14.520
[Guest]: they seem to have that period, they've embraced Christianity.

01:45:14.520 --> 01:45:19.000
[Guest]: And this family lived in the street called Keerthikar Street, okay, and they still have

01:45:19.000 --> 01:45:20.000
[Guest]: their homes there.

01:45:20.000 --> 01:45:21.000
[Guest]: In Tanjavur.

01:45:21.000 --> 01:45:22.000
[Guest]: In Tanjavur.

01:45:22.000 --> 01:45:28.280
[Guest]: And these three brothers start going to all these towns nearby, Kumbakonam, you know,

01:45:28.280 --> 01:45:32.360
[Guest]: Myladurai, Tiruvannamalur, all these places and doing work.

01:45:32.360 --> 01:45:36.880
[Guest]: And at the same time, you have this Vaidyanath Iyer, who becomes this great teacher.

01:45:36.880 --> 01:45:41.840
[Guest]: And then you have the biggest superstar of Carnatic percussion, Palgat Maniyar, moving

01:45:41.840 --> 01:45:42.840
[Guest]: to Tanjavur.

01:45:42.840 --> 01:45:43.840
[Guest]: And why does he move?

01:45:43.840 --> 01:45:46.160
[Guest]: Because the best makers are there.

01:45:46.160 --> 01:45:48.000
[Guest]: And Paraland is there.

01:45:48.000 --> 01:45:54.980
[Guest]: And then, because of such a huge stature that Maniyar has within the whole Carnatic imagination,

01:45:54.980 --> 01:46:00.120
[Guest]: the makers that make for Maniyar automatically become those that everybody else seeks, because

01:46:00.120 --> 01:46:01.800
[Guest]: they want that kind of sound.

01:46:01.800 --> 01:46:06.920
[Guest]: So Maniyar's most powerful competitor was Palani Subramaniam Pillai.

01:46:06.920 --> 01:46:11.480
[Guest]: And there is this tussle for makers between them, you know, and Palani is not a Brahmin.

01:46:11.480 --> 01:46:16.760
[Guest]: So there is a tussle there between them, not only because of abilities, because of caste

01:46:16.760 --> 01:46:21.480
[Guest]: differences, but there's also a tussle for getting the best maker for themselves.

01:46:21.480 --> 01:46:25.160
[Guest]: So there is this multiple little competitions that are happening.

01:46:25.160 --> 01:46:30.940
[Guest]: And from Paraland, if you see, in fact, that family tree is mind boggling.

01:46:30.940 --> 01:46:35.800
[Guest]: Now there are about, I don't know how many makers in that family, I think 30 plus.

01:46:35.800 --> 01:46:40.520
[Guest]: And that whole family is now in the business of making mridangams.

01:46:40.520 --> 01:46:41.640
[Guest]: This is Tanjavur.

01:46:41.640 --> 01:46:45.000
[Guest]: Then you have a tradition that is happening in Chennai, then Madras.

01:46:45.000 --> 01:46:47.340
[Guest]: You have Telugu speaking people making Madras.

01:46:47.340 --> 01:46:50.640
[Guest]: You also have a pretty old tradition in near Palakkad.

01:46:50.640 --> 01:46:52.600
[Guest]: Then you have a tradition in Andhra.

01:46:52.600 --> 01:46:55.000
[Guest]: So you have other pockets also.

01:46:55.000 --> 01:47:00.400
[Guest]: But the major contribution and the influence comes from the Tanjavur tradition.

01:47:00.400 --> 01:47:06.680
[Amit Varma]: And I found one story really entertaining and telling about how Mani Iyer wants a particular

01:47:06.680 --> 01:47:11.280
[Unknown]: kind of sound on his left side, which Palani gets.

01:47:11.280 --> 01:47:15.800
[Amit Varma]: But even though they have the same maker, which is Paraland, as you said, if I pronounced

01:47:15.800 --> 01:47:16.800
[Amit Varma]: it correctly.

01:47:16.800 --> 01:47:18.800
[Guest]: Throughout this episode, I have pronounced everything wrong.

01:47:18.800 --> 01:47:22.360
[Guest]: Actually you have done a pretty decent job, by the way.

01:47:22.360 --> 01:47:26.960
[Amit Varma]: But you know, I have no bones about my bad pronunciation in every single language.

01:47:26.960 --> 01:47:29.080
[Amit Varma]: That's what, you know, being half Bengali does.

01:47:29.080 --> 01:47:31.280
[Amit Varma]: You pronounce everything wrong in every language.

01:47:31.280 --> 01:47:34.280
[Amit Varma]: So tell us a story about that.

01:47:34.280 --> 01:47:35.280
[Guest]: So that's a very interesting story.

01:47:35.280 --> 01:47:40.360
[Guest]: This is a very famous story that has been told many times in the folklore.

01:47:40.360 --> 01:47:43.560
[Guest]: And it's a very telling story, like you said, it's a very interesting story.

01:47:43.560 --> 01:47:45.940
[Guest]: So basically the Mridangam has two sides.

01:47:45.940 --> 01:47:50.360
[Guest]: The one that you see, if you just go on YouTube, click any Carnatic concert, you will see the

01:47:50.360 --> 01:47:52.480
[Guest]: black spot on the right side.

01:47:52.480 --> 01:47:53.480
[Guest]: That's the dominant side.

01:47:53.480 --> 01:47:57.800
[Guest]: Then you have a bassy end like the Daga of the tabla, which on the left, which you don't

01:47:57.800 --> 01:47:58.800
[Guest]: see.

01:47:58.800 --> 01:48:02.880
[Guest]: So Palani was known for his, when Palani, by the way, is not his name, his name is Subramaniam

01:48:02.880 --> 01:48:03.880
[Amit Varma]: Pillai.

01:48:03.880 --> 01:48:04.880
[Amit Varma]: Palani is a place.

01:48:04.880 --> 01:48:05.880
[Amit Varma]: Apologies.

01:48:05.880 --> 01:48:06.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:48:06.880 --> 01:48:07.880
[Guest]: Okay.

01:48:07.880 --> 01:48:08.880
[Guest]: So we all call him Palani.

01:48:08.880 --> 01:48:09.880
[Guest]: No apologies.

01:48:09.880 --> 01:48:10.880
[Guest]: We all call him Palani.

01:48:10.880 --> 01:48:11.880
[Guest]: So that's a very, very South Indian thing.

01:48:11.880 --> 01:48:12.880
[Guest]: We start talking, you know, we call Aryakudi.

01:48:12.880 --> 01:48:13.880
[Guest]: Aryakudi, Ramanuja Yengar is his name.

01:48:13.880 --> 01:48:14.880
[Guest]: Aryakudi is the place.

01:48:14.880 --> 01:48:18.280
[Guest]: We start calling them by the place.

01:48:18.280 --> 01:48:20.360
[Guest]: So Palani's left is like exquisite.

01:48:20.360 --> 01:48:26.600
[Guest]: He gets this little, very interesting baritone kind of movement, kind of sound.

01:48:26.600 --> 01:48:28.600
[Guest]: And he has a special technique also.

01:48:28.600 --> 01:48:32.480
[Guest]: Now there is this battle between Maniyar and Palani.

01:48:32.480 --> 01:48:35.520
[Guest]: Nobody can, I mean, they had, they were congenial with each other.

01:48:35.520 --> 01:48:41.160
[Guest]: They were friends and they even shared diocese, but yet there is this little thing.

01:48:41.160 --> 01:48:47.080
[Guest]: And but the sound of Palani's on this left, on the base side, Maniyar could never get.

01:48:47.080 --> 01:48:48.080
[Guest]: Okay.

01:48:48.080 --> 01:48:52.560
[Guest]: So in that competition, Paraland is making mridangams for both these people.

01:48:52.560 --> 01:48:58.920
[Guest]: So once Paraland has gone to Trichy, where Palani lived, done some work and come back.

01:48:58.920 --> 01:48:59.920
[Guest]: So Maniyar doesn't stop.

01:48:59.920 --> 01:49:02.640
[Guest]: He says, okay, what do you do there?

01:49:02.640 --> 01:49:05.760
[Guest]: I did some couple of, I made a couple of mridangams for him.

01:49:05.760 --> 01:49:07.880
[Guest]: What do you do special for him?

01:49:07.880 --> 01:49:10.200
[Guest]: No, I just did what I do for you.

01:49:10.200 --> 01:49:11.200
[Guest]: Really?

01:49:11.200 --> 01:49:12.200
[Guest]: Are you sure?

01:49:12.200 --> 01:49:13.680
[Guest]: Then he leaves it.

01:49:13.680 --> 01:49:15.120
[Guest]: But he's like, he really wants to know.

01:49:15.120 --> 01:49:16.600
[Guest]: He comes back and keeps bothering Paraland.

01:49:16.600 --> 01:49:19.800
[Guest]: But I never get the sound on the left like he does.

01:49:19.800 --> 01:49:20.800
[Guest]: You do something for him.

01:49:20.800 --> 01:49:21.800
[Guest]: No, sir.

01:49:21.800 --> 01:49:22.800
[Guest]: I do the same thing.

01:49:22.800 --> 01:49:27.000
[Guest]: So this goes on and finally says, you have to make a mridangam for me so that the left

01:49:27.000 --> 01:49:30.120
[Guest]: sound is as good as Palani's left sound.

01:49:30.120 --> 01:49:33.800
[Guest]: So this man does it once, does it twice, does it thrice, every time Maniyar comes and says,

01:49:33.800 --> 01:49:34.800
[Guest]: this is not it.

01:49:34.800 --> 01:49:37.520
[Guest]: It's not, I'm not getting the same effect that he gets.

01:49:37.520 --> 01:49:40.520
[Guest]: Finally, Maniyar is off to some city for a concert.

01:49:40.520 --> 01:49:42.840
[Guest]: So Paraland tells him, you go and come, sir.

01:49:42.840 --> 01:49:45.280
[Guest]: By the time you come, I will get it organized for you.

01:49:45.280 --> 01:49:48.400
[Guest]: I will get special skin also for it.

01:49:48.400 --> 01:49:49.400
[Guest]: He comes back.

01:49:49.400 --> 01:49:50.400
[Guest]: He's testing all mridangams.

01:49:50.400 --> 01:49:52.760
[Guest]: He says, where is that mridangam?

01:49:52.760 --> 01:49:55.560
[Guest]: The family were telling me soon that mridangam started, they start calling the mridangam

01:49:55.560 --> 01:49:56.560
[Guest]: itself Palani mridangam.

01:49:56.560 --> 01:49:57.560
[Guest]: So it's interesting.

01:49:57.560 --> 01:50:03.040
[Guest]: So he comes back and then he tests that one.

01:50:03.040 --> 01:50:04.040
[Guest]: He says, no.

01:50:04.040 --> 01:50:07.320
[Guest]: I think by this time, Paraland has had enough of it, right?

01:50:07.320 --> 01:50:11.480
[Guest]: So he turns around and says, sir, I will say something you should not misunderstand.

01:50:11.480 --> 01:50:12.480
[Guest]: He says, what?

01:50:12.480 --> 01:50:16.760
[Guest]: He says, that sound is in his hand, not in the skin.

01:50:16.760 --> 01:50:18.220
[Guest]: So Maniyar is shocked.

01:50:18.220 --> 01:50:21.600
[Guest]: So I can't imagine anybody who would probably tell Maniyar this, right?

01:50:21.600 --> 01:50:23.280
[Guest]: Because he's this huge figure.

01:50:23.280 --> 01:50:27.680
[Guest]: Maniyar is like, you're telling me that I'll never get this sound all my life?

01:50:27.680 --> 01:50:28.680
[Guest]: That's in his hand.

01:50:28.680 --> 01:50:30.400
[Guest]: So in Tamil, the word is kai vaag, okay?

01:50:30.400 --> 01:50:31.960
[Guest]: We say it also for cooking, right?

01:50:31.960 --> 01:50:35.560
[Guest]: When people, you make the same dish, somebody, somebody have is in the hair or green fingers.

01:50:35.560 --> 01:50:37.040
[Guest]: It's very similar to that.

01:50:37.040 --> 01:50:39.560
[Guest]: So he says that sound is in Palani's hand.

01:50:39.560 --> 01:50:41.240
[Guest]: So almost Maniyar gives up.

01:50:41.240 --> 01:50:47.040
[Guest]: But what's interesting is, is that this is a story that has been retold many times.

01:50:47.040 --> 01:50:51.880
[Guest]: And that also tells you about that relationship between Maniyar and Palani, which is actually

01:50:51.880 --> 01:50:52.880
[Amit Varma]: very unusual.

01:50:52.880 --> 01:50:57.760
[Guest]: It's like an outlier, definitely unusual, which is why I found that relationship extremely

01:50:57.760 --> 01:50:58.760
[Guest]: intriguing.

01:50:58.760 --> 01:50:59.960
[Guest]: I wish Palani was alive.

01:50:59.960 --> 01:51:01.200
[Guest]: I wish Maniyar was alive.

01:51:01.200 --> 01:51:06.400
[Guest]: I could interview them separately and find out what there was because it's a complicated

01:51:06.400 --> 01:51:07.480
[Guest]: relationship.

01:51:07.480 --> 01:51:12.440
[Guest]: But in that relationship, there are these interesting what you could call transgressions

01:51:12.440 --> 01:51:18.960
[Guest]: of norms in the way Palani could take liberties with Maniyar or in the care that Maniyar had

01:51:18.960 --> 01:51:26.000
[Guest]: for him, not just because he was a great maker, but also because there was something there.

01:51:26.000 --> 01:51:28.760
[Guest]: It's actually very, very beautiful.

01:51:28.760 --> 01:51:29.760
[Amit Varma]: It's very beautiful.

01:51:29.760 --> 01:51:34.360
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating film to be made on this if someone is sort of interested.

01:51:34.360 --> 01:51:41.040
[Amit Varma]: And you talk about how the relationship between the players and the makers is one of the term

01:51:41.040 --> 01:51:43.840
[Amit Varma]: you use as paternalistic feudalism.

01:51:43.840 --> 01:51:46.040
[Guest]: So kind of just elaborate on that a bit for me.

01:51:46.040 --> 01:51:48.100
[Guest]: But that's that's the reality of Indian society.

01:51:48.100 --> 01:51:50.440
[Guest]: This is not special of only of these two.

01:51:50.440 --> 01:51:51.440
[Unknown]: It's true.

01:51:51.440 --> 01:51:55.800
[Guest]: If the Indian society is a power equation, it's paternalistic feudalism.

01:51:55.800 --> 01:52:00.720
[Guest]: So there is it's important for us to understand this because we also engage in it every time.

01:52:00.720 --> 01:52:04.840
[Guest]: Every time we say that, you know, we are we look at our house, we take care of all the

01:52:04.840 --> 01:52:09.400
[Guest]: people who come into domestic work, we pay for their education, we make sure that their

01:52:09.400 --> 01:52:11.080
[Guest]: health care is taken care of.

01:52:11.080 --> 01:52:14.920
[Guest]: You know, I grew up in this lady's arms as a child.

01:52:14.920 --> 01:52:17.360
[Guest]: So she's like my mother.

01:52:17.360 --> 01:52:18.360
[Guest]: She's like my mother.

01:52:18.360 --> 01:52:23.360
[Guest]: So but just like if you just dig a little deeper, I mean, are these really equalizers?

01:52:23.360 --> 01:52:27.120
[Guest]: I mean, does it make that relationship really like a friend or even like a friend?

01:52:27.120 --> 01:52:28.120
[Guest]: It doesn't.

01:52:28.120 --> 01:52:29.120
[Guest]: Right.

01:52:29.120 --> 01:52:34.040
[Guest]: So there is feudalism allows for this possibility of care.

01:52:34.040 --> 01:52:35.280
[Guest]: OK.

01:52:35.280 --> 01:52:37.920
[Guest]: And but it never removes the feudalistic nature of it.

01:52:37.920 --> 01:52:39.920
[Guest]: You're still the giver.

01:52:39.920 --> 01:52:44.800
[Guest]: That individual is still the receiver that never goes away in a real friendship.

01:52:44.800 --> 01:52:47.160
[Guest]: This doesn't exist between you and me.

01:52:47.160 --> 01:52:49.960
[Guest]: If you wanted something, there's no conversation about it.

01:52:49.960 --> 01:52:50.960
[Guest]: You don't want to ask.

01:52:50.960 --> 01:52:51.960
[Guest]: Right.

01:52:51.960 --> 01:52:52.960
[Guest]: We just do it.

01:52:52.960 --> 01:52:53.960
[Guest]: This is not how feudalism works.

01:52:53.960 --> 01:52:57.680
[Guest]: So there is this paternalistic I need to take care of these people.

01:52:57.680 --> 01:52:58.680
[Guest]: You know, I know what's good.

01:52:58.680 --> 01:52:59.680
[Guest]: I know what's good.

01:52:59.680 --> 01:53:00.680
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:53:00.680 --> 01:53:01.680
[Guest]: I know what's good for them.

01:53:01.680 --> 01:53:02.680
[Guest]: I know that the children need education.

01:53:02.680 --> 01:53:03.680
[Guest]: They have to be educated.

01:53:03.680 --> 01:53:04.680
[Guest]: So we have to take care of it.

01:53:04.680 --> 01:53:09.280
[Guest]: So I mean, there is a certain positivity to it, right, in some sense.

01:53:09.280 --> 01:53:15.080
[Guest]: At the same time, it's very important that the power to make the decision is with you.

01:53:15.080 --> 01:53:17.000
[Guest]: You are deciding what is good.

01:53:17.000 --> 01:53:19.040
[Guest]: You are deciding that this is how it should be.

01:53:19.040 --> 01:53:24.640
[Guest]: And the other person is constantly, subconsciously, sometimes overtly reminded that you are the

01:53:24.640 --> 01:53:26.720
[Guest]: giver who's taking care of them.

01:53:26.720 --> 01:53:32.360
[Guest]: There is always a feeling that if not for this individual, where would my son go?

01:53:32.360 --> 01:53:33.840
[Guest]: Where would I be?

01:53:33.840 --> 01:53:36.440
[Guest]: So this is the structure of paternalistic feudalism.

01:53:36.440 --> 01:53:40.120
[Amit Varma]: And you give an example of this where, you know, different times in the book, you have

01:53:40.120 --> 01:53:43.600
[Amit Varma]: a maker growing old and saying, I can't work anymore.

01:53:43.600 --> 01:53:45.760
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, what will happen to me?

01:53:45.760 --> 01:53:49.960
[Amit Varma]: And the advice given by the player is that let your sons come into the profession when

01:53:49.960 --> 01:53:54.920
[Amit Varma]: the player's sons themselves have gone abroad and they're doctors and they're computer engineers.

01:53:54.920 --> 01:53:59.800
[Amit Varma]: But to him, it's logical that the maker's son must be exactly and then there's no questioning

01:53:59.800 --> 01:54:00.800
[Guest]: of that at all.

01:54:00.800 --> 01:54:01.800
[Guest]: Right.

01:54:01.800 --> 01:54:05.000
[Guest]: You know, I took care of you, I'll take care of your son.

01:54:05.000 --> 01:54:07.960
[Guest]: Just make sure that your son is also making Mridangams for me.

01:54:07.960 --> 01:54:09.200
[Guest]: That continues the whole thing.

01:54:09.200 --> 01:54:10.680
[Amit Varma]: It continues to this day.

01:54:10.680 --> 01:54:11.680
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:54:11.680 --> 01:54:12.680
[Guest]: That idea still continues.

01:54:12.680 --> 01:54:15.440
[Guest]: But I think the younger generation are very different.

01:54:15.440 --> 01:54:17.200
[Guest]: Younger generation makers are also tougher.

01:54:17.200 --> 01:54:22.880
[Guest]: And I think there is great affirmation and there is also aspiration.

01:54:22.880 --> 01:54:28.640
[Guest]: So not many of them are going to really want to send their children in this profession.

01:54:28.640 --> 01:54:29.640
[Guest]: I don't think so.

01:54:29.640 --> 01:54:32.600
[Guest]: I know the older generation would hope that what I'm saying is wrong, because there is

01:54:32.600 --> 01:54:35.760
[Guest]: that whole, whatever is said and done, this is our family.

01:54:35.760 --> 01:54:36.760
[Guest]: That is also there.

01:54:36.760 --> 01:54:37.760
[Guest]: That feeling is also there.

01:54:37.760 --> 01:54:39.400
[Guest]: But I think the younger generation are not probably going to do that.

01:54:39.400 --> 01:54:43.560
[Guest]: In fact, I've had one Mridangam player feel very bad that it's not going to happen.

01:54:43.560 --> 01:54:47.240
[Guest]: They said, you know, if these people are all going to these IT companies, there's one quote,

01:54:47.240 --> 01:54:53.840
[Guest]: one maker, one player told me that they would rather be a peon or a guard in an AC room

01:54:53.840 --> 01:54:57.240
[Guest]: than do this work, though this work pays well.

01:54:57.240 --> 01:54:58.240
[Amit Varma]: That's very interesting.

01:54:58.240 --> 01:54:59.240
[Guest]: Where do you think that comes from?

01:54:59.240 --> 01:55:01.080
[Amit Varma]: That's very, that is not just here.

01:55:01.080 --> 01:55:02.880
[Amit Varma]: Is it striking out at the feudalism?

01:55:02.880 --> 01:55:03.880
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:55:03.880 --> 01:55:04.880
[Guest]: No, this is said by the player.

01:55:04.880 --> 01:55:05.880
[Guest]: Okay.

01:55:05.880 --> 01:55:06.880
[Guest]: Right.

01:55:06.880 --> 01:55:07.880
[Guest]: The player is upset.

01:55:07.880 --> 01:55:13.240
[Guest]: The player is upset that the person would rather be, you know, a chowkidar, who's inside

01:55:13.240 --> 01:55:20.000
[Guest]: this AC room or this peon than be a Mridangam maker, though Mridangam making has money.

01:55:20.000 --> 01:55:24.520
[Guest]: Forgetting that there's so many other things involved in why they don't want to do this.

01:55:24.520 --> 01:55:27.000
[Guest]: This is classic and this you find everywhere else.

01:55:27.000 --> 01:55:30.800
[Guest]: People who say that, no, I don't find any agricultural labourers anymore.

01:55:30.800 --> 01:55:33.880
[Guest]: They would rather go and work in an office.

01:55:33.880 --> 01:55:35.920
[Guest]: You've heard many people say these things, right?

01:55:35.920 --> 01:55:37.400
[Guest]: So it's the same mindset.

01:55:37.400 --> 01:55:38.400
[Guest]: Again, it's feudalism.

01:55:38.400 --> 01:55:41.280
[Guest]: It is, you know, it's the same kind of feudalism that is at play.

01:55:41.280 --> 01:55:46.040
[Guest]: So they would rather have these people in control, take care of them, but make sure

01:55:46.040 --> 01:55:52.800
[Guest]: they are there and any kind of mobility, which is seen by the individual as being far better.

01:55:52.800 --> 01:55:55.040
[Guest]: Because it is not just about being the peon.

01:55:55.040 --> 01:55:56.040
[Guest]: It's about respect.

01:55:56.040 --> 01:56:01.160
[Guest]: You know, many people like to wear that uniform when they become a, you know, like the security

01:56:01.160 --> 01:56:06.560
[Guest]: in a corporate office, there is dignity that is felt by the individual when they wear the

01:56:06.560 --> 01:56:09.200
[Guest]: uniform and stand there.

01:56:09.200 --> 01:56:14.480
[Guest]: You and I may not understand it, but then I'm happier if they are going to the abattoir,

01:56:14.480 --> 01:56:18.640
[Guest]: making sure they get the skin, making sure they're standing under the sun for hours,

01:56:18.640 --> 01:56:22.000
[Guest]: because I believe they make 2000 rupees more because of that.

01:56:22.000 --> 01:56:25.280
[Guest]: You know, this is a very, very classic behaviour.

01:56:25.280 --> 01:56:32.440
[Amit Varma]: And is it more possible today in your book you write about how at one time it was very

01:56:32.440 --> 01:56:35.800
[Amit Varma]: difficult for a maker to be a player.

01:56:35.800 --> 01:56:39.680
[Amit Varma]: No point even aspiring to that, you immediately knew that, oh, this is not going to happen

01:56:39.680 --> 01:56:41.680
[Amit Varma]: and you reconcile with what you have.

01:56:41.680 --> 01:56:45.680
[Amit Varma]: Is it more possible today with a more upwardly mobile aspirational generation?

01:56:45.680 --> 01:56:48.560
[Guest]: I like to believe it is, but it's not so easy.

01:56:48.560 --> 01:56:49.720
[Guest]: I mean, I know it's not.

01:56:49.720 --> 01:56:50.720
[Amit Varma]: You still have the...

01:56:50.720 --> 01:56:51.720
[Amit Varma]: It is very difficult.

01:56:51.720 --> 01:56:54.640
[Guest]: I mean, it's not just about the maker, the caste entrenchment is there.

01:56:54.640 --> 01:56:59.960
[Guest]: So it's not just because, not just as far as Mridangam makers, children are concerned,

01:56:59.960 --> 01:57:03.160
[Guest]: I think it's true of people coming from multiple communities.

01:57:03.160 --> 01:57:07.080
[Guest]: Very difficult to break through this, through the fiefdom, it's very hard.

01:57:07.080 --> 01:57:10.080
[Guest]: But I'd like to believe that it will gradually change.

01:57:10.080 --> 01:57:14.440
[Guest]: Already I know there are two, three people learning, whether they will become professional

01:57:14.440 --> 01:57:17.360
[Guest]: players themselves, I don't know.

01:57:17.360 --> 01:57:21.880
[Guest]: But maybe that itself is a transition, you know, that slowly in the next generation,

01:57:21.880 --> 01:57:25.640
[Guest]: the next pedal will be pushed and then you have them as players.

01:57:25.640 --> 01:57:27.840
[Guest]: But it's not easy.

01:57:27.840 --> 01:57:28.840
[Guest]: It's not easy.

01:57:28.840 --> 01:57:34.000
[Guest]: It is hard because still these structures are at play, you know, still these attitudes

01:57:34.000 --> 01:57:36.440
[Guest]: are subconsciously there.

01:57:36.440 --> 01:57:41.360
[Guest]: So does the teacher teach with the same intensity to the son of a Mridangam maker compared to

01:57:41.360 --> 01:57:44.520
[Guest]: say my son?

01:57:44.520 --> 01:57:45.520
[Guest]: That's a big question.

01:57:45.520 --> 01:57:51.240
[Guest]: Even though the teacher is not consciously recognizing it, you know, probably not.

01:57:51.240 --> 01:57:56.520
[Guest]: They presume that, you know, how much is this guy going to get, you know, enough for him,

01:57:56.520 --> 01:57:57.520
[Guest]: this is enough for him.

01:57:57.520 --> 01:58:03.520
[Guest]: Whereas TM Krishna's son, oh, this guy's, you know, a lot of talent will also get those

01:58:03.520 --> 01:58:04.520
[Guest]: early opportunities.

01:58:04.520 --> 01:58:10.480
[Guest]: And a lot of these things that you think of and who would have rather put on stage first,

01:58:10.480 --> 01:58:14.640
[Guest]: you know, all these things are, are definitely operational.

01:58:14.640 --> 01:58:17.800
[Guest]: So I don't know, it's going to be hard.

01:58:17.800 --> 01:58:22.320
[Amit Varma]: That's very interesting, and I'm just thinking that game theoretically, even if every single

01:58:22.320 --> 01:58:27.840
[Amit Varma]: person, every single person who's deciding a concert has a choice between, say, a lower

01:58:27.840 --> 01:58:32.720
[Amit Varma]: caste new player and an upper caste new player, even if their individual instincts say take

01:58:32.720 --> 01:58:36.600
[Amit Varma]: the lower caste guy, they will still not do it because they worry of what the others may

01:58:36.600 --> 01:58:38.600
[Guest]: say and they might take the safer route.

01:58:38.600 --> 01:58:40.640
[Guest]: And also, it's a very simple thing.

01:58:40.640 --> 01:58:44.840
[Guest]: I give an example of names, you know, names give away identities.

01:58:44.840 --> 01:58:51.320
[Guest]: So a lot of people who come from other non-brahminical communities have names that are very Tamil,

01:58:51.320 --> 01:58:59.720
[Guest]: Arul Selvan, okay, whereas brahminical communities will be Mukund, Srinivas, TM Krishna.

01:58:59.720 --> 01:59:06.880
[Guest]: So if I was given two names, I was given the name Mukund, Mukund somebody, and I was given

01:59:06.880 --> 01:59:15.920
[Guest]: the name, you know, like I said, Arul, instinctively I look for Mukund.

01:59:15.920 --> 01:59:19.160
[Guest]: It's just something I do like reflex, right?

01:59:19.160 --> 01:59:27.040
[Guest]: And somehow I feel in the concert list, TM Krishna vocal, somebody else violin, Arul

01:59:27.040 --> 01:59:35.120
[Guest]: Mridangam doesn't sound as cool as Mukund Mridangam, it sounds natural.

01:59:35.120 --> 01:59:37.920
[Guest]: You know, so you are thinking of these things.

01:59:37.920 --> 01:59:42.080
[Guest]: I mean, you're thinking of so many things, you're thinking of the way the person looks,

01:59:42.080 --> 01:59:46.280
[Guest]: you're thinking whether the person will be able to speak in, if you're traveling abroad.

01:59:46.280 --> 01:59:50.280
[Guest]: I mean, we all do this, we're traveling abroad, my colleagues, I'm thinking, can that colleague

01:59:50.280 --> 01:59:51.280
[Guest]: speak English?

01:59:51.280 --> 01:59:55.360
[Guest]: When we go to a dinner, we are thinking all these things.

01:59:55.360 --> 01:59:58.320
[Guest]: It's not just about the stage, we're thinking of so many other things.

01:59:58.320 --> 02:00:01.980
[Guest]: Culturally, will I be able to have conversations?

02:00:01.980 --> 02:00:04.360
[Guest]: You know, will there be disconnect?

02:00:04.360 --> 02:00:07.080
[Guest]: All this plays a role in these choices.

02:00:07.080 --> 02:00:08.440
[Amit Varma]: Can we hang together?

02:00:08.440 --> 02:00:09.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:00:09.440 --> 02:00:12.240
[Guest]: Can we hang together is a very important part, community building.

02:00:12.240 --> 02:00:16.440
[Guest]: So you want a similar kind of person with whom you can have a conversation.

02:00:16.440 --> 02:00:17.440
[Guest]: Is it cool enough?

02:00:17.440 --> 02:00:19.800
[Guest]: You said that's such an important idea.

02:00:19.800 --> 02:00:26.120
[Guest]: So in all this, the person who's an, within quote, an outsider is in a hugely disadvantaged

02:00:26.120 --> 02:00:27.120
[Guest]: position.

02:00:27.120 --> 02:00:31.040
[Guest]: I mean, even women, for example, I've heard so many men say, you know, I don't want to

02:00:31.040 --> 02:00:35.200
[Guest]: take a woman violinist because, you know, it's the kind of, you know, we'll all be hanging

02:00:35.200 --> 02:00:36.200
[Guest]: out.

02:00:36.200 --> 02:00:39.080
[Guest]: So, you know, conversations cannot be free.

02:00:39.080 --> 02:00:40.080
[Guest]: We're not even talking about talent.

02:00:40.080 --> 02:00:43.440
[Amit Varma]: So basically, they want the freedom to make sexist jokes and stuff like that.

02:00:43.440 --> 02:00:44.440
[Guest]: Exactly, exactly.

02:00:44.440 --> 02:00:49.320
[Guest]: So you don't feel it's there, you know, it's easy enough, you know.

02:00:49.320 --> 02:00:52.000
[Guest]: This is being said even for women, okay.

02:00:52.000 --> 02:00:56.320
[Guest]: Or they will say, you know, we can just share rooms, but you know, with women, then it becomes

02:00:56.320 --> 02:00:57.840
[Guest]: a little complicated.

02:00:57.840 --> 02:01:01.020
[Guest]: All these ridiculous things I said, as far as gender is concerned.

02:01:01.020 --> 02:01:05.840
[Guest]: So the same thing in different ways works here too, right?

02:01:05.840 --> 02:01:07.360
[Amit Varma]: So this is how people are thinking.

02:01:07.360 --> 02:01:12.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, you are thinking about how you are thinking, even if these instinctive thoughts come, you

02:01:12.040 --> 02:01:14.880
[Amit Varma]: are correcting for them.

02:01:14.880 --> 02:01:16.840
[Amit Varma]: So you know, how do you then do it?

02:01:16.840 --> 02:01:21.240
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you've then added this extra layer of consciousness to your decisions, right?

02:01:21.240 --> 02:01:23.080
[Guest]: How does that work?

02:01:23.080 --> 02:01:29.600
[Guest]: So some people think is I just have just complicated my own life, because they'll accuse you of

02:01:29.600 --> 02:01:36.280
[Guest]: posturing or tokenism or not doing enough, or not doing enough.

02:01:36.280 --> 02:01:41.040
[Guest]: People have asked me, you know, name people from other castes that you have on stage with

02:01:41.040 --> 02:01:42.040
[Guest]: you.

02:01:42.040 --> 02:01:45.880
[Guest]: I'm not going to be naming people, it's their choice, you know, I'm not going to do that.

02:01:45.880 --> 02:01:50.920
[Guest]: So I think that what I try to do is constantly be like you said, have that layer, make sure

02:01:50.920 --> 02:01:52.920
[Guest]: that layer doesn't go away.

02:01:52.920 --> 02:02:00.400
[Guest]: And I don't find it to be any way limiting my free flow of being, you know, because people

02:02:00.400 --> 02:02:03.040
[Guest]: may think it just stops you from doing very easy thing.

02:02:03.040 --> 02:02:04.960
[Guest]: No, actually, it helps me a lot.

02:02:04.960 --> 02:02:10.920
[Guest]: It makes me see people I've never seen before, makes me spot talent that I would not notice,

02:02:10.920 --> 02:02:11.920
[Guest]: right?

02:02:11.920 --> 02:02:15.240
[Guest]: Because I realized why I'm not spotted that talent, you know, or when I go somewhere and

02:02:15.240 --> 02:02:20.440
[Guest]: listen to say this person is talented, you know, and so it allows me in fact, to take

02:02:20.440 --> 02:02:27.600
[Guest]: a lot of the rubbish in front of my eyes and see things in a way that I would not see before.

02:02:27.600 --> 02:02:37.200
[Guest]: If anything, it's helped me find many interesting artists, share non-stage time with people

02:02:37.200 --> 02:02:44.160
[Guest]: who are very different and find ways in which you can connect and not limited by wanting

02:02:44.160 --> 02:02:45.580
[Guest]: the similar kind of person.

02:02:45.580 --> 02:02:48.400
[Guest]: So it has been extremely liberating.

02:02:48.400 --> 02:02:52.120
[Amit Varma]: So I'll share with you, so this study comes to mind, which I read about in a book, I keep

02:02:52.120 --> 02:02:55.980
[Amit Varma]: talking about brilliant book called super forecasting by Philip Tetlock, where he talks

02:02:55.980 --> 02:03:01.280
[Amit Varma]: about this study, which showed that the most important factor in good decision making is

02:03:01.280 --> 02:03:05.720
[Amit Varma]: not the things you would expect, like intelligence or education or whatever is diversity.

02:03:05.720 --> 02:03:10.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, that's and obviously, this is not about decision making, but do you feel

02:03:10.040 --> 02:03:15.760
[Amit Varma]: that diversity, just ensuring diversity without necessarily compromising on whatever, but

02:03:15.760 --> 02:03:21.520
[Amit Varma]: just ensuring diversity, sort of enhances the level of your thinking or the level of

02:03:21.520 --> 02:03:22.520
[Guest]: your performance?

02:03:22.520 --> 02:03:23.520
[Guest]: Definitely.

02:03:23.520 --> 02:03:24.520
[Guest]: See, diversity is very important.

02:03:24.520 --> 02:03:29.880
[Guest]: I think diversity also enhances the art form itself.

02:03:29.880 --> 02:03:34.280
[Guest]: Any work, I mean, if I mean, take the work of journalism or take anything, you need diverse

02:03:34.280 --> 02:03:36.680
[Guest]: people, diverse voices saying different things.

02:03:36.680 --> 02:03:37.680
[Amit Varma]: Diverse points of view.

02:03:37.680 --> 02:03:38.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you need.

02:03:38.680 --> 02:03:44.120
[Guest]: So even in music, you have different tonalities, different notions.

02:03:44.120 --> 02:03:50.320
[Guest]: You need, for example, the Nadaswaram, which is now not considered, not presented as mainstream

02:03:50.320 --> 02:03:51.320
[Guest]: Carnatic music.

02:03:51.320 --> 02:03:55.160
[Guest]: You need that voice to be amplified because you need that different sound to come in,

02:03:55.160 --> 02:03:59.120
[Guest]: different notion of of Carnatic music or different notion of Khyal.

02:03:59.120 --> 02:04:05.160
[Guest]: So the diversity is lacking entirely across Indian art forms to a large extent.

02:04:05.160 --> 02:04:10.480
[Guest]: So the diversity brings different ways of even hearing the same Sa.

02:04:10.480 --> 02:04:13.000
[Guest]: It could be simple.

02:04:13.000 --> 02:04:19.160
[Guest]: So it is diversity linguistically, diversity geographically, diversity in caste, in gender,

02:04:19.160 --> 02:04:20.160
[Guest]: in all this.

02:04:20.160 --> 02:04:26.320
[Guest]: I mean, we need people from the trans community singing these art forms, you know, playing

02:04:26.320 --> 02:04:27.360
[Guest]: these art forms.

02:04:27.360 --> 02:04:33.160
[Guest]: We need more women playing Murudangam because we need less machismo in all these things.

02:04:33.160 --> 02:04:37.320
[Guest]: It's all full of, you know, showing off, showing off.

02:04:37.320 --> 02:04:40.160
[Guest]: We need we need a different idea.

02:04:40.160 --> 02:04:47.040
[Guest]: So diversity is essential for any community building, which is truly open.

02:04:47.040 --> 02:04:53.800
[Guest]: It also is essential for art, for any job, any any area of work to really be alive and

02:04:53.800 --> 02:04:55.720
[Guest]: vibrant with ideas.

02:04:55.720 --> 02:04:57.200
[Guest]: You want vibrancy of ideas.

02:04:57.200 --> 02:04:58.200
[Guest]: You need diversity.

02:04:58.200 --> 02:05:00.400
[Guest]: Otherwise, it's not going to happen.

02:05:00.400 --> 02:05:02.120
[Guest]: You will be happy with what you're experiencing.

02:05:02.120 --> 02:05:03.200
[Guest]: That's a different thing.

02:05:03.200 --> 02:05:07.200
[Guest]: But you're not going to have contestation, you're going to have conflicting thoughts,

02:05:07.200 --> 02:05:11.000
[Guest]: you're not going to have interesting bouts, you're not going to have different perceptions,

02:05:11.000 --> 02:05:13.000
[Guest]: and you're not going to have any movement which is forward.

02:05:13.000 --> 02:05:14.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:05:14.000 --> 02:05:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And comfort zones are inherently very restricting.

02:05:16.000 --> 02:05:18.280
[Amit Varma]: I mean, they are like straitjackets.

02:05:18.280 --> 02:05:22.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, I want to move to a bunch of general questions, leaving the book aside.

02:05:22.480 --> 02:05:26.680
[Amit Varma]: But first, I have to ask you about your visit to the abattoir which I found absolutely fascinating

02:05:26.680 --> 02:05:33.720
[Amit Varma]: because you like, first of all, what really interested me is the intricate science and

02:05:33.720 --> 02:05:38.600
[Amit Varma]: almost the knowledge of which can only come from lived experience of actually constructing

02:05:38.600 --> 02:05:41.040
[Amit Varma]: the Mridangam and the different skins involved.

02:05:41.040 --> 02:05:45.600
[Amit Varma]: Like you point out that, you know, there are three layers, it's cow, goat, cow, or buffalo,

02:05:45.600 --> 02:05:47.440
[Amit Varma]: goat, buffalo, as it were.

02:05:47.440 --> 02:05:54.680
[Amit Varma]: And the cow layer is always a female who's had two kids, because then the skin is stretchable

02:05:54.680 --> 02:05:57.360
[Amit Varma]: enough to just the right degree.

02:05:57.360 --> 02:06:01.920
[Amit Varma]: And, and your, you know, description of how you went to the abattoir and the makers who

02:06:01.920 --> 02:06:06.160
[Amit Varma]: were with you, what they looked for, how they chose what they chose was absolutely fascinating.

02:06:06.160 --> 02:06:10.200
[Amit Varma]: But tell me about you, you know, you expected to go there and be disgusted and repelled

02:06:10.200 --> 02:06:11.200
[Amit Varma]: and you weren't.

02:06:11.200 --> 02:06:12.200
[Amit Varma]: I thought I'll puke.

02:06:12.200 --> 02:06:13.200
[Guest]: And you didn't?

02:06:13.200 --> 02:06:14.200
[Guest]: I didn't puke.

02:06:14.200 --> 02:06:15.200
[Guest]: I really thought I would.

02:06:15.200 --> 02:06:18.880
[Guest]: I was warned by all the, by the maker who took me, Suse Nath and said, are you sure

02:06:18.880 --> 02:06:19.880
[Guest]: you want to come?

02:06:19.880 --> 02:06:22.400
[Guest]: I don't think you'll survive.

02:06:22.400 --> 02:06:28.400
[Guest]: And I expected myself to really find the place just difficult to handle.

02:06:28.400 --> 02:06:34.240
[Guest]: I still, I'm not able to explain why I did not go through that experience.

02:06:34.240 --> 02:06:38.280
[Guest]: You know, I'm able to kind of understand it and I try and place it in the book.

02:06:38.280 --> 02:06:39.360
[Guest]: But how did that happen?

02:06:39.360 --> 02:06:48.280
[Guest]: I think what was most intriguing was how there are so many reals in the world, right?

02:06:48.280 --> 02:06:51.560
[Guest]: And we don't see so many of the realities in the reals.

02:06:51.560 --> 02:06:57.280
[Guest]: And I entered a new real for me as an outsider, that this isn't everyday happening.

02:06:57.280 --> 02:06:58.280
[Guest]: Okay.

02:06:58.280 --> 02:07:02.120
[Guest]: You know, every day in the morning, you have this happening in the upper floor.

02:07:02.120 --> 02:07:03.120
[Guest]: This is their old normal.

02:07:03.120 --> 02:07:04.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:07:04.120 --> 02:07:05.120
[Amit Varma]: The blood and the gore and the skin.

02:07:05.120 --> 02:07:06.600
[Guest]: This is the normal.

02:07:06.600 --> 02:07:07.600
[Guest]: And this is part of it.

02:07:07.600 --> 02:07:12.560
[Guest]: You know, the meat is taken, like I, the Mridangam maker always told me that there's nothing

02:07:12.560 --> 02:07:14.080
[Guest]: that goes waste here.

02:07:14.080 --> 02:07:16.380
[Guest]: I told him that many times.

02:07:16.380 --> 02:07:21.760
[Guest]: It's like from the skin to the meat, everything has, the bones, everything has some utility

02:07:21.760 --> 02:07:22.760
[Guest]: somewhere.

02:07:22.760 --> 02:07:23.760
[Guest]: So we don't waste anything.

02:07:23.760 --> 02:07:27.480
[Guest]: I remember that, that stays with me, that whole point that nothing is thrown away.

02:07:27.480 --> 02:07:31.000
[Guest]: You know, nothing is discarded as, you know, this is of no use.

02:07:31.000 --> 02:07:36.920
[Guest]: And you go there, you sit there, you see them work, you see the conversation and you're

02:07:36.920 --> 02:07:39.780
[Guest]: like, this is very normal.

02:07:39.780 --> 02:07:40.780
[Guest]: This happens every day.

02:07:40.780 --> 02:07:46.000
[Guest]: They're having a cup of tea, there is gooey stuff all over the place, there's blood everywhere.

02:07:46.000 --> 02:07:47.160
[Guest]: But what does that mean?

02:07:47.160 --> 02:07:49.760
[Guest]: I mean, what does that say of that?

02:07:49.760 --> 02:07:52.800
[Guest]: I mean, can I pass judgment on that job?

02:07:52.800 --> 02:07:55.680
[Guest]: Can I pass, you know, that is why it confused a lot of things.

02:07:55.680 --> 02:07:59.240
[Guest]: You know, I know that, you know, animal activists may find this problematic and, you know, maybe

02:07:59.240 --> 02:08:01.480
[Guest]: they may think that I'm being insensitive.

02:08:01.480 --> 02:08:06.080
[Guest]: I don't know, but this is how I experienced it, that there was something that I, this

02:08:06.080 --> 02:08:08.400
[Guest]: was something I couldn't judge.

02:08:08.400 --> 02:08:12.760
[Guest]: There's something I couldn't be judgmental in, like you asked me about the old and the

02:08:12.760 --> 02:08:16.240
[Guest]: new, the previous question you asked me about, are we judging money here, for example, from

02:08:16.240 --> 02:08:17.360
[Guest]: this, these standards.

02:08:17.360 --> 02:08:24.020
[Guest]: So am I judging the people there who do this every day from my standards of animal rights,

02:08:24.020 --> 02:08:26.240
[Guest]: my notions of killing?

02:08:26.240 --> 02:08:27.920
[Guest]: I don't know.

02:08:27.920 --> 02:08:28.960
[Guest]: I don't know.

02:08:28.960 --> 02:08:32.840
[Guest]: But the fact is that there was something very real about it.

02:08:32.840 --> 02:08:37.560
[Guest]: There was something, I'm going to use this word with great care when I'm going to use

02:08:37.560 --> 02:08:42.440
[Guest]: it, there's something nonviolent about it.

02:08:42.440 --> 02:08:47.160
[Guest]: I know this seems like a misplaced word when cows are being killed.

02:08:47.160 --> 02:08:56.000
[Guest]: But I'm saying that because it was not an act of anger, there was no, there was no aggression.

02:08:56.000 --> 02:08:57.000
[Amit Varma]: It's weird.

02:08:57.000 --> 02:09:01.800
[Guest]: There's something very, very weird about it.

02:09:01.800 --> 02:09:04.600
[Guest]: There's something, the way I experienced it is weird.

02:09:04.600 --> 02:09:08.240
[Guest]: And they go, and I won't tell you that even now people say that, you know, that any skin

02:09:08.240 --> 02:09:09.240
[Guest]: is taken.

02:09:09.240 --> 02:09:10.240
[Guest]: No.

02:09:10.240 --> 02:09:14.280
[Guest]: When a Mridangam maker wants a certain kind of skin, the maker informs a person inside

02:09:14.280 --> 02:09:17.620
[Guest]: the abattoir who chooses a cow correctly for it.

02:09:17.620 --> 02:09:20.040
[Guest]: It has to be skinned in a certain manner.

02:09:20.040 --> 02:09:21.040
[Amit Varma]: So the cuts are not on the skin.

02:09:21.040 --> 02:09:22.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, there are no cuts on the skin.

02:09:22.520 --> 02:09:24.080
[Amit Varma]: And you attempted this apparently.

02:09:24.080 --> 02:09:28.800
[Guest]: I tried peeling out the flesh and it's, oh God, it's very hard to do.

02:09:28.800 --> 02:09:36.440
[Guest]: And so there is great science, specificity, observation skills, and the way it's nailed,

02:09:36.440 --> 02:09:37.440
[Guest]: it's stretched.

02:09:37.440 --> 02:09:39.680
[Guest]: It's, it's something else.

02:09:39.680 --> 02:09:42.280
[Guest]: And it's not easy and it's a very hard job.

02:09:42.280 --> 02:09:47.720
[Amit Varma]: No, and I've always sort of complained about the hypocrisy of people who are vegetarians,

02:09:47.720 --> 02:09:50.600
[Amit Varma]: but they wear leather belts or they'll carry purses and all that.

02:09:50.600 --> 02:09:55.760
[Amit Varma]: And in this case, any vegetarian Brahmin who is enjoying Carnatic music is enjoying the

02:09:55.760 --> 02:10:00.880
[Amit Varma]: sound of a Mridangam, which is put together with all this animal skin and all of this

02:10:00.880 --> 02:10:03.840
[Amit Varma]: death and blood and gore and all of that.

02:10:03.840 --> 02:10:07.040
[Amit Varma]: And the question is not to pass judgment on it and say that, okay, don't listen to the

02:10:07.040 --> 02:10:08.040
[Amit Varma]: music.

02:10:08.040 --> 02:10:10.140
[Amit Varma]: The question is just to, you know, at least don't be in denial.

02:10:10.140 --> 02:10:11.140
[Guest]: This is what it is.

02:10:11.140 --> 02:10:15.360
[Guest]: That's why I see, I have a problem with Rajagopalachari, exactly what you said, right?

02:10:15.360 --> 02:10:20.560
[Guest]: This denial that, you know, you don't want to talk about this, this doesn't exist, but

02:10:20.560 --> 02:10:26.640
[Guest]: you will say, oh, what Nada in that Mridangam artistry, oh, I enjoyed it.

02:10:26.640 --> 02:10:33.160
[Guest]: But you realize that if that Nada came because cow skin was vibrating and it's in that resonance

02:10:33.160 --> 02:10:36.920
[Guest]: that you're experiencing ecstasy, you're experiencing divinity.

02:10:36.920 --> 02:10:44.280
[Guest]: Let's, let's juxtapose those words, notion of experiencing divinity from the skin of

02:10:44.280 --> 02:10:45.280
[Guest]: a cow.

02:10:45.280 --> 02:10:49.760
[Guest]: I mean, you have to accept that this is real.

02:10:49.760 --> 02:10:54.080
[Guest]: You have to, there has to be some acknowledgement and also means it's not just acknowledgement

02:10:54.080 --> 02:11:00.040
[Guest]: of that, acknowledgement of the people who make sure that that's possible for you, acknowledgement

02:11:00.040 --> 02:11:01.040
[Amit Varma]: of the makers.

02:11:01.040 --> 02:11:03.800
[Guest]: Because someone else is going out there and skinning that cow, it's not you.

02:11:03.800 --> 02:11:08.800
[Guest]: You know, I don't want to sound like I was, you know, just as you were speaking, I'm insensitive

02:11:08.800 --> 02:11:13.080
[Guest]: to, you know, animals or insensitive to animal rights, no.

02:11:13.080 --> 02:11:19.400
[Guest]: But I just want to say it's far more complicated in experience than we think it is.

02:11:19.400 --> 02:11:20.400
[Guest]: You know, I don't know.

02:11:20.400 --> 02:11:22.160
[Guest]: I mean, it's very, very complicated.

02:11:22.160 --> 02:11:27.200
[Guest]: You know, like I was saying, a villager rears a goat, loves the goat.

02:11:27.200 --> 02:11:28.960
[Guest]: Any agriculturalist will tell you this.

02:11:28.960 --> 02:11:35.520
[Guest]: They'll rear the goats, they love the goat, take it every day out to graze, bring it back.

02:11:35.520 --> 02:11:40.040
[Guest]: They can drink the milk and then they send it out to be killed.

02:11:40.040 --> 02:11:42.520
[Guest]: Now, was there love for the goat?

02:11:42.520 --> 02:11:43.720
[Guest]: Of course.

02:11:43.720 --> 02:11:45.600
[Guest]: Was there a relationship with the goat?

02:11:45.600 --> 02:11:46.600
[Guest]: Yes.

02:11:46.600 --> 02:11:51.240
[Guest]: So are they heartless human beings because they sent it to the abattoir?

02:11:51.240 --> 02:11:52.240
[Guest]: No.

02:11:52.240 --> 02:11:54.080
[Guest]: So how does this work?

02:11:54.080 --> 02:11:58.720
[Guest]: I think we need this nuance when we are dealing with these things, you know.

02:11:58.720 --> 02:12:05.760
[Guest]: Otherwise, there is this, again, evil, good, correct, wrong, you know, judgments that we

02:12:05.760 --> 02:12:06.760
[Guest]: throw.

02:12:06.760 --> 02:12:09.680
[Guest]: So I think we need to be far more careful with these things.

02:12:09.680 --> 02:12:12.480
[Guest]: And that's what that experience taught me.

02:12:12.480 --> 02:12:19.680
[Guest]: You know, that experience taught me that even in an act of killing, there is nuance in some

02:12:19.680 --> 02:12:21.360
[Guest]: weird way, you know.

02:12:21.360 --> 02:12:22.840
[Guest]: I'm not encouraging violence.

02:12:22.840 --> 02:12:25.640
[Guest]: I'm not saying that we should be killing each other.

02:12:25.640 --> 02:12:27.280
[Guest]: But I'm trying to say that there is this complexity.

02:12:27.280 --> 02:12:30.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there's an acceptance that this is the way things are.

02:12:30.120 --> 02:12:34.320
[Amit Varma]: Even if you're not skinning cows, we are killing tiny beings all the time.

02:12:34.320 --> 02:12:40.160
[Guest]: Like you said, we are consuming things, we are consuming belts and shoes and, you know.

02:12:40.160 --> 02:12:43.840
[Guest]: And we ourselves are colonized by bacteria, so lest you think you are better than a cow.

02:12:43.840 --> 02:12:51.680
[Guest]: And sanyasis sat on deer skin or tiger skin and spoke about nonviolence and about love

02:12:51.680 --> 02:12:52.680
[Guest]: and affection.

02:12:52.680 --> 02:12:54.520
[Amit Varma]: Now, that's very interesting, isn't it?

02:12:54.520 --> 02:12:56.200
[Amit Varma]: I'm reminded of Talib's turkey.

02:12:56.200 --> 02:13:00.920
[Amit Varma]: So Nassim Nicholas Talib tells a story of a turkey where a turkey wakes up one day and

02:13:00.920 --> 02:13:01.920
[Amit Varma]: it has a really good day.

02:13:01.920 --> 02:13:05.360
[Amit Varma]: It's taken out, it's given a lot of grain, it has its time in the sun.

02:13:05.360 --> 02:13:07.600
[Amit Varma]: And then it assumes, okay, tomorrow will be like this.

02:13:07.600 --> 02:13:09.560
[Amit Varma]: And lo and behold, tomorrow is like that.

02:13:09.560 --> 02:13:13.280
[Amit Varma]: And it's like that for 364 days in a row and is completely chilling.

02:13:13.280 --> 02:13:14.880
[Amit Varma]: And the 365th day is Christmas.

02:13:14.880 --> 02:13:17.680
[Guest]: So, yeah, so I don't know.

02:13:17.680 --> 02:13:18.680
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

02:13:18.680 --> 02:13:24.120
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, I think your book is something that listeners of the show are definitely

02:13:24.120 --> 02:13:27.480
[Amit Varma]: should pick up and I'll kind of recommend that I want to move on to some bigger questions

02:13:27.480 --> 02:13:30.960
[Amit Varma]: because I've taken more than two hours of your time in.

02:13:30.960 --> 02:13:33.360
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of move on now.

02:13:33.360 --> 02:13:37.720
[Amit Varma]: One thing that you've, you know, written about in some of your essays is I see disparaging

02:13:37.720 --> 02:13:40.280
[Amit Varma]: mentions of the market and I get where that's coming from.

02:13:40.280 --> 02:13:47.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, the way I see it is that I really object to people who classify state, society and

02:13:47.560 --> 02:13:49.040
[Amit Varma]: market as three separate things.

02:13:49.040 --> 02:13:50.880
[Amit Varma]: I think there are two separate things.

02:13:50.880 --> 02:13:55.080
[Amit Varma]: And the market and society, I mean, the markets are the mechanism by which society fulfills

02:13:55.080 --> 02:13:56.640
[Amit Varma]: its own needs.

02:13:56.640 --> 02:14:02.080
[Amit Varma]: And where markets seem misogynist and patriarchal and rambunistic is whatever if, is if those

02:14:02.080 --> 02:14:06.400
[Amit Varma]: are the people who can really afford to buy things and who are sort of controlling it.

02:14:06.400 --> 02:14:10.080
[Amit Varma]: But I think what we've seen in recent times, and I was chatting with you over lunch about

02:14:10.080 --> 02:14:16.440
[Amit Varma]: this is, for example, there is TikTok and you could say there is even YouTube and various

02:14:16.440 --> 02:14:21.560
[Amit Varma]: other means by which and ironically, Gio has played a part in this by making bandwidth

02:14:21.560 --> 02:14:29.480
[Amit Varma]: so cheap that by which you suddenly have different classes of people possessing both the means

02:14:29.480 --> 02:14:33.360
[Amit Varma]: of production and the means of distribution, which they did not earlier, the means of production

02:14:33.360 --> 02:14:39.200
[Amit Varma]: did come a while ago, but and the means of distribution, which is why I find some tremendous

02:14:39.200 --> 02:14:44.600
[Amit Varma]: cutting edge art on TikTok if people look for it, which is far removed from the art,

02:14:44.600 --> 02:14:50.360
[Amit Varma]: for example, produced by Bollywood elites and so on.

02:14:50.360 --> 02:14:52.320
[Guest]: So do you think there is something to this?

02:14:52.320 --> 02:14:58.600
[Guest]: So I mean, I think my criticism of the market is to presume that the market by itself is

02:14:58.600 --> 02:14:59.960
[Guest]: a solution.

02:14:59.960 --> 02:15:04.880
[Guest]: That's my problem, because there is this belief that the capitalist market kind of levels

02:15:04.880 --> 02:15:05.880
[Guest]: everything.

02:15:05.880 --> 02:15:10.680
[Guest]: And I think my criticism comes from that belief system that somehow that the capitalist market

02:15:10.680 --> 02:15:15.520
[Guest]: structure is going to like solve all these issues because everybody has access, which

02:15:15.520 --> 02:15:16.520
[Guest]: is just bull.

02:15:16.520 --> 02:15:20.320
[Guest]: You know, like you said, it only functions how society functions.

02:15:20.320 --> 02:15:21.320
[Guest]: That's my criticism.

02:15:21.320 --> 02:15:26.320
[Guest]: My criticism being that the market is only going to reflect what society is.

02:15:26.320 --> 02:15:27.800
[Guest]: It's not going to do anything.

02:15:27.800 --> 02:15:33.240
[Guest]: So unless you ask, allow society to ask those questions, the market will not transform.

02:15:33.240 --> 02:15:34.240
[Amit Varma]: That's my point.

02:15:34.240 --> 02:15:35.240
[Amit Varma]: So I agree with you.

02:15:35.240 --> 02:15:37.360
[Amit Varma]: But I'll say that's a criticism of society, not markets.

02:15:37.360 --> 02:15:41.640
[Guest]: No, but the market is just a part of society, I mean, you can't separate it from society

02:15:41.640 --> 02:15:42.640
[Guest]: at all.

02:15:42.640 --> 02:15:46.120
[Guest]: It behaves because market is constructed by people.

02:15:46.120 --> 02:15:50.160
[Guest]: So therefore, social construction itself is a market, right?

02:15:50.160 --> 02:15:53.640
[Amit Varma]: Because everything is being consumed, all everything is being produced and everything

02:15:53.640 --> 02:15:54.640
[Amit Varma]: is being used.

02:15:54.640 --> 02:15:56.720
[Amit Varma]: I'd say all voluntary interactions are part of the market.

02:15:56.720 --> 02:15:59.600
[Guest]: So you and I speaking, this is in a sense a market interaction.

02:15:59.600 --> 02:16:00.600
[Guest]: This is exactly.

02:16:00.600 --> 02:16:01.600
[Guest]: So that's my point.

02:16:01.600 --> 02:16:07.280
[Guest]: But to your point of the subversion that happens, that's also always true of most market structures.

02:16:07.280 --> 02:16:12.160
[Guest]: When something is pushed in a certain manner, you always find through history, you'll always

02:16:12.160 --> 02:16:17.880
[Guest]: find the counter voices, subversive voice, finding an opening that allows to ask that

02:16:17.880 --> 02:16:22.720
[Guest]: difficult question, which is why you had incredible subversive voice right through history, irrespective

02:16:22.720 --> 02:16:24.560
[Guest]: of which part of the world you're talking about.

02:16:24.560 --> 02:16:28.920
[Guest]: Now, TikTok, I'm not exposed as much to TikTok as you are, but I can see TikTok as being

02:16:28.920 --> 02:16:30.560
[Guest]: another example of that.

02:16:30.560 --> 02:16:34.840
[Guest]: Now, here we go to the idea of technology also, especially in our times.

02:16:34.840 --> 02:16:38.360
[Guest]: So my criticism of that is, again, comes from this notion that technology by itself will

02:16:38.360 --> 02:16:39.360
[Guest]: do something.

02:16:39.360 --> 02:16:45.560
[Guest]: I think TikTok is an example that you have a robust part of society that is willing to

02:16:45.560 --> 02:16:50.320
[Guest]: ask these difficult questions, which actually is a good sign for any society.

02:16:50.320 --> 02:16:56.880
[Guest]: And now technology enables that as a possibility to give it visibility and to be a counterpoint

02:16:56.880 --> 02:16:59.600
[Guest]: to what is being consumed by most of us.

02:16:59.600 --> 02:17:01.720
[Guest]: I see it like that kind of interaction.

02:17:01.720 --> 02:17:04.000
[Guest]: I think it's a very important interaction.

02:17:04.000 --> 02:17:06.960
[Guest]: And I think that that's where technology can help.

02:17:06.960 --> 02:17:12.800
[Guest]: But for example, people believe that YouTube is going to democratize art, rubbish.

02:17:12.800 --> 02:17:14.620
[Guest]: It's not going to democratize art.

02:17:14.620 --> 02:17:19.880
[Guest]: So you need a counter movement, which is going to allow to push that to happen.

02:17:19.880 --> 02:17:22.260
[Guest]: And that comes from these conversations that we are having.

02:17:22.260 --> 02:17:25.040
[Amit Varma]: So I'll, I'll, I'll just say that we are actually in complete agreement.

02:17:25.040 --> 02:17:27.320
[Unknown]: We are phrasing it slightly differently.

02:17:27.320 --> 02:17:29.880
[Amit Varma]: I do not at all mean that markets are a panacea.

02:17:29.880 --> 02:17:30.880
[Amit Varma]: Of course they're not.

02:17:30.880 --> 02:17:34.760
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I will be completely with you and say that markets will just reflect what society

02:17:34.760 --> 02:17:35.760
[Amit Varma]: is.

02:17:35.760 --> 02:17:40.200
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, in different interesting ways, especially through technology, like

02:17:40.200 --> 02:17:44.880
[Amit Varma]: I've actually said that in these difficult political times, I believe that technology

02:17:44.880 --> 02:17:49.680
[Amit Varma]: is a one thing that could surprise us by empowering individuals in ways that the state cannot.

02:17:49.680 --> 02:17:51.960
[Guest]: But Amit, you always had something that surprises you.

02:17:51.960 --> 02:17:52.960
[Guest]: But it's not a panacea.

02:17:52.960 --> 02:17:53.960
[Guest]: I'm not saying that.

02:17:53.960 --> 02:17:55.280
[Amit Varma]: You're addressing it as if...

02:17:55.280 --> 02:17:59.080
[Guest]: Yeah, I'm just saying that, you know, now it's technology, right?

02:17:59.080 --> 02:18:00.640
[Guest]: And technology is just a medium.

02:18:00.640 --> 02:18:02.120
[Guest]: Technology could mean so many things.

02:18:02.120 --> 02:18:08.640
[Guest]: So people who wrote, for example, texts in the early 19th century, women who wrote very

02:18:08.640 --> 02:18:11.160
[Amit Varma]: sensuous texts that were banned at that point in time.

02:18:11.160 --> 02:18:12.160
[Amit Varma]: Those weren't technology.

02:18:12.160 --> 02:18:13.160
[Unknown]: I mean, that's what I'm saying.

02:18:13.160 --> 02:18:14.160
[Unknown]: That's a different...

02:18:14.160 --> 02:18:19.600
[Guest]: So I'm saying those, the medium of technology is always being used, I think through history,

02:18:19.600 --> 02:18:22.280
[Guest]: to challenge these structures.

02:18:22.280 --> 02:18:29.480
[Guest]: The problem happens is when, if the dominant power, societal power, becomes so powerful

02:18:29.480 --> 02:18:34.880
[Guest]: that it's not going to... suppose we ban TikTok in this country, or we ban the internet.

02:18:34.880 --> 02:18:37.600
[Amit Varma]: Suppose I'm in China, for example, I can't even Google search.

02:18:37.600 --> 02:18:40.320
[Amit Varma]: I don't dispute the coercive power of the state.

02:18:40.320 --> 02:18:44.480
[Amit Varma]: But to use an example that you yourself have brought up in your writing, that if you look

02:18:44.480 --> 02:18:49.320
[Amit Varma]: at the USA, what has happened over the last century, that first jazz and then hip hop

02:18:49.320 --> 02:18:54.640
[Amit Varma]: have become dominant cultural forms, and classical music is basically dying, opera is dying in

02:18:54.640 --> 02:18:56.200
[Amit Varma]: Mainland England.

02:18:56.200 --> 02:19:01.760
[Amit Varma]: So you know, those elite forms are dying because of the reach of mass media.

02:19:01.760 --> 02:19:03.120
[Guest]: But I don't think they will die.

02:19:03.120 --> 02:19:06.480
[Amit Varma]: Well, I mean, and the reason for that is because of where they're placed.

02:19:06.480 --> 02:19:07.480
[Amit Varma]: Sure.

02:19:07.480 --> 02:19:08.480
[Guest]: And they shouldn't die.

02:19:08.480 --> 02:19:09.480
[Guest]: Every form should survive.

02:19:09.480 --> 02:19:10.480
[Guest]: That's a different thing.

02:19:10.480 --> 02:19:12.040
[Guest]: Whether they should or should not die is a different thing.

02:19:12.040 --> 02:19:15.640
[Guest]: But I think they will not die fundamentally, because they still occupy the same space.

02:19:15.640 --> 02:19:16.640
[Guest]: The numbers...

02:19:16.640 --> 02:19:21.360
[Amit Varma]: But the dominance of jazz and hip hop still speaks to a lot, and that is the success of

02:19:21.360 --> 02:19:22.360
[Amit Varma]: the market and technology.

02:19:22.360 --> 02:19:27.240
[Guest]: Without a doubt, it speaks to a lot, but it also speaks to the fact that even now aspirational

02:19:27.240 --> 02:19:30.520
[Guest]: culture remains with classical.

02:19:30.520 --> 02:19:31.800
[Guest]: It remains with that niche.

02:19:31.800 --> 02:19:35.760
[Guest]: The niche may be only 25,000, but it's still aspirational.

02:19:35.760 --> 02:19:42.840
[Guest]: And the question is, for me is, while something like hip hop dominates imagination, mass imagination,

02:19:42.840 --> 02:19:48.920
[Guest]: how can hip hop also dominate, or shall we say challenged very, very frontally, the notions

02:19:48.920 --> 02:19:54.320
[Guest]: of the niche, because the niche still control these kinds of systems of what is accepted.

02:19:54.320 --> 02:20:00.720
[Amit Varma]: I, you know, I totally agree with you in terms of the sort of cultural domination of certain

02:20:00.720 --> 02:20:02.120
[Amit Varma]: elites and all that.

02:20:02.120 --> 02:20:06.120
[Amit Varma]: But I think if there is going to be a fight back from counterculture, as it has been in

02:20:06.120 --> 02:20:08.600
[Amit Varma]: the past, then it will happen through markets and technology.

02:20:08.600 --> 02:20:11.840
[Amit Varma]: But I think we're broadly in agreement, just saying in different ways.

02:20:11.840 --> 02:20:16.720
[Amit Varma]: The other question that I want to move on, which we discussed during lunch, at which

02:20:16.720 --> 02:20:17.800
[Amit Varma]: point we were in agreement.

02:20:17.800 --> 02:20:24.200
[Amit Varma]: I don't know what now, no, but is essentially about, you know, moving away for a moment

02:20:24.200 --> 02:20:30.360
[Amit Varma]: from music and your sort of insights on music and the structures around music and moving

02:20:30.360 --> 02:20:36.160
[Amit Varma]: on to what's happening around us in this country and the crisis of liberalism, so to say, is

02:20:36.160 --> 02:20:41.920
[Amit Varma]: that one of the debates between Ambedkar and Gandhi on caste, and I'm mostly on the side

02:20:41.920 --> 02:20:44.920
[Amit Varma]: of Ambedkar, but I think Gandhi had one valid point.

02:20:44.920 --> 02:20:50.520
[Amit Varma]: And Ambedkar's point was that we have to reform society from the top down, sort of echoing

02:20:50.520 --> 02:20:55.400
[Amit Varma]: what Nehru also believed, while Gandhi and others believe that no, the change can only

02:20:55.400 --> 02:20:56.560
[Amit Varma]: happen in the culture.

02:20:56.560 --> 02:21:00.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, despite my other agreements with Ambedkar and my other disagreements with Gandhi, I

02:21:00.920 --> 02:21:05.120
[Amit Varma]: think there is something to this in the sense that I think what has happened in India and

02:21:05.120 --> 02:21:11.440
[Amit Varma]: tell me what you think about it, is that we had a liberal elite found this country with

02:21:11.440 --> 02:21:16.920
[Amit Varma]: a relatively liberal constitution when society itself was illiberal.

02:21:16.920 --> 02:21:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Society has remained illiberal, politics has caught up.

02:21:20.000 --> 02:21:21.280
[Amit Varma]: And that is a great failure.

02:21:21.280 --> 02:21:22.680
[Guest]: Is that something you'd agree with?

02:21:22.680 --> 02:21:28.520
[Guest]: Well, more or less, yes, I mean, now in retrospect, this may be wrong to say now, but I don't

02:21:28.520 --> 02:21:36.280
[Guest]: know whether we as a society were ready for the idea of India that we were given with

02:21:36.280 --> 02:21:37.280
[Guest]: the constitution.

02:21:37.280 --> 02:21:44.360
[Guest]: I don't know, because like you said, it was, it was a notional idea based on some, it was

02:21:44.360 --> 02:21:45.360
[Guest]: a hope.

02:21:45.360 --> 02:21:50.080
[Guest]: Actually, our constitution is hope, is like, can we with its limitations, whatever it is,

02:21:50.080 --> 02:21:55.000
[Guest]: that can we be like this, but what it does not consider, and what it does not, the people

02:21:55.000 --> 02:22:00.680
[Guest]: do not consider is unless there is ground level actual work with the multiple culture

02:22:00.680 --> 02:22:06.520
[Guest]: structures that are there in society, which are the complete antithesis of what we hope

02:22:06.520 --> 02:22:08.400
[Guest]: to be, we are never going to get there.

02:22:08.400 --> 02:22:14.400
[Guest]: If anything, things will get worse, which is a big liberal failure, in my opinion, because

02:22:14.400 --> 02:22:20.960
[Guest]: you have this notion, limited notions, whatever they are, of equality, of, you know, of equity,

02:22:20.960 --> 02:22:22.040
[Guest]: all these notions.

02:22:22.040 --> 02:22:29.360
[Guest]: But how is it going to really happen in society unless children, schools, culture systems,

02:22:29.360 --> 02:22:32.840
[Guest]: art forms are actually engaging in that manner?

02:22:32.840 --> 02:22:36.720
[Guest]: I mean, even elite private schools, where did we ever speak about equality?

02:22:36.720 --> 02:22:40.160
[Guest]: Where did we ever speak about rights?

02:22:40.160 --> 02:22:43.780
[Guest]: You know, we don't have a notion of rights in this country, we don't have what it means.

02:22:43.780 --> 02:22:47.840
[Guest]: We believe it's favorism, we believe that we should be always grateful to somebody who

02:22:47.840 --> 02:22:49.920
[Guest]: has done what they should be doing.

02:22:49.920 --> 02:22:56.400
[Guest]: So there is a complete gap between this hope, and the fact is that we never actually worked

02:22:56.400 --> 02:22:57.400
[Guest]: for it.

02:22:57.400 --> 02:23:01.480
[Guest]: So as a society, we were not ready for any of this, because this was not part of our

02:23:01.480 --> 02:23:02.940
[Guest]: culture conversations.

02:23:02.940 --> 02:23:07.160
[Guest]: This is not part of the fact that this is the India that we're hoping for.

02:23:07.160 --> 02:23:10.280
[Guest]: There is a top down model.

02:23:10.280 --> 02:23:14.040
[Guest]: And people, this doesn't mean the people on top actually completely agree to this model,

02:23:14.040 --> 02:23:19.100
[Guest]: we should also remember that, that the elite who put this structure, many of them in themselves

02:23:19.100 --> 02:23:21.840
[Guest]: were like feudal lords.

02:23:21.840 --> 02:23:25.360
[Guest]: So they wanted this notion of India, but they were not like that.

02:23:25.360 --> 02:23:30.080
[Guest]: So there is this multiple contradictions in the at the level of the constructors at the

02:23:30.080 --> 02:23:35.960
[Guest]: level of social structures, and right through our independent history, we have never addressed

02:23:35.960 --> 02:23:36.960
[Guest]: it.

02:23:36.960 --> 02:23:38.840
[Guest]: I'll give you one example.

02:23:38.840 --> 02:23:42.200
[Guest]: Look at our education, private education system.

02:23:42.200 --> 02:23:45.160
[Guest]: I mean, we expect I, you know, my children go to private school.

02:23:45.160 --> 02:23:50.880
[Guest]: So I expect my daughter, who studied 12 years in a private school, with similar kind of

02:23:50.880 --> 02:23:57.600
[Guest]: people, with same kind of ideas, to suddenly come go to the new world in college, and understand

02:23:57.600 --> 02:23:58.600
[Guest]: what equality is.

02:23:58.600 --> 02:24:00.480
[Guest]: This is utter rubbish.

02:24:00.480 --> 02:24:04.400
[Guest]: You're creating an education system that is fundamentally discriminatory.

02:24:04.400 --> 02:24:07.120
[Guest]: We know who are the people going to public schools, we know who are the people going

02:24:07.120 --> 02:24:08.120
[Guest]: to private schools.

02:24:08.120 --> 02:24:11.520
[Guest]: Those who are aspiration want to move from public school to private school.

02:24:11.520 --> 02:24:15.300
[Guest]: So you have not addressed a fundamental idea of even education.

02:24:15.300 --> 02:24:21.280
[Guest]: So when you don't have a, don't build a culture, I mean, my daughter's not had shared meal

02:24:21.280 --> 02:24:23.800
[Guest]: with people of diversity.

02:24:23.800 --> 02:24:24.800
[Guest]: She is not.

02:24:24.800 --> 02:24:26.880
[Guest]: So she's never going to understand what that is.

02:24:26.880 --> 02:24:29.040
[Guest]: How is she ever going to understand equality?

02:24:29.040 --> 02:24:33.000
[Guest]: You know, so we don't have a culture of equality, we don't have a culture of fraternity, we

02:24:33.000 --> 02:24:35.380
[Guest]: have no culture of socialism.

02:24:35.380 --> 02:24:43.400
[Guest]: So the interesting point is that unless there is cultural transformation in the way we behave,

02:24:43.400 --> 02:24:49.280
[Guest]: in the way we see each other, this preamble of our constitution is never going to be a

02:24:49.280 --> 02:24:55.280
[Guest]: reality, which is why the constitution itself has so many, so many problematic parts.

02:24:55.280 --> 02:25:02.120
[Guest]: The preamble has this incredible set of lines, but there are multiple parts of the constitution

02:25:02.120 --> 02:25:05.360
[Guest]: that are exactly a counterpoint to that.

02:25:05.360 --> 02:25:10.000
[Guest]: How do we let that pass after 72 years, how do we have draconian laws?

02:25:10.000 --> 02:25:14.440
[Guest]: How do we don't see that even in the liberal world, we've done nothing.

02:25:14.440 --> 02:25:19.380
[Guest]: So let's not talk about X government or Y government, the socialist spirited government

02:25:19.380 --> 02:25:21.280
[Guest]: of this country did not do anything.

02:25:21.280 --> 02:25:22.280
[Guest]: Why?

02:25:22.280 --> 02:25:27.080
[Guest]: Because somewhere we are still feudalistic, somewhere we want that power.

02:25:27.080 --> 02:25:30.640
[Guest]: We want to make sure you have freedom of expression, but we don't want it fully.

02:25:30.640 --> 02:25:33.760
[Guest]: We want to draw that line and I want to decide where that line is.

02:25:33.760 --> 02:25:35.840
[Guest]: So that's the problem we're in.

02:25:35.840 --> 02:25:39.840
[Amit Varma]: So cultural transformation is essential for us if we want to move anywhere.

02:25:39.840 --> 02:25:43.760
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I recorded an episode with Madhav Khosla, author of the brilliant book, India's

02:25:43.760 --> 02:25:48.200
[Amit Varma]: Founding Moment, which will air in, I think, three weeks time after you listen to this,

02:25:48.200 --> 02:25:52.320
[Amit Varma]: which kind of talks about many of the decisions that I think our founders got wrong.

02:25:52.320 --> 02:25:57.040
[Amit Varma]: For example, all the reasonable restrictions to our rights, which I think make some of

02:25:57.040 --> 02:26:02.280
[Amit Varma]: those rights meaningless with the over centralization of the state, which they did for very interesting

02:26:02.280 --> 02:26:03.280
[Amit Varma]: reasons.

02:26:03.280 --> 02:26:08.200
[Amit Varma]: These weren't sort of, you know, automatic decisions, but you'll have to wait for that

02:26:08.200 --> 02:26:09.200
[Amit Varma]: episode.

02:26:09.200 --> 02:26:11.920
[Amit Varma]: I'm also, you know, reminded in this context of what Andrew Breitbart once said, where

02:26:11.920 --> 02:26:14.520
[Amit Varma]: he said, politics is downstream of culture.

02:26:14.520 --> 02:26:17.520
[Amit Varma]: You want politics to change, you change the culture first.

02:26:17.520 --> 02:26:19.560
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't go the other way around.

02:26:19.560 --> 02:26:23.880
[Amit Varma]: And this is something I'd done an episode with Akshay Mukul on the Gita Press.

02:26:23.880 --> 02:26:28.560
[Amit Varma]: And this is something that is so demonstrated by what the Hindutva folks got absolutely

02:26:28.560 --> 02:26:29.560
[Amit Varma]: right.

02:26:29.560 --> 02:26:33.480
[Amit Varma]: In terms of strategy, in terms of tactics, they completely nailed it.

02:26:33.480 --> 02:26:39.960
[Amit Varma]: Is it a sort of a fundamental problem of liberal elites like us, that we want a thousand flowers

02:26:39.960 --> 02:26:40.960
[Amit Varma]: to flourish.

02:26:40.960 --> 02:26:45.040
[Amit Varma]: So we can't, you know, put a program in place like the communist world or like the Hindutva

02:26:45.040 --> 02:26:46.040
[Amit Varma]: guys did.

02:26:46.040 --> 02:26:50.080
[Amit Varma]: There's no programmatic way of thinking because that's alien to us as it should be.

02:26:50.080 --> 02:26:51.800
[Amit Varma]: We just want to let diversity flourish.

02:26:51.800 --> 02:26:55.840
[Amit Varma]: But in the process, what happens is that we haven't been able to counter these dangerous

02:26:55.840 --> 02:26:56.840
[Guest]: narratives.

02:26:56.840 --> 02:26:57.840
[Guest]: Absolutely.

02:26:57.840 --> 02:26:59.680
[Guest]: I think they got it absolutely right.

02:26:59.680 --> 02:27:05.680
[Guest]: When they realized that if you want to influence people, we influence their behavior and behavior

02:27:05.680 --> 02:27:08.080
[Guest]: comes from cultural habituation.

02:27:08.080 --> 02:27:14.920
[Guest]: So as long as we keep playing that and they had this very, very divisive, you can easily

02:27:14.920 --> 02:27:19.080
[Guest]: manipulate these cultures and they manipulated it right through and now we are where we are.

02:27:19.080 --> 02:27:21.960
[Guest]: So they got it right when they realized that culture is where you need to change.

02:27:21.960 --> 02:27:26.580
[Guest]: Even the anger and the hate you see today is a result of years and decades and decades

02:27:26.580 --> 02:27:30.720
[Guest]: and decades of actually playing around with those notions of cultures.

02:27:30.720 --> 02:27:33.760
[Guest]: Now at the same time, we have this liberal world in India.

02:27:33.760 --> 02:27:38.960
[Guest]: I think one of the, I believe, I know what I said, what I'm going to say is kind of difficult

02:27:38.960 --> 02:27:48.040
[Guest]: and problematic is this inability of the liberal world to engage with faith and belief and

02:27:48.040 --> 02:27:55.560
[Guest]: ritual and also propagate a certain condescension towards any of that.

02:27:55.560 --> 02:27:58.000
[Guest]: Almost say that is not modern India.

02:27:58.000 --> 02:28:00.520
[Guest]: Almost say that that is not the way we should be thinking now.

02:28:00.520 --> 02:28:05.080
[Guest]: That is something of the old and that is, of course, it is intrinsically entrenched

02:28:05.080 --> 02:28:10.640
[Guest]: in different discriminative things, but there is also something very real about it.

02:28:10.640 --> 02:28:20.860
[Guest]: The fact that ritual, faith, belief is a fundamental human need and you need to respect it.

02:28:20.860 --> 02:28:22.480
[Guest]: You need to engage with it.

02:28:22.480 --> 02:28:27.600
[Guest]: Otherwise, what has happened and what the RSS has done very effectively is they've almost,

02:28:27.600 --> 02:28:31.200
[Guest]: I mean the BJP and RSS is almost saying independent India is a fraud.

02:28:31.200 --> 02:28:34.480
[Guest]: That whatever you had for 70 years is an evil.

02:28:34.480 --> 02:28:39.440
[Guest]: It's almost against everything that Indianness is that civilizational India knew everything.

02:28:39.440 --> 02:28:41.520
[Guest]: We were this people who loved each other.

02:28:41.520 --> 02:28:43.080
[Guest]: We had no discrimination.

02:28:43.080 --> 02:28:44.880
[Guest]: Women were goddesses.

02:28:44.880 --> 02:28:45.880
[Guest]: Everything was correct.

02:28:45.880 --> 02:28:50.560
[Guest]: And all that was destroyed by what the constitution of India without saying it, they're actually

02:28:50.560 --> 02:28:56.400
[Guest]: saying that the constitution and the democratic idea of India is actually a destruction of

02:28:56.400 --> 02:28:57.900
[Guest]: the idea of India.

02:28:57.900 --> 02:29:03.720
[Guest]: And the reason they're able to see that effectively is because of the inability of the liberal

02:29:03.720 --> 02:29:12.280
[Guest]: in the center, in the central left to engage with these very, very nuanced notions of faith.

02:29:12.280 --> 02:29:15.760
[Guest]: Respect it because people of faith feel disrespected.

02:29:15.760 --> 02:29:18.120
[Guest]: Let's be very honest here.

02:29:18.120 --> 02:29:19.440
[Guest]: They do feel disrespected.

02:29:19.440 --> 02:29:21.440
[Guest]: I know how problematic is what I'm saying.

02:29:21.440 --> 02:29:22.940
[Guest]: Of course, you have to challenge notions.

02:29:22.940 --> 02:29:25.840
[Guest]: You have to challenge patriarchy, you have to challenge caste, you have to challenge

02:29:25.840 --> 02:29:33.280
[Guest]: gender, but we have to find a way by which we can find partnership there because otherwise

02:29:33.280 --> 02:29:40.920
[Guest]: you're pushing more people towards being fanatical, you know, because now they're feeling threatened.

02:29:40.920 --> 02:29:47.280
[Guest]: And like I said, Amit, how much of explanation can you actually give me when I feel threatened?

02:29:47.280 --> 02:29:48.280
[Guest]: I believe it.

02:29:48.280 --> 02:29:49.880
[Guest]: Then you lash out viscerally.

02:29:49.880 --> 02:29:50.880
[Guest]: That's it.

02:29:50.880 --> 02:29:51.880
[Guest]: I just believe it.

02:29:51.880 --> 02:29:52.880
[Guest]: I believe I'm being cornered.

02:29:52.880 --> 02:29:53.880
[Guest]: I believe I'm threatened.

02:29:53.880 --> 02:29:54.880
[Guest]: You can say a lot.

02:29:54.880 --> 02:29:56.240
[Guest]: This makes, there's no logic in this.

02:29:56.240 --> 02:29:57.300
[Guest]: What are you talking about?

02:29:57.300 --> 02:29:59.120
[Guest]: But it makes no sense.

02:29:59.120 --> 02:30:00.120
[Amit Varma]: But this feeling is real.

02:30:00.120 --> 02:30:03.000
[Amit Varma]: There are two conflicting impulses here.

02:30:03.000 --> 02:30:09.000
[Amit Varma]: The first impulse is to say that, listen, we have to engage with the reality out there.

02:30:09.000 --> 02:30:14.640
[Amit Varma]: So at a tactical level, to be able to win, we need to reclaim nationalism, like you've

02:30:14.640 --> 02:30:19.360
[Amit Varma]: said and reclaim Hinduism, perhaps, as some have said, like I think that's Shashi Tharoor's

02:30:19.360 --> 02:30:20.360
[Amit Varma]: whole point.

02:30:20.360 --> 02:30:24.760
[Amit Varma]: But there's another way of looking at it, where somebody could say from conviction that

02:30:24.760 --> 02:30:30.080
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to reclaim nationalism because nationalism by definition is exclusionary,

02:30:30.080 --> 02:30:34.120
[Amit Varma]: but I don't want to reclaim Hinduism, even though it's better and different from Hindutva,

02:30:34.120 --> 02:30:38.920
[Amit Varma]: but I don't want to reclaim it because I want to move past it because I want to move past

02:30:38.920 --> 02:30:42.520
[Amit Varma]: caste and all these other things, which is part of the baggage of Hinduism.

02:30:42.520 --> 02:30:47.200
[Amit Varma]: So it's a battle between first principles and beliefs you might come from and the tactics

02:30:47.200 --> 02:30:49.200
[Amit Varma]: required to win the battle.

02:30:49.200 --> 02:30:52.820
[Amit Varma]: And there is and I'm thinking aloud, so I'm sorry if I'm rambling, but it seems to me

02:30:52.820 --> 02:30:59.440
[Amit Varma]: at some point that if you compromise on those core convictions for the sake of tactics,

02:30:59.440 --> 02:31:00.800
[Guest]: you change until you're no longer like that.

02:31:00.800 --> 02:31:02.880
[Guest]: I am not talking tactically.

02:31:02.880 --> 02:31:04.080
[Guest]: I am not talking tactically.

02:31:04.080 --> 02:31:06.600
[Guest]: I'm not talking about reclaiming Hinduism at all.

02:31:06.600 --> 02:31:07.600
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

02:31:07.600 --> 02:31:08.600
[Amit Varma]: You've spoken about reclaiming nationalism.

02:31:08.600 --> 02:31:09.600
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:31:09.600 --> 02:31:10.600
[Amit Varma]: Two different things.

02:31:10.600 --> 02:31:11.600
[Amit Varma]: I want to place them very different.

02:31:11.600 --> 02:31:12.600
[Amit Varma]: I am not talking about reclaiming Hinduism.

02:31:12.600 --> 02:31:13.600
[Amit Varma]: Sure.

02:31:13.600 --> 02:31:14.600
[Amit Varma]: I wasn't referring to you.

02:31:14.600 --> 02:31:17.800
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm just saying, no, I'm saying those who say, I think, in fact, I disagree with

02:31:17.800 --> 02:31:20.640
[Guest]: the notion of reclaiming Hinduism.

02:31:20.640 --> 02:31:27.520
[Guest]: I disagree with Mr. Tharoor's position in that, because I think it's about, see, every discourse

02:31:27.520 --> 02:31:29.520
[Guest]: has to move.

02:31:29.520 --> 02:31:34.240
[Guest]: I don't believe Hinduism is some ideal discourse in whatever form that we want to reclaim.

02:31:34.240 --> 02:31:36.480
[Guest]: It is not ideal.

02:31:36.480 --> 02:31:37.480
[Guest]: Hinduism is discriminative.

02:31:37.480 --> 02:31:39.560
[Guest]: Let's be very clear.

02:31:39.560 --> 02:31:41.200
[Guest]: Islam is discriminative.

02:31:41.200 --> 02:31:42.960
[Guest]: Christianity is discriminative.

02:31:42.960 --> 02:31:45.760
[Guest]: So when we say we want to reclaim something, you're almost saying there was a point of

02:31:45.760 --> 02:31:48.560
[Guest]: time when it was this perfect body.

02:31:48.560 --> 02:31:50.000
[Guest]: Nonsense.

02:31:50.000 --> 02:31:51.000
[Guest]: It was not.

02:31:51.000 --> 02:31:52.000
[Guest]: No structure can be.

02:31:52.000 --> 02:31:54.960
[Guest]: I am saying, can we find a way?

02:31:54.960 --> 02:31:56.320
[Guest]: I don't know how.

02:31:56.320 --> 02:31:57.320
[Guest]: Okay.

02:31:57.320 --> 02:32:03.000
[Guest]: Can we find a way by which we don't need to discard the feeling of hope and feeling of

02:32:03.000 --> 02:32:07.640
[Guest]: security that people get from certain things?

02:32:07.640 --> 02:32:08.640
[Guest]: It could be faith.

02:32:08.640 --> 02:32:09.640
[Guest]: It could be religious.

02:32:09.640 --> 02:32:13.400
[Guest]: It could be even ritual, which is not necessarily connected with faith.

02:32:13.400 --> 02:32:18.560
[Guest]: Could we find a way to have that as a part of our democratic narrative?

02:32:18.560 --> 02:32:21.360
[Guest]: Can that be part of the way we feel?

02:32:21.360 --> 02:32:23.300
[Guest]: That's my intriguing question here.

02:32:23.300 --> 02:32:24.300
[Guest]: How is it possible?

02:32:24.300 --> 02:32:27.920
[Guest]: Can we, do we need new rituals, for example?

02:32:27.920 --> 02:32:31.520
[Guest]: You know, because ritual is a very important part of how we live our life.

02:32:31.520 --> 02:32:34.480
[Guest]: Do we need new imagination of faith?

02:32:34.480 --> 02:32:39.840
[Guest]: We have to think in that manner, that there are certain things that people do and we do

02:32:39.840 --> 02:32:41.360
[Guest]: that is part of who we are.

02:32:41.360 --> 02:32:43.640
[Guest]: That may not essentially be discriminative.

02:32:43.640 --> 02:32:47.320
[Guest]: Everything in the past is not that, but everything in the past is also not positive.

02:32:47.320 --> 02:32:49.440
[Guest]: So it's not about reclaiming Hinduism.

02:32:49.440 --> 02:32:50.780
[Guest]: It's not about reclaiming anything.

02:32:50.780 --> 02:32:57.360
[Guest]: It's about finding a connection between cultural practices that are there across this country

02:32:57.360 --> 02:33:06.480
[Guest]: and giving those cultural practices a democratic, modern space.

02:33:06.480 --> 02:33:08.600
[Guest]: Because right now we don't want to give it space.

02:33:08.600 --> 02:33:11.720
[Guest]: We are saying, oh, leave all that.

02:33:11.720 --> 02:33:13.480
[Guest]: I don't think that works.

02:33:13.480 --> 02:33:14.960
[Amit Varma]: I don't think that works.

02:33:14.960 --> 02:33:18.800
[Amit Varma]: You know, coming from anyone else, I would just say those are just words, but coming

02:33:18.800 --> 02:33:22.160
[Amit Varma]: from you, that's very credible because in a sense, that's what you're trying to do with

02:33:22.160 --> 02:33:27.080
[Amit Varma]: Carnatic music and you know, not, you're not abandoning the form into something else.

02:33:27.080 --> 02:33:28.080
[Guest]: Exactly the point.

02:33:28.080 --> 02:33:29.080
[Guest]: Right.

02:33:29.080 --> 02:33:30.080
[Guest]: So how do I complicate that?

02:33:30.080 --> 02:33:34.080
[Guest]: You know, when you engage with different art forms, you let them communicate with each

02:33:34.080 --> 02:33:36.240
[Guest]: other, talk to each other in some fashion.

02:33:36.240 --> 02:33:38.360
[Guest]: It's a very uncomfortable conversation.

02:33:38.360 --> 02:33:42.600
[Guest]: It's a, it's sometimes just doesn't work, but there is something interesting that form,

02:33:42.600 --> 02:33:46.520
[Guest]: there is a reflection that happens, there is a seeing that happens.

02:33:46.520 --> 02:33:49.800
[Guest]: That's why I feel art plays an important role in what I'm saying now.

02:33:49.800 --> 02:33:50.800
[Guest]: Art forms.

02:33:50.800 --> 02:33:54.760
[Guest]: And I'm not talking about, you know, another thing, this country, you know, the political

02:33:54.760 --> 02:33:57.440
[Guest]: world has no sense of art.

02:33:57.440 --> 02:34:04.880
[Guest]: The left thing, art is protests and slogans and plays and songs that is about propaganda.

02:34:04.880 --> 02:34:09.540
[Guest]: These are we've been viewing, but no, I'm just talking about art forms that exist.

02:34:09.540 --> 02:34:12.280
[Guest]: You know, they practice across this country.

02:34:12.280 --> 02:34:13.840
[Guest]: How can they become part of this country?

02:34:13.840 --> 02:34:18.200
[Guest]: Because I think that's where they can find ways in what I'm saying that you can't find

02:34:18.200 --> 02:34:19.760
[Guest]: in any other place.

02:34:19.760 --> 02:34:26.080
[Guest]: You know, how can we create places where these, you know, shall we say collaborate, or maybe

02:34:26.080 --> 02:34:31.600
[Guest]: even contest each other, or maybe reach out to people that they don't reach out before.

02:34:31.600 --> 02:34:34.900
[Guest]: Sometimes when you experience an art form from a community that you have no connection

02:34:34.900 --> 02:34:38.440
[Guest]: with, just that experience changes the way you relate to the community.

02:34:38.440 --> 02:34:40.440
[Guest]: There's so much possible.

02:34:40.440 --> 02:34:49.520
[Guest]: But I feel discarding these practices as being archaic or as being being reductionist in

02:34:49.520 --> 02:34:55.080
[Guest]: only a sociological sense without taking the experience as being an important part is problematic.

02:34:55.080 --> 02:35:01.800
[Guest]: And I, I feel even more sure that in our present situation, it is essential that we do this.

02:35:01.800 --> 02:35:05.880
[Guest]: Otherwise, we're going to just lose more, because you're not talking about it.

02:35:05.880 --> 02:35:10.480
[Amit Varma]: So you know, you and I are almost the same age, and sometimes I have to remind myself

02:35:10.480 --> 02:35:14.640
[Amit Varma]: that listen, 60% of the country is born after 1991.

02:35:14.640 --> 02:35:17.680
[Amit Varma]: The average age is something like 27.

02:35:17.680 --> 02:35:20.640
[Amit Varma]: Everybody's like, everybody's like a kid to me.

02:35:20.640 --> 02:35:24.200
[Amit Varma]: And it's okay for me to feel this, you know, disconnected, because I'm a solitary animal

02:35:24.200 --> 02:35:25.200
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

02:35:25.200 --> 02:35:29.440
[Amit Varma]: But you actually travel around, you engage with young people, you perform everywhere,

02:35:29.440 --> 02:35:33.120
[Amit Varma]: you speak everywhere, you know, you've been to Shaheen Bagh recently, you're part of all

02:35:33.120 --> 02:35:37.200
[Amit Varma]: of this ferment that is happening, you've actively made yourself participant in all

02:35:37.200 --> 02:35:38.280
[Amit Varma]: of this.

02:35:38.280 --> 02:35:42.520
[Amit Varma]: What's your sense that is there hope to be had from this young generation coming up that

02:35:42.520 --> 02:35:47.040
[Amit Varma]: on the one hand, we have a terrible jobs crisis, a terrible employment crisis, a lot of it

02:35:47.040 --> 02:35:51.360
[Amit Varma]: feeds into these, you know, divisive narratives that are floating around.

02:35:51.360 --> 02:35:55.880
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, you interact at an artistic level with a tremendous number of

02:35:55.880 --> 02:35:56.880
[Amit Varma]: young people.

02:35:56.880 --> 02:35:57.880
[Amit Varma]: What's the sense you get?

02:35:57.880 --> 02:35:59.120
[Guest]: Or where this country is going?

02:35:59.120 --> 02:36:04.240
[Guest]: Well, I don't know whether there can be a generality in that, but I do think that younger

02:36:04.240 --> 02:36:07.240
[Guest]: people have definitely surprised me.

02:36:07.240 --> 02:36:11.400
[Guest]: I would have thought some time ago that there's no energy there.

02:36:11.400 --> 02:36:14.880
[Guest]: And I actually think it's our generation that has failed.

02:36:14.880 --> 02:36:20.200
[Guest]: It's you and I, who I think really did not engage robustly with ourselves and with what

02:36:20.200 --> 02:36:26.040
[Guest]: was around us, especially if comes from, you know, social capital and cultural capital.

02:36:26.040 --> 02:36:30.400
[Guest]: And in a way, I think the younger generation is reminding us of what we should have been

02:36:30.400 --> 02:36:32.080
[Guest]: doing.

02:36:32.080 --> 02:36:34.360
[Guest]: So it's not just about the protests.

02:36:34.360 --> 02:36:35.360
[Guest]: It's not just about the protests.

02:36:35.360 --> 02:36:39.520
[Guest]: It's also in the way, you know, this whole idea of culture we discussed, I found the

02:36:39.520 --> 02:36:43.000
[Guest]: most interesting conversations about that with young people.

02:36:43.000 --> 02:36:48.560
[Guest]: Because when I talk about this, when I talk about the need to find these ways we can bridge

02:36:48.560 --> 02:36:53.760
[Guest]: culture or old culture with the democratic idea of India, and I don't see it as necessarily

02:36:53.760 --> 02:36:59.640
[Guest]: being an impossibility, they almost feel like, yeah, we're unable to connect.

02:36:59.640 --> 02:37:03.920
[Guest]: Because however you are, wherever you are, I think there is this disconnection and they

02:37:03.920 --> 02:37:07.760
[Guest]: feel that, for example, we don't have a language to counter that discourse.

02:37:07.760 --> 02:37:13.040
[Guest]: We don't have a language to counter this, your anti-culture discourse, your anti-Indian

02:37:13.040 --> 02:37:14.040
[Guest]: discourse.

02:37:14.040 --> 02:37:15.440
[Guest]: We have a political point.

02:37:15.440 --> 02:37:20.800
[Guest]: We have an intellectual way, but we don't have an emotional way to counter that.

02:37:20.800 --> 02:37:24.280
[Guest]: And I think that's something I find the younger people willing to engage with.

02:37:24.280 --> 02:37:28.480
[Guest]: I've had a couple of very interesting conversations with younger groups about this, you know,

02:37:28.480 --> 02:37:30.040
[Guest]: and they have great ideas.

02:37:30.040 --> 02:37:36.720
[Guest]: I think one important thing that I think young people have, which we need is imagination.

02:37:36.720 --> 02:37:41.120
[Guest]: And that gives me the greatest hope, because I think if there's anything that is dead in

02:37:41.120 --> 02:37:45.440
[Guest]: political India today, it's imagination.

02:37:45.440 --> 02:37:51.920
[Guest]: Because all we have is rhetoric, reaction, followed by a cycle of rhetoric and reaction.

02:37:51.920 --> 02:37:55.960
[Guest]: There is no imagination, there is no creativity, because unless there is creativity, there

02:37:55.960 --> 02:37:56.960
[Guest]: can't be politics.

02:37:56.960 --> 02:37:57.960
[Guest]: You're redundant.

02:37:57.960 --> 02:37:59.800
[Guest]: You're a waste of time.

02:37:59.800 --> 02:38:03.480
[Guest]: And that's why people are getting bored, especially of opposition politics, because everybody

02:38:03.480 --> 02:38:05.520
[Guest]: is saying the same parroted thing again and again.

02:38:05.520 --> 02:38:07.760
[Guest]: You and I can say it, you know?

02:38:07.760 --> 02:38:08.760
[Guest]: So where is the imagination?

02:38:08.760 --> 02:38:13.400
[Guest]: And I think the younger people in the way they protest and the creative ways in which

02:38:13.400 --> 02:38:20.440
[Guest]: they're expressing themselves and saying things of great importance and profundity, in sometimes

02:38:20.440 --> 02:38:25.000
[Guest]: just two words, in just an image, is magnificent.

02:38:25.000 --> 02:38:26.880
[Guest]: But does that mean everything will change tomorrow?

02:38:26.880 --> 02:38:27.880
[Guest]: Probably not.

02:38:27.880 --> 02:38:28.880
[Amit Varma]: Maybe another generation.

02:38:28.880 --> 02:38:29.880
[Amit Varma]: I don't know.

02:38:29.880 --> 02:38:34.280
[Amit Varma]: Shame on you for saying that we were ending on such a nice note of hope and I was suddenly

02:38:34.280 --> 02:38:39.200
[Amit Varma]: for the first time in months feeling good about the world and you've done that.

02:38:39.200 --> 02:38:42.920
[Amit Varma]: I have like two more pages of questions, but we'll save it for another episode.

02:38:42.920 --> 02:38:44.800
[Amit Varma]: I've taken up more than two and a half hours of your time.

02:38:44.800 --> 02:38:45.800
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for being so generous.

02:38:45.800 --> 02:38:46.800
[Amit Varma]: Thank you, Amit.

